  3  * The global CCC namespace. 
  4  * 
  5  * @namespace
  6  */
  7 pvc = {};

  9 /**
 10  * The CCC options namespace.
 11  * <p>
 12  * All types of this namespace,
 13  * as well as of the namespaces below this one, 
 14  * are 
 15  * <b>documentation</b> types -
 16  * they do not exist, in code, 
 17  * and serve only to document the structure of the options objects 
 18  * that each chart type accepts in its constructor.
 19  * 
 20  * <p>
 21  * The following code shows how to 
 22  * create and configure a very simple CCC Bar chart:
 23  * 
 24  * <pre>// Options are placed in a plain JS object
 25  * var options = {
 26  *     title:  "A CCC Bar chart",
 27  *     legend: true,
 28  *     crosstabMode: false
 29  * };
 30  * 
 31  * var data = {
 32  *     metadata: [
 33  *         {colIndex: 0, colType: "String", colName: "Series"}, 
 34  *         {colIndex: 1, colType: "String", colName: "Category"}, 
 35  *         {colIndex: 2, colType: "String", colName: "Value"}
 36  *     ],
 37  *     resultset: [
 38  *         ["London", "2010-01-02", 1],
 39  *         ["London", "2010-01-03", 2],
 40  *         ["London", "2010-01-04", 3],
 41  *         ["London", "2010-01-05", 2],
 42  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-01", 3],
 43  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-02", 6],
 44  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-04", 1],
 45  *         ["Paris",  "2010-01-05", 7],
 46  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-01", 3],
 47  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-02", 2],
 48  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-03", 1],
 49  *         ["Lisbon", "2010-01-04", 5]
 50  *     ]
 51  * };
 52  * 
 53  * new pvc.BarChart(options)
 54  * .setData(data)
 55  * .render();
 56  * </pre>
 57  * Note that the options object is a plain JavaScript object,
 58  * and not a {@link pvc.options.charts.BarChart}
 59  * 
 60  * <p>
 61  * 
 62  * @namespace
 63  */
 64 pvc.options = {};
 65 
 66 /**
 67  * The namespace of CCC chart extension point classes. 
 68  * 
 69  * @namespace
 70  */
 71 pvc.options.ext = {};
 72 
 73 /**
 74  * The namespace of chart options classes. 
 75  * 
 76  * @namespace
 77  */
 78 pvc.options.charts = {};
 79 
 80 /**
 81  * The options documentation class of the basic chart facet.
 82  * 
 83  * <h2>Default Data Format</h2>
 84  * <p>
 85  * This section describes, in general, the data format accepted by CCC charts.
 86  * Most of what is here presented applies to all chart types.
 87  * <p>
 88  * The option {@link #crosstabMode} is by far the most important,
 89  * as it makes the top-level choice between the
 90  * two data formats: 
 91  * <i>relational</i> and 
 92  * <i>crosstab</i>.
 93  * <p>
 94  * Each of this formats has its own variants and,
 95  * also, both have some configuration options in common.
 96  * 
 97  * <h3>Relational Format</h3>
 98  * <p>
 99  * This format is a regular tabular format where each column of the data source
100  * corresponds to a different property of the described entity.
101  * <p>
102  * Each entity is described in a single row.
103  * Although not required,
104  * usually, one or more of the columns together identify the entity.
105  * 
106  * <h4>Example relational dataset</h4>
107  * 
108  * <pre>
109  * {
110  *     "metadata": [
111  *         {"colName": "city",  "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "City"},
112  *         {"colName": "date",  "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"},
113  *         {"colName": "quant", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Quantity"}
114  *     ],
115  *     "resultset": [
116  *         ["London", "2011-06-05", 72],
117  *         ["London", "2011-06-06", 50],
118  *         ["Paris",  "2011-06-05", 27],
119  *         ["Paris",  "2011-06-06",  5],
120  *         ["Lisbon", "2011-06-05", 30],
121  *         ["Lisbon", "2011-06-12", 60]
122  *     ]
123  * }
124  *             
125  * </pre>
126  * 
127  * <h3>Crosstab Format</h3>
128  * <p>
129  * The cross-tabular format goes away from the one-to-one correspondence
130  * between 
131  * <i>row</i> and 
132  * <i>entity</i>, and 
133  * <i>column</i> and 
134  * <i>property</i>.
135  * <p>
136  * Instead, it provides a grouped and aggregated view of the entities and their properties:
137  * 
138  * <ul>
139  * 
140  * <li>One row is spawned per distinct combination of the values of the "rows" properties</li>
141  * 
142  * <li>One column is spawned per distinct combination of the values of the "columns" properties</li>
143  * 
144  * <li>One cell contains a single somehow aggregated value, or 
145  * <tt>null</tt>, corresponding to its row and column's value</li>
146  * </ul>
147  * <p>
148  * The way in which a cross-tabular form is encoded in a single-tabular structure is, in kind words, 
149  * <i>sui generis</i>.
150  * The first 
151  * <i>N</i> columns are "rows" properties, and maintain the column-property correspondence.
152  * The following columns, however, each correspond to a distinct combination of the 
153  * <i>values</i> of the "columns" properties.
154  * This leads to the 
155  * <i>values</i> of the "columns" properties being placed in a column's 
156  * <tt>colName</tt> attribute (see example, below).
157  * 
158  * <h4>Downsides</h4>
159  * <p>
160  * This form of encoding is nice and concise,
161  * but achieves that at the cost of occupying the space intended for metadata
162  * and, thus, resulting in absent metadata for the underlying entities "columns" and "measures" properties.
163  * <p>
164  * Because of this reason, unfortunately,
165  * CCC could never really rely on the values of the "colName" and "colLabel" metadata attributes.
166  * We do try to use these, when they actually contain metadata,
167  * to default dimensions' labels (see {@link #dataIgnoreMetadataLabels}).
168  * 
169  * <h4>Example crosstab dataset with one property per group</h4>
170  * This is a crosstab dataset with one "rows", one "columns" and one "measures" property.
171  * 
172  * <pre>
173  * {
174  *     "metadata": [
175  *         {"colName": "date",   "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"  },
176  *         {"colName": "London", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London"},
177  *         {"colName": "Paris",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris" },
178  *         {"colName": "Lisbon", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon"}
179  *     ],
180  *     "resultset": [
181  *         ["2011-06-05", 72,     27,   30],
182  *         ["2011-06-06", 50,      5, null],
183  *         ["2011-06-12", null, null,   60]
184  *     ]
185  * }
186  *             
187  * </pre>
188  * 
189  * <h4>Example crosstab dataset with two properties per discrete group</h4>
190  * This is a crosstab dataset with two "rows" properties, two "columns" properties and one "measures" property.
191  * 
192  * <pre>
193  * {
194  *     "metadata": [
195  *         {"colName": "date",   "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"          },
196  *         {"colName": "family", "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Product Family"},
197  *         {"colName": "London~Ready",      "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~Ready"      },
198  *         {"colName": "London~InProgress", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~In Progress"},
199  *         {"colName": "Paris~Ready",       "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~Ready"       },
200  *         {"colName": "Paris~InProgress",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~In Progress" },
201  *         {"colName": "Lisbon~InProgress", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon~In Progress"}
202  *     ],
203  *     "resultset": [
204  *         ["2011-06-05", "Cars",     52,    0,   15,    2,   15],
205  *         ["2011-06-05", "Planes",   10,   10    10,    0,   15],
206  *         ["2011-06-06", "Cars",     10,   10,    1,    3, null],
207  *         ["2011-06-06", "Planes",   10,   20,    0,    1, null],
208  *         ["2011-06-12", "Cars",   null, null, null, null,   58],
209  *         ["2011-06-12", "Planes", null, null, null, null,    2]
210  *     ]
211  * }
212  *             
213  * </pre>
214  * 
215  * <h4>Example crosstab dataset with two properties in every group</h4>
216  * This is a crosstab dataset with two "rows" properties, two "columns" properties and two "measures" property.
217  * Yep. Sales are just ten times the quantity...
218  * <p>
219  * For this example to work,
220  * both options {@link #isMultiValued} and {@link #dataMeasuresInColumns} must be set to 
221  * <tt>true</tt>.
222  * 
223  * <pre>
224  * {
225  *     "metadata": [
226  *         {"colName": "date",   "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Date"          },
227  *         {"colName": "family", "colType": "String",  "colLabel": "Product Family"},
228  *         {"colName": "London~Ready~quant",      "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~Ready~Quantity"      },
229  *         {"colName": "London~Ready~sales",      "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~Ready~Sales"         },
230  *         {"colName": "London~InProgress~quant", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~In Progress~Quantity"},
231  *         {"colName": "London~InProgress~sales", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "London~In Progress~Sales"   },
232  *         {"colName": "Paris~Ready~quant",       "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~Ready~Quantity"       },
233  *         {"colName": "Paris~Ready~sales",       "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~Ready~Sales"          },
234  *         {"colName": "Paris~InProgress~quant",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~In Progress~Quantity" },
235  *         {"colName": "Paris~InProgress~sales",  "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Paris~In Progress~Sales"    },
236  *         {"colName": "Lisbon~InProgress~quant", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon~In Progress~Quantity"},
237  *         {"colName": "Lisbon~InProgress~sales", "colType": "Numeric", "colLabel": "Lisbon~In Progress~Sales"   }
238  *     ],
239  *     "resultset": [
240  *         ["2011-06-05", "Cars",     52,  520,    0,    0,  15,  150,    2,    20,  15,   150],
241  *         ["2011-06-05", "Planes",   10,  100,   10   100,  10,  100,    0,     0,  15,   150],
242  *         ["2011-06-06", "Cars",     10,  100,   10,  100,   1,   10,    3,    30, null, null],
243  *         ["2011-06-06", "Planes",   10,  100,   20,  200,   0,    0,    1,    10, null, null],
244  *         ["2011-06-12", "Cars",   null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null,   58,  580],
245  *         ["2011-06-12", "Planes", null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null,    2,  200]
246  *     ]
247  * }
248  *             
249  * </pre>
250  * 
251  * <h3>Physical Column Groups</h3>
252  * Traditionally, cross-tabular data contains "categories" in "rows" and "series" in "columns".
253  * Because of this, when in the context of the crosstab format,
254  * these terms end up being used interchangeably.
255  * <p>
256  * The separation of columns, at the data format layer,
257  * results in (what is referred to in this text as) 
258  * <i>physical column groups</i>.
259  * Three physical groups are identified: "series", "categories" and "measures".
260  * 
261  * <h4>Crosstab Format</h4>
262  * As explained, in the 
263  * <i>crosstab</i> format,
264  * the separation is physical, structural, unchangeable.
265  * <p>
266  * Remember, however,
267  * that the the "categories" 
268  * <i>physical group</i> is defined above as
269  * "the first 
270  * <i>N</i> columns are rows properties".
271  * By default, 
272  * <i>N</i> is determined as the number of initial, consecutive columns with a "string" type.
273  * If that is not the case, option {@link #dataCategoriesCount} allows stating otherwise.
274  * 
275  * <h4>Relational Format</h4>
276  * In the 
277  * <i>relational</i> format, however,
278  * the separation between "series" and "categories" is not physical, but, simply, convenient.
279  * As you'll see below, the separation helps in automatically loading data into common CCC's dimensions.
280  * <p>
281  * By default,
282  * when a data source contains a single discrete column,
283  * it is a considered a column of the "categories" 
284  * <i>physical group</i>.
285  * Otherwise, if it contains more discrete columns,
286  * the first is considered of the "series" 
287  * <i>physical group</i>,
288  * and all the remaining of the "categories" 
289  * <i>physical group</i>.
290  * This division is arbitrary.
291  * If you want more control, the option {@link #dataCategoriesCount}
292  * allows limiting the number of columns globbed by the "categories" 
293  * <i>physical group</i>.
294  * 
295  * <h4>Series in Rows, please</h4>
296  * It is common enough to want to swap the columns of the "series" and "categories" 
297  * <i>physical groups</i>.
298  * The option {@link #seriesInRows} exists for just that.
299  * 
300  * <h3>Logical Table</h3>
301  * The 
302  * <i>logical table</i>, or, in some contexts, the 
303  * <i>logical row</i>,
304  * is a reorganization of the source data
305  * into a logical format in which columns
306  * are properties of the underlying described entity
307  * and each entity is described in a single row.
308  * This is true, independently of the data source format being 
309  * <i>crosstab</i> or 
310  * <i>relational</i>.
311  * <p>
312  * In the 
313  * <i>relational</i> format, this is already the case.
314  * In the 
315  * <i>crosstab</i> format, however, a logical row contains information
316  * from one of the source rows and one of the source "columns" columns.
317  * <p>
318  * Apart from this restructuring,
319  * the columns of a logical row are also organized according to their
320  * source 
321  * <i>physical group</i>:
322  * 
323  * <style>
324  * .logicalrow {
325  * border-spacing: 0;
326  * margin: 1em 0;
327  * }
328  * .logicalrow td {
329  * border:  solid 1px;
330  * padding: 5px;
331  * }
332  * </style>
333  * 
334  * <table class='logicalrow' style='font-style: italic;'>
335  * 
336  * <tr>
337  * 
338  * <td>series</td>
339  * 
340  * <td>categories</td>
341  * 
342  * <td>measures</td>
343  * </tr>
344  * </table>
345  * <p>
346  * Because of this reordering,
347  * in the 
348  * <i>relational</i> format,
349  * the logical row can differ from the source row,
350  * when, in the latter,
351  * the columns of type "string" are not all before the columns of type "number".
352  * 
353  * <h3>Default Dimension Mapping</h3>
354  * Many chart types,
355  * like the pie, bar and point family, heat grid and box plot,
356  * automatically define and load dimensions —
357  * CCC's data column concept —
358  * for each of the 
359  * <i>logical table</i>'s 
360  * <i>physical groups</i>,
361  * with names from the corresponding 
362  * <i>dimension groups</i>:
363  * "series", "category" and "value". For example,
364  * if there are two columns of the "series" 
365  * <i>physical group</i>,
366  * two of the "categories" 
367  * <i>physical group</i> and
368  * one of the "measures" 
369  * <i>physical group</i>,
370  * the logical row would have its columns mapped
371  * to dimensions in the following way:
372  * 
373  * <table class='logicalrow'>
374  * 
375  * <tr>
376  * 
377  * <td>series</td>
378  * 
379  * <td>series2</td>
380  * 
381  * <td>category</td>
382  * 
383  * <td>category2</td>
384  * 
385  * <td>value</td>
386  * </tr>
387  * </table>
388  * <p>
389  * Other chart types,
390  * like the metric-point, bullet, sunburst, treemap charts,
391  * only rely on the discrete/continuous separation of the 
392  * <i>logical table</i> columns
393  * and automatically generate dimensions, from available columns, in other custom ways.
394  * See each chart type's options documentation page for information on its data format.
395  * 
396  * <h3>Explicit Dimension Mapping</h3>
397  * Whenever the default dimension mapping does not satisfy your needs,
398  * the {@link #readers} option allows mapping each position of the
399  * 
400  * <i>logical row</i> explicitly and independently.
401  * <p>
402  * For example, one could obtain the mapping:
403  * 
404  * <table class='logicalrow'>
405  * 
406  * <tr>
407  * 
408  * <td>category</td>
409  * 
410  * <td>series</td>
411  * 
412  * <td>series2</td>
413  * 
414  * <td>value</td>
415  * 
416  * <td>category2</td>
417  * </tr>
418  * </table>
419  * by specifying the following 
420  * <i>readers</i> value:
421  * 
422  * <pre>
423  * {
424  *     readers: ["category", "series", "series2", "value", "category2"]
425  * }
426  * 
427  * </pre>
428  * Another use of the 
429  * <i>readers</i> option is to be able to
430  * specify business names for the names of dimensions.
431  * For example, for the last crosstab format example,
432  * "crosstab dataset with two properties in every group",
433  * one would achieve the same effect, but using business dimension names,
434  * with the mapping:
435  * 
436  * <table class='logicalrow'>
437  * 
438  * <tr>
439  * 
440  * <td>city</td>
441  * 
442  * <td>orderState</td>
443  * 
444  * <td>date</td>
445  * 
446  * <td>family</td>
447  * 
448  * <td>quantity</td>
449  * 
450  * <td>sales</td>
451  * </tr>
452  * </table>
453  * by specifying the following 
454  * <i>readers</i> and probable 
455  * <i>visual roles</i> values:
456  * 
457  * <pre>
458  * {
459  *     readers: ["city", "orderState", "date", "family", "quantity", "sales"],
460  *     visualRoles: {
461  *         series:   "city, orderState",
462  *         category: "date, family",
463  *         value:    "quantity"
464  *     }
465  * }
466  * 
467  * </pre>
468  * 
469  * @class
470  * @abstract
471  */
472 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart = function(){};
473         
474         
475         
476         
477 /**
478  * A callback function that is called
479  * when the user clicks on a visual element.
480  * 
481  * @returns {undefined}
482  * @method
483  * @this pvc.visual.Context
484  * @param {pvc.visual.Scene} scene
485  * The scene associated with the visual item.
486  * 
487  * @category Chart > Actions
488  */
489 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.clickAction = function(){};
490 /**
491  * A callback function that is called
492  * before the chart is rendered,
493  * but after if has been pre-rendered.
494  * <p>
495  * You can use this action to:
496  * 
497  * <ul>
498  * 
499  * <li>use the 
500  * <i>mark events</i> API on time-series categorical charts</li>
501  * 
502  * <li>extend in special ways the already created protovis marks.</li>
503  * </ul>
504  * 
505  * @returns {undefined}
506  * @method
507  * @this pvc.visual.Context
508  * @param {pvc.visual.Scene} scene
509  * The scene associated with the visual item.
510  * 
511  * @category Chart > Actions
512  */
513 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.renderCallback = function(){};
514 /**
515  * A callback function that is called after the chart has finished rendering, including any animations.
516  * 
517  * @returns {undefined}
518  * @method
519  * @this pvc.visual.Context
520  * @param {pvc.visual.Scene} scene
521  * The scene associated with the visual item.
522  * 
523  * @category Chart > Actions
524  */
525 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.renderedCallback = function(){};
526 /**
527  * An array of dimensions calculations.
528  * <p>
529  * Can be specified to calculate the values of certain dimensions.
530  * 
531  * @type list(pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation)
532  * @category Chart > Data
533  */
534 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.calculations = undefined;
535 /**
536  * A map whose keys are
537  * the dimension type group names and whose values are
538  * the default dimension type group options.
539  * <p>
540  * A dimension type group is
541  * a group of dimension types
542  * that have a common non-numeric prefix in its name.
543  * <p>
544  * This property does not define any dimension types, per si,
545  * but allows specifying default values
546  * for dimension types of a group,
547  * that apply in case they are effectively used.
548  * 
549  * @type map(string : pvc.options.DimensionType)
550  * @category Chart > Data
551  */
552 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.dimensionGroups = undefined;
553 /**
554  * A map whose keys are
555  * the dimension type names and whose values are
556  * the dimension type options.
557  * <p>
558  * You don't need to define dimensions
559  * unless you want to change their name or properties.
560  * Charts automatically define default dimensions
561  * to satisfy their visual roles' requirements.
562  * <p>
563  * Dimension options can be partial,
564  * so that it is possible to override only certain options.
565  * 
566  * @type map(string : pvc.options.DimensionType)
567  * @category Chart > Data
568  */
569 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.dimensions = undefined;
570 /**
571  * The chart's format provider.
572  * 
573  * @type pvc.options.format.FormatProvider
574  * @category Chart > Data
575  */
576 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.format = undefined;
577 /**
578  * The separator used to join the labels of the values of
579  * a multi-dimensional visual role.
580  * <p>
581  * For example, if a visual role,
582  * has the dimensions "Territory" and "ProductType",
583  * a compound value could be shown as "EMEA ~ Classic Cars".
584  * <p>
585  * See also {@link #dataSeparator}.
586  * 
587  * @type string
588  * @default ' ~ '
589  * @category Chart > Data
590  */
591 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.groupedLabelSep = undefined;
592 /**
593  * Indicates if datums
594  * whose value in every measure dimension is null
595  * are ignored.
596  * <p>
597  * A dimension is considered a measure dimension if
598  * there is at least one measure visual role currently bound to it.
599  * 
600  * @type boolean
601  * @default true
602  * @category Chart > Data
603  */
604 pvc.options.charts.BasicChart.prototype.ignoreNulls = undefined;
605 /**
606  * A function that formats the 
607  * <i>non-null</i> values of 
608  * <i>numeric</i> dimensions.
609  * <p>
610  * When this property is specified,
611  * it sets also the
612  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} format of the chart's format provider,
613  * {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#format}.
614  * Consequently, its value is inherited by the number dimension types'
615  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#format}.
616  * <p>
617  * Conversely, if the chart's format provider
618  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} format is specified,
619  * its value sets this property, {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#valueFormat}.
620  * <p>
621  * When both are specified, the one in the chart's format provider has precedence.
622  * <p>
623  * Note: in a previous CCC version this property applied only to
624  * dimensions named 
625  * <tt>value</tt>, 
626  * <tt>value2</tt>, etc.

654  * 
655  * <h4>Relational format</h4>

657  * "series" and "category" 
658  * <i>physical groups</i>, in a custom way.
659  * <p>
660  * By default, if only a single discrete column exists, it is a "category".
661  * Otherwise, the first column is a "series" column and all the remaining are "category" columns.

678  * The capability to use the data source's provided metadata labels
679  * is most useful in the relational format, i.e., when {@link #crosstabMode} is 
680  * <tt>false</tt>.

1291 /**
1292  * A function used to format 
1293  * <i>non-null</i> 
1294  * <i>numeric</i> values
1295  * as percentages.
1296  * <p>
1297  * When this property is specified,\
1298  * it sets also the
1299  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#percent} format of the chart's format provider,
1300  * {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#format}.
1301  * Consequently, its value is inherited by the number dimension types'
1302  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#format}.
1303  * <p>
1304  * Conversely, if the chart's format provider
1305  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#percent} format is specified,
1306  * its value sets this property, {@link pvc.options.charts.Chart#percentValueFormat}.
1307  * <p>
1308  * When both are specified, the one in the chart's format provider has precedence.
1309  * 
1310  * @returns {string!}
1311  * The number formatted as a non-empty string.

1633  * The data part value of the subset of data that the plot consumes.
1634  * <p>
1635  * This option can only be used in code,
1636  * from within {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#plots}.
1637  * <p>
1638  * By default, for internal plots,
1639  * like 
1640  * <i>main</i> and 
1641  * <i>plot2</i>,
1642  * data is partitioned into two data parts,
1643  * 
1644  * <tt>"0"</tt> and

1648  * 
1649  * <tt>plot2Series</tt>, or 
1650  * <tt>plot2SeriesIndexes</tt>, options

1653  * {@link pvc.options.charts.PointChart#plot2Series}).

1657  * <tt>"trend"</tt>.
1658  * <p>

1660  * <tt>"0"</tt>.
1661  * <p>

1668 /**
1669  * The name of the plot being defined or configured.
1670  * <p>
1671  * This option can only be used in code,
1672  * from within {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#plots}.
1673  * <p>
1674  * To configure an internal plot, its reserved name is specified:
1675  * 
1676  * <dl>
1677  * 
1678  * <dt>
1679  * <i>main</i></dt>
1680  * 
1681  * <dd>the main plot of a chart; for example, a bar chart has a main plot of type 
1682  * <tt>bar</tt></dd>
1683  * 
1684  * <dt>
1685  * <i>plot2</i></dt>
1686  * 
1687  * <dd>the special second plot;
1688  * this is the plot that, in applicable chart types,
1689  * is activated when the option 
1690  * <i>plot2</i> is 
1691  * <tt>true</tt>;
1692  * configuring the second plot this way implicitly activates it,
1693  * and the value of option 
1694  * <i>plot2</i> is ignored.
1695  * </dd>
1696  * 
1697  * <dt>
1698  * <i>trend</i></dt>
1699  * 
1700  * <dd>the special trend plot;
1701  * this is the plot that, in applicable chart types,
1702  * is activated when other plots specify one of the options 
1703  * <i>trend</i> or 
1704  * <i>trendType</i>.
1705  * </dd>
1706  * </dl>
1707  * <p>
1708  * In this case, if {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#type} is also specified,
1709  * it must match the plot type of the corresponding internal plot.
1710  * <p>
1711  * To define a new plot, specify a {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#type}
1712  * and, no name, or one that is not reserved.
1713  * <p>
1714  * The name of a plot cannot have dot (".") character in it.
1715  * 
1716  * @type string
1717  * @category General
1718  */

1969 /**
1970  * Fixates the height of each 
1971  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
1972  * <p>
1973  * A value of type 
1974  * <tt>number</tt>,
1975  * or of type 
1976  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
1977  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
1978  * <p>
1979  * A value of type 
1980  * <tt>string</tt>,
1981  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
1982  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
1983  * <p>
1984  * This property may cause the 
1985  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
1986  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
1987  * <p>
1988  * When this property is unspecified,
1989  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
1990  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
1991  * which may impose it a value.
1992  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
1993  * this property remains unspecified,
1994  * it is determined as follows.
1995  * <p>
1996  * If the layout will have a single column
1997  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
1998  * is 
1999  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
2000  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
2001  * <p>
2002  * If the layout will have a single row
2003  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
2004  * is 
2005  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
2006  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
2007  * <p>
2008  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
2009  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
2010  * <p>
2011  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
2012  * but is something around 
2013  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
2014  * 
2015  * @type number|string
2016  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2017  */
2018 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
2019 /**
2020  * The margins of a 
2021  * <i>small</i> chart.
2022  * <p>
2023  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
2024  * the different supported data types.
2025  * 
2026  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
2027  * @default '2%'
2028  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2029  */
2030 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;

2037  *

2039  * @default 0
2040  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout

2042 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
2043 /**
2044  * Fixates the width of each 
2045  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
2046  * <p>
2047  * A value of type 
2048  * <tt>number</tt>,
2049  * or of type 
2050  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
2051  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
2052  * <p>
2053  * A value of type 
2054  * <tt>string</tt>,
2055  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
2056  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
2057  * <p>
2058  * This property may cause the 
2059  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
2060  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
2061  * <p>
2062  * When this property is unspecified,
2063  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
2064  * used to determine it:
2065  * by dividing the initially available content width
2066  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
2067  * <i>actually</i> occur
2068  * (so that if there are less small charts than
2069  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
2070  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
2071  * <p>
2072  * When an infinite value is specified for
2073  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
2074  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
2075  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
2076  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
2077  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
2078  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
2079  * but is something around 
2080  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
2081  * The width is then calculated.
2082  * 
2083  * @type number|string
2084  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
2085  */
2086 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

2103 /**
2104  * The 
2105  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
2106  * allows turning a chart into a 
2107  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
2108  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
2109  * <p>
2110  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
2111  * as a small multiples chart.
2112  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
2113  * 
2114  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
2115  * 
2116  * <i>Bullet</i>,
2117  * 
2118  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
2119  * 
2120  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
2121  * <p>
2122  * The 
2123  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
2124  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
2125  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
2126  * <p>
2127  * The 
2128  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
2129  * every dimension whose name has the 
2130  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
2131  * <p>
2132  * One 
2133  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
2134  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
2135  * that is present in the source data.
2136  * Each small chart then receives as its data
2137  * the partition of the source data that shares its
2138  * unique combination of values.
2139  * <p>
2140  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
2141  * for more information on supported data types.
2142  * 
2143  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
2144  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
2145  */
2146 pvc.options.charts.PieChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

2637 /**
2638  * The behavior to apply when the text of a value label does not fit within the bounds of its associated slice.
2639  * <p>
2640  * This option applies only when {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesVisible} is true.
2641  * <p>
2642  * Moreover, it also applies only for certain configurations of value label placement,
2643  * relative to the associated slice. Presently, the supported placements are:
2644  * 
2645  * <ul>
2646  * 
2647  * <li>
2648  * <b>non-negative text margin</b>,
2649  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}.

2652  * <li>
2653  * <b>values anchor is outer</b> —
2654  * {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesAnchor}
2655  * is
2656  * {@link pvc.options.varia.WedgeAnchor#Outer}.
2657  * </li>
2658  * 
2659  * <li>
2660  * <b>text baseline is middle</b> —
2661  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textBaseline}
2662  * is
2663  * {@link pvc.options.varia.TextBaseline#Middle}.
2664  * </li>
2665  * 
2666  * <li>
2667  * <b>text is inside and aligned with the middle angle of the slice</b> —
2668  * if the label has a
2669  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAlign}
2670  * of
2671  * {@link pvc.options.varia.TextAlignment#Right},
2672  * then
2673  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
2674  * must be (modulo) equal to the middle angle of the slice.
2675  * <p>
2676  * Otherwise,
2677  * if the label has a
2678  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAlign}
2679  * of
2680  * {@link pvc.options.varia.TextAlignment#Left},
2681  * then
2682  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
2683  * must be (modulo) equal to the middle angle of the slice plus 
2684  * <tt>PI</tt>
2685  * (the opposite angle).
2686  * </li>
2687  * </ul>
2688  * <p>
2689  * When an unsupported placement occurs, the label is shown.
2690  * <p>
2691  * Note that for the purposes of hiding and trimming,
2692  * the value of {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}
2693  * is used for more that the distance between the anchor points of the label and the slice.
2694  * It is also included as a required margin at the opposite side of the
2695  * configured text alignment.
2696  * Also, half of the text margin is included on the bottom and top sides.
2697  * 
2698  * @type pvc.options.varia.ValuesOverflow
2699  * @default 'hide'
2700  * @category Style
2701  */
2702 pvc.options.plots.PiePlot.prototype.valuesOverflow = undefined;

2720 /**
2721  * The extension points of the pie plot type.
2722  * <p>

2724  * 
2725  * <ul>
2726  * 
2727  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
2728  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
2729  * without need to prefix the extension point with the

2731  * </li>

2734  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
2735  * plot id or name.
2736  * </li>

2740  * <i>main</i>,

2743  * at the chart options level, directly.
2744  * </li>
2745  * </ul>
2746  * <p>
2747  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
2748  * 
2749  * <ol>
2750  * 
2751  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
2752  * <tt>pie</tt>)</li>
2753  * 
2754  * <li>extension property (ex: 
2755  * <tt>slice</tt>)</li>
2756  * 
2757  * <li>the "_" character</li>
2758  * 
2759  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
2760  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
2761  * </ol>
2762  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
2763  * <tt>pieSlice_strokeStyle</tt>
2764  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
2765  * <p>
2766  * The extension points of the 
2767  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
2768  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
2769  * In the example, when the 
2770  * <tt>pie</tt> plot is the main plot,
2771  * the extension point can be written as 
2772  * <tt>slice_strokeStyle</tt>.

2936 /**
2937  * The options documentation class of the 
2938  * <b>Treemap</b> chart.
2939  * <p>
2940  * Treemap charts display hierarchical data using nested rectangles.
2941  * They excel in revealing the location of valuable areas buried in a deep hierarchy.
2942  * 
2943  * <p>
2944  * The root data node is represented by the root rectangle,
2945  * which occupies the whole plot area.
2946  * </p>
2947  * 
2948  * <p>
2949  * The area of a leaf node is proportional to
2950  * the percentage of the 
2951  * <i>size</i> dimension over its sibling nodes.
2952  * The area of a non-leaf node is the sum of the areas of its child nodes.
2953  * If no 
2954  * <i>size</i> dimension is specified,
2955  * then all sibling-leaf nodes will have identical areas.
2956  * </p>
2957  * 
2958  * <p>
2959  * Rectangles are usually colored so that siblings have the same color.
2960  * This way, it is easy to identify sibling nodes and compare their relative sizes.
2961  * In this way, the colors that are shown are the colors of leaf nodes' parents.
2962  * </p>
2963  * 
2964  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
2965  * <p>
2966  * For general information on the supported 
2967  * <b>data formats</b>
2968  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
2969  * <p>
2970  * The treemap chart employs a non-default 
2971  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
2972  * 
2973  * <ol>
2974  * 
2975  * <li>
2976  * All of the free 
2977  * <i>discrete</i> columns of the 
2978  * <i>logical table</i>
2979  * generate and load free dimensions of the "category" 
2980  * <i>dimension group</i>:
2981  * "category", "category2", "category4", ...
2982  * </li>
2983  * 
2984  * <li>The first free 
2985  * <i>continuous</i> column of the 
2986  * <i>logical table</i>
2987  * generates and loads the "size" dimension, if free.
2988  * </li>
2989  * </ol>
2990  * 
2991  * <style>
2992  * .dataformat {
2993  * border-spacing: 0;
2994  * margin: 1em 0;
2995  * }
2996  * .dataformat td {
2997  * border:  solid 1px;
2998  * padding: 3px;
2999  * width:   80px;
3000  * }
3001  * </style>
3002  * <p>
3003  * The following is a possible default layout and dimension assignment:
3004  * 
3005  * <table class='dataformat'>
3006  * 
3007  * <tr>
3008  * <td>
3009  * <b>Index</b></td>
3010  * <td>0</td>
3011  * <td>1</td>
3012  * <td>2</td>
3013  * <td>3</td></tr>
3014  * 
3015  * <tr>
3016  * <td>
3017  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
3018  * <td>category</td>
3019  * <td>category2</td>
3020  * <td>category4</td>
3021  * <td>size</td></tr>
3022  * 
3023  * <tr>
3024  * <td>
3025  * <b>DataType</b></td>
3026  * <td>string</td>
3027  * <td>string</td>
3028  * <td>string</td>
3029  * <td>number</td></tr>
3030  * </table>
3031  * <p>
3032  * Note that the dimension "category3" was not assigned to index 3, hypothetically because it was not free (was explicitly bound to some index, using a reader).
3033  * 
3034  * <h3>How To Bind The Color Visual Role</h3>
3035  * The Treemap's 
3036  * <tt>color</tt> visual role can only be bound to discrete dimensions.
3037  * <p>
3038  * By default, the 
3039  * <tt>color</tt> role is bound to the
3040  * dimensions of the 
3041  * <tt>category</tt> role — its default 
3042  * <i>source role</i>.
3043  * <p>
3044  * The 
3045  * <tt>color</tt> role can also be bound to other discrete dimension(s), explicitly.
3046  * 
3047  * <h4>Solution 1</h4>
3048  * One possibility is to 
3049  * <i>switch</i> one of the automatically fed "category" dimensions
3050  * to the 
3051  * <tt>color</tt> visual role.
3052  * For example:
3053  * 
3054  * <pre>
3055  * categoryRole: "category", // steal one here
3056  * colorRole:    "category2" // and assign it here
3057  * 
3058  * </pre>
3059  * 
3060  * <h4>Solution 2</h4>
3061  * Another possibility is to configure the {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers}
3062  * with the actual layout, using the default dimension names of
3063  * the desired visual roles.
3064  * For example:
3065  * 
3066  * <pre>
3067  * readers: "color, category, category2, size"
3068  * 
3069  * </pre>
3070  * 
3071  * <h4>Solution 3</h4>
3072  * Of course, you can (and probably should) use actual business names for the names of dimensions.
3073  * To that end, both the readers and the visual roles' mappings need to be specified:
3074  * 
3075  * <pre>
3076  * readers:      "orderType, productFamily, productType, sales"
3077  * categoryRole: "productFamily, productType",
3078  * colorRole:    "orderType",
3079  * sizeRole:     "sales"
3080  * 
3081  * </pre>
3082  * 
3083  * <h3></h3>
3084  * 
3085  * @class
3086  * @extends pvc.options.charts.Chart
3087  */
3088 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart = function(){};

3206 /**
3207  * Fixates the height of each 
3208  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
3209  * <p>
3210  * A value of type 
3211  * <tt>number</tt>,
3212  * or of type 
3213  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
3214  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
3215  * <p>
3216  * A value of type 
3217  * <tt>string</tt>,
3218  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
3219  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
3220  * <p>
3221  * This property may cause the 
3222  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
3223  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
3224  * <p>
3225  * When this property is unspecified,
3226  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
3227  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
3228  * which may impose it a value.
3229  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
3230  * this property remains unspecified,
3231  * it is determined as follows.

3233  * If the layout will have a single column
3234  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
3235  * is 
3236  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
3237  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
3238  * <p>
3239  * If the layout will have a single row
3240  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
3241  * is 
3242  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
3243  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
3244  * <p>
3245  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
3246  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
3247  * <p>
3248  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
3249  * but is something around 
3250  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
3251  *

3284  * A value of type

3288  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.

3290  * A value of type 
3291  * <tt>string</tt>,

3294  * <p>
3295  * This property may cause the 
3296  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
3297  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
3298  * <p>
3299  * When this property is unspecified,
3300  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
3301  * used to determine it:
3302  * by dividing the initially available content width
3303  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
3304  * <i>actually</i> occur
3305  * (so that if there are less small charts than
3306  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
3307  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
3308  * <p>
3309  * When an infinite value is specified for
3310  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
3311  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
3312  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
3313  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
3314  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
3315  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
3316  * but is something around 
3317  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
3318  * The width is then calculated.
3319  * 
3320  * @type number|string
3321  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
3322  */
3323 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;
3324 /**
3325  * The indexes of columns of the 
3326  * <i>logical table</i> that are to feed the
3327  * default
3328  * 
3329  * <tt>multiChart</tt>,
3330  * 
3331  * <tt>multiChart2</tt>, ...
3332  * dimensions.
3333  * <p>
3334  * See {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers} for related information.
3335  * 
3336  * @type number|string|list(number|string)
3337  * @category Chart > Data Source
3338  */
3339 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.multiChartIndexes = undefined;
3340 /**
3341  * The 
3342  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
3343  * allows turning a chart into a 
3344  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
3345  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
3346  * <p>
3347  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
3348  * as a small multiples chart.
3349  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
3350  * 
3351  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
3352  * 
3353  * <i>Bullet</i>,
3354  * 
3355  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
3356  * 
3357  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
3358  * <p>
3359  * The 
3360  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
3361  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
3362  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
3363  * <p>
3364  * The 
3365  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
3366  * every dimension whose name has the 
3367  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
3368  * <p>
3369  * One 
3370  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
3371  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
3372  * that is present in the source data.
3373  * Each small chart then receives as its data
3374  * the partition of the source data that shares its
3375  * unique combination of values.
3376  * <p>
3377  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
3378  * for more information on supported data types.
3379  * 
3380  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
3381  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
3382  */
3383 pvc.options.charts.TreemapChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

3901 /**
3902  * The options documentation class of the 
3903  * <b>Bullet</b> chart.
3904  * <p>
3905  * This chart type was only partially updated,
3906  * to support some of the new CCC v.2 features.
3907  * 
3908  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
3909  * For general information on the supported 
3910  * <b>data formats</b>
3911  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
3912  * <p>
3913  * Note that, unlike most chart types,
3914  * the bullet chart has a default
3915  * {@link #dataTypeCheckingMode}
3916  * of {@link pvc.options.varia.DataTypeCheckingMode#Extended}.
3917  * <p>
3918  * Also, the bullet chart employs a non-default 
3919  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
3920  * 
3921  * <ol>
3922  * 
3923  * <li>The first free 
3924  * <i>discrete</i> column of the 
3925  * <i>logical table</i>
3926  * generates and loads the "title" dimension, if free.
3927  * </li>
3928  * 
3929  * <li>The second free 
3930  * <i>discrete</i> column of the 
3931  * <i>logical table</i>
3932  * generates and loads the "subTitle" dimension, if free.
3933  * </li>
3934  * 
3935  * <li>Free 
3936  * <i>continuous</i> columns of the 
3937  * <i>logical table</i> generate and load,
3938  * in order, skipping the dimension when not-free,
3939  * the following numeric 
3940  * <i>dimensions</i>:
3941  * 
3942  * <ol>

4648  * <p>
4649  * The 
4650  * <tt>value</tt> domain
4651  * is split into several parts (or classes) at the given points.
4652  * <p>
4653  * Each dimension that is bound to the 
4654  * <tt>range</tt> role
4655  * splits the 
4656  * <tt>value</tt> domain at a certain point.
4657  * <p>
4658  * By default, each part is painted with a successively brighter gray color.
4659  * <p>
4660  * The 
4661  * <tt>range</tt> visual role automatically binds to
4662  * all numeric dimensions whose name has the 
4663  * <tt>range</tt> prefix.
4664  * <p>
4665  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
4666  * for more information on supported data types.
4667  * 
4668  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
4669  * @category Visual Roles
4670  */
4671 pvc.options.visualRoles.BulletPlotVisualRoles.prototype.range = undefined;
4672 /**
4673  * The 
4674  * <tt>subTitle</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
4675  * represents the sub-title of each bullet.
4676  * <p>
4677  * The 
4678  * <tt>subTitle</tt> visual role automatically binds to
4679  * all dimensions whose name has the 
4680  * <tt>subTitle</tt> prefix.
4681  * <p>
4682  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
4683  * for more information on supported data types.
4684  * 
4685  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
4686  * @category Visual Roles
4687  */
4688 pvc.options.visualRoles.BulletPlotVisualRoles.prototype.subTitle = undefined;

4693  * <p>

4696  * all dimensions whose name has the

4706 /**
4707  * The 
4708  * <tt>value</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
4709  * represents the main measure under analysis, for a given
4710  * title and sub-title categories,
4711  * and is visually encoded by the length of a bar visual element.
4712  * <p>
4713  * The values, one for each dimension bound to the 
4714  * <tt>value</tt> role,
4715  * are represented by overlapping bars,
4716  * each painted with a successively brighter blue color.
4717  * The length of each bar is proportional to the corresponding value.
4718  * Negative values are considered 
4719  * <tt>0</tt>.
4720  * <p>
4721  * The 
4722  * <tt>value</tt> visual role automatically binds to
4723  * all numeric dimensions whose name has the 
4724  * <tt>value</tt> prefix.
4725  * <p>
4726  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
4727  * for more information on supported data types.
4728  * 
4729  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
4730  * @category Visual Roles
4731  */
4732 pvc.options.visualRoles.BulletPlotVisualRoles.prototype.value = undefined;
4733 /**
4734  * The options documentation class of the 
4735  * <b>Sunburst</b> chart.
4736  * <p>
4737  * Sunburst charts display hierarchical data using series of rings.
4738  * They are great to quickly drill down trough a deep hierarchy, while still maintaining the notion
4739  * of its dimension.
4740  * 
4741  * <p>
4742  * Each ring represents the children of the ring it
4743  * encloses and the area of each slice corresponds to its 
4744  * <i>value</i>.
4745  * </p>
4746  * 
4747  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
4748  * For general information on the supported 
4749  * <b>data formats</b>
4750  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
4751  * <p>
4752  * The sunburst chart employs a non-default 
4753  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
4754  * 
4755  * <ol>
4756  * 
4757  * <li>
4758  * All of the free 
4759  * <i>discrete</i> columns of the 
4760  * <i>logical table</i>
4761  * generate and load free dimensions of the "category" 
4762  * <i>dimension group</i>:
4763  * "category", "category2", "category4", ...
4764  * </li>
4765  * 
4766  * <li>The first free 
4767  * <i>continuous</i> column of the 
4768  * <i>logical table</i>
4769  * generates and loads the "size" dimension, if free.
4770  * </li>
4771  * </ol>
4772  * 
4773  * <style>
4774  * .dataformat {
4775  * border-spacing: 0;
4776  * margin: 1em 0;
4777  * }
4778  * .dataformat td {
4779  * border:  solid 1px;
4780  * padding: 3px;
4781  * width:   80px;
4782  * }
4783  * </style>
4784  * <p>
4785  * The following is a possible default layout and dimension assignment:
4786  * 
4787  * <table class='dataformat'>
4788  * 
4789  * <tr>
4790  * <td>
4791  * <b>Index</b></td>
4792  * <td>0</td>
4793  * <td>1</td>
4794  * <td>2</td>
4795  * <td>3</td></tr>
4796  * 
4797  * <tr>
4798  * <td>
4799  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
4800  * <td>category</td>
4801  * <td>category2</td>
4802  * <td>category4</td>
4803  * <td>size</td></tr>
4804  * 
4805  * <tr>
4806  * <td>
4807  * <b>DataType</b></td>
4808  * <td>string</td>
4809  * <td>string</td>
4810  * <td>string</td>
4811  * <td>number</td></tr>
4812  * </table>
4813  * <p>
4814  * Note that the dimension "category3" was not assigned to index 3, hypothetically because it was not free (was explicitly bound to some index, using a reader).
4815  * 
4816  * <h3>How To Bind The Color Visual Role</h3>
4817  * The Sunburst's 
4818  * <tt>color</tt> visual role can only be bound to discrete dimensions.
4819  * <p>
4820  * By default, the 
4821  * <tt>color</tt> role is bound to the
4822  * dimensions of the 
4823  * <tt>category</tt> role — its default 
4824  * <i>source role</i>.
4825  * <p>
4826  * The 
4827  * <tt>color</tt> role can also be bound to other discrete dimension(s), explicitly.
4828  * 
4829  * <h4>Solution 1</h4>
4830  * One possibility is to 
4831  * <i>switch</i> one of the automatically fed "category" dimensions
4832  * to the 
4833  * <tt>color</tt> visual role.
4834  * For example:
4835  * 
4836  * <pre>
4837  * categoryRole: "category", // steal one here
4838  * colorRole:    "category2" // and assign it here
4839  * 
4840  * </pre>
4841  * 
4842  * <h4>Solution 2</h4>
4843  * Another possibility is to configure the {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers}
4844  * with the actual layout, using the default dimension names of
4845  * the desired visual roles.
4846  * For example:
4847  * 
4848  * <pre>
4849  * readers: "color, category, category2, size"
4850  * 
4851  * </pre>
4852  * 
4853  * <h4>Solution 3</h4>
4854  * Of course, you can (and probably should) use actual business names for the names of dimensions.
4855  * To that end, both the readers and the visual roles' mappings need to be specified:
4856  * 
4857  * <pre>
4858  * readers:      "orderType, productFamily, productType, sales"
4859  * categoryRole: "productFamily, productType",
4860  * colorRole:    "orderType",
4861  * sizeRole:     "sales"
4862  * 
4863  * </pre>
4864  * 
4865  * @class
4866  * @extends pvc.options.charts.Chart
4867  */
4868 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart = function(){};

4986 /**
4987  * Fixates the height of each 
4988  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
4989  * <p>
4990  * A value of type 
4991  * <tt>number</tt>,
4992  * or of type 
4993  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
4994  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
4995  * <p>
4996  * A value of type 
4997  * <tt>string</tt>,
4998  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
4999  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
5000  * <p>
5001  * This property may cause the 
5002  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
5003  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
5004  * <p>
5005  * When this property is unspecified,
5006  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
5007  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
5008  * which may impose it a value.
5009  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
5010  * this property remains unspecified,
5011  * it is determined as follows.
5012  * <p>
5013  * If the layout will have a single column
5014  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
5015  * is 
5016  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
5017  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
5018  * <p>
5019  * If the layout will have a single row
5020  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
5021  * is 
5022  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
5023  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
5024  * <p>
5025  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
5026  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
5027  * <p>
5028  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
5029  * but is something around 
5030  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
5031  * 
5032  * @type number|string
5033  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5034  */
5035 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
5036 /**
5037  * The margins of a 
5038  * <i>small</i> chart.
5039  * <p>
5040  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
5041  * the different supported data types.
5042  * 
5043  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
5044  * @default '2%'
5045  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5046  */
5047 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
5048 /**
5049  * The paddings of a 
5050  * <i>small</i> chart.
5051  * <p>
5052  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
5053  * the different supported data types.
5054  * 
5055  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
5056  * @default 0
5057  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5058  */
5059 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
5060 /**
5061  * Fixates the width of each 
5062  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
5063  * <p>
5064  * A value of type 
5065  * <tt>number</tt>,
5066  * or of type 
5067  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
5068  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
5069  * <p>
5070  * A value of type 
5071  * <tt>string</tt>,
5072  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
5073  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
5074  * <p>
5075  * This property may cause the 
5076  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
5077  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
5078  * <p>
5079  * When this property is unspecified,
5080  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
5081  * used to determine it:
5082  * by dividing the initially available content width
5083  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
5084  * <i>actually</i> occur
5085  * (so that if there are less small charts than
5086  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
5087  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
5088  * <p>
5089  * When an infinite value is specified for
5090  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
5091  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
5092  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
5093  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
5094  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
5095  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
5096  * but is something around 
5097  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
5098  * The width is then calculated.
5099  * 
5100  * @type number|string
5101  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
5102  */
5103 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

5120 /**
5121  * The 
5122  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
5123  * allows turning a chart into a 
5124  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
5125  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
5126  * <p>
5127  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
5128  * as a small multiples chart.
5129  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
5130  * 
5131  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
5132  * 
5133  * <i>Bullet</i>,
5134  * 
5135  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
5136  * 
5137  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
5138  * <p>
5139  * The 
5140  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
5141  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
5142  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
5143  * <p>
5144  * The 
5145  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
5146  * every dimension whose name has the 
5147  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
5148  * <p>
5149  * One 
5150  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
5151  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
5152  * that is present in the source data.
5153  * Each small chart then receives as its data
5154  * the partition of the source data that shares its
5155  * unique combination of values.
5156  * <p>
5157  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
5158  * for more information on supported data types.
5159  * 
5160  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
5161  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
5162  */
5163 pvc.options.charts.SunburstChart.prototype.multiChartRole = undefined;

5281 /**
5282  * The extension points of the sunburst chart type.
5283  * <p>
5284  * Chart extension points can also be specified directly at the chart options level.
5285  * <p>
5286  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
5287  * 
5288  * <ol>
5289  * 
5290  * <li>extension property (ex: 
5291  * <tt>smallBase</tt>)</li>
5292  * 
5293  * <li>the "_" character</li>
5294  * 
5295  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
5296  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
5297  * </ol>
5298  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
5299  * <tt>smallBase_strokeStyle</tt>
5300  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
5301  * 
5302  * @class

5346 /**
5347  * The 
5348  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
5349  * allows turning a chart into a 
5350  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
5351  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
5352  * <p>
5353  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
5354  * as a small multiples chart.
5355  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
5356  * 
5357  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
5358  * 
5359  * <i>Bullet</i>,
5360  * 
5361  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
5362  * 
5363  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
5364  * <p>
5365  * The 
5366  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
5367  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
5368  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
5369  * <p>
5370  * The 
5371  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
5372  * every dimension whose name has the 
5373  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
5374  * <p>
5375  * One 
5376  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
5377  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
5378  * that is present in the source data.
5379  * Each small chart then receives as its data
5380  * the partition of the source data that shares its
5381  * unique combination of values.
5382  * <p>
5383  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
5384  * for more information on supported data types.
5385  * 
5386  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
5387  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
5388  */
5389 pvc.options.visualRoles.SunburstChartVisualRoles.prototype.multiChart = undefined;

5483  * 
5484  * <ul>
5485  *

5502  * (modulo) equal to the middle angle of the slice.
5503  * </li>

5512  * configured text alignment.

5537 /**
5538  * The extension points of the sunburst plot type.
5539  * <p>
5540  * Plot extension points can be specified:
5541  * 
5542  * <ul>
5543  * 
5544  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
5545  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
5546  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
5547  * plot id or name.
5548  * </li>
5549  * 
5550  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
5551  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
5552  * plot id or name.
5553  * </li>
5554  * 
5555  * <li>
5556  * if it is an internal plot (
5557  * <i>main</i>, 
5558  * <i>plot2</i> or 
5559  * <i>trend</i>),
5560  * at the chart options level, directly.
5561  * </li>
5562  * </ul>
5563  * <p>
5564  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
5565  * 
5566  * <ol>
5567  * 
5568  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
5569  * <tt>sunburst</tt>)</li>
5570  * 
5571  * <li>extension property (ex: 
5572  * <tt>leaf</tt>)</li>
5573  * 
5574  * <li>the "_" character</li>
5575  * 
5576  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
5577  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
5578  * </ol>
5579  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
5580  * <tt>sunburstLeaf_strokeStyle</tt>
5581  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
5582  * <p>
5583  * The extension points of the 
5584  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
5585  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
5586  * In the example, when the 
5587  * <tt>sunburst</tt> plot is the main plot,
5588  * the extension point can be written as 
5589  * <tt>leaf_strokeStyle</tt>.
5590  * 
5591  * @class
5592  */

5935 /**
5936  * The 
5937  * <tt>series</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that represents a
5938  * 
5939  * <i>series</i> of connected data points.
5940  * <p>
5941  * Most cartesian charts represent graphically
5942  * the connectedness of data points of a given series in some way,
5943  * by connecting points with a line,
5944  * by giving them all the same color,
5945  * or, simply,
5946  * by the order in which they are drawn,
5947  * and when overlapped, some stay on top of others.
5948  * <p>
5949  * The 
5950  * <tt>series</tt> visual role automatically binds to
5951  * every dimension whose name has the 
5952  * <tt>series</tt> prefix.
5953  * <p>
5954  * The visual role itself is optional,
5955  * yet, when unbound,
5956  * a dimension with a "series" prefix
5957  * is automatically created for it,

5960  * in that dimension.
5961  * <p>

6032 /**
6033  * The 
6034  * <tt>category</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
6035  * represents a generic 
6036  * <i>logical grouping</i> of the data points.
6037  * <p>
6038  * Category data may be discrete or continuous.
6039  * The relevant characteristic is that
6040  * data with equal category values is grouped and
6041  * summarized in some way.
6042  * <p>
6043  * So,
6044  * if more that one data point exists for a given
6045  * series and category values combination,
6046  * nevertheless,
6047  * only one visual element is generated for the whole group.
6048  * <p>
6049  * Some chart types support
6050  * showing continuous category types, in a continuous scale.
6051  * Others,
6052  * turn continuous dimension types bound to the 
6053  * <tt>category</tt>
6054  * visual role into discrete dimension types,
6055  * and then show the continuous categories in a discrete scale.
6056  * <p>
6057  * The 
6058  * <tt>category</tt> visual role automatically binds to
6059  * every dimension whose name has the 
6060  * <tt>category</tt> prefix.
6061  * <p>
6062  * The visual role itself is optional,
6063  * yet, when unbound,
6064  * a dimension with a "category" prefix
6065  * is automatically created for it,
6066  * and all datums will have the value 
6067  * <tt>null</tt>
6068  * in that dimension.
6069  * <p>
6070  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
6071  * for more information on supported data types.
6072  * 
6073  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
6074  * @category Visual Roles
6075  */
6076 pvc.options.visualRoles.CategoricalPlotVisualRoles.prototype.category = undefined;

6208 /**
6209  * Fixates the height of each 
6210  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
6211  * <p>
6212  * A value of type 
6213  * <tt>number</tt>,
6214  * or of type 
6215  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
6216  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
6217  * <p>
6218  * A value of type 
6219  * <tt>string</tt>,
6220  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
6221  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
6222  * <p>
6223  * This property may cause the 
6224  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
6225  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
6226  * <p>
6227  * When this property is unspecified,
6228  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
6229  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
6230  * which may impose it a value.
6231  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
6232  * this property remains unspecified,
6233  * it is determined as follows.
6234  * <p>
6235  * If the layout will have a single column
6236  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
6237  * is 
6238  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
6239  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
6240  * <p>
6241  * If the layout will have a single row
6242  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
6243  * is 
6244  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
6245  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
6246  * <p>
6247  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
6248  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
6249  * <p>
6250  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
6251  * but is something around 
6252  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
6253  * 
6254  * @type number|string
6255  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6256  */
6257 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
6258 /**
6259  * The margins of a 
6260  * <i>small</i> chart.
6261  * <p>
6262  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
6263  * the different supported data types.
6264  * 
6265  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
6266  * @default '2%'
6267  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6268  */
6269 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
6270 /**
6271  * The paddings of a 
6272  * <i>small</i> chart.
6273  * <p>
6274  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
6275  * the different supported data types.
6276  * 
6277  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
6278  * @default 0
6279  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6280  */
6281 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
6282 /**
6283  * Fixates the width of each 
6284  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
6285  * <p>
6286  * A value of type 
6287  * <tt>number</tt>,
6288  * or of type 
6289  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
6290  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
6291  * <p>
6292  * A value of type 
6293  * <tt>string</tt>,
6294  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
6295  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
6296  * <p>
6297  * This property may cause the 
6298  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
6299  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
6300  * <p>
6301  * When this property is unspecified,
6302  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
6303  * used to determine it:
6304  * by dividing the initially available content width
6305  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
6306  * <i>actually</i> occur
6307  * (so that if there are less small charts than
6308  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
6309  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
6310  * <p>
6311  * When an infinite value is specified for
6312  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
6313  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
6314  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
6315  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
6316  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
6317  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
6318  * but is something around 
6319  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
6320  * The width is then calculated.
6321  * 
6322  * @type number|string
6323  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
6324  */
6325 pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;

6587 /**
6588  * The interpolation mode used to
6589  * fill-in null or missing values.
6590  * <p>
6591  * The interpolation is applied to
6592  * the measure roles of the plot that
6593  * are represented in the orthogonal cartesian axis.
6594  * <p>
6595  * With the exception of the box plot,
6596  * this role is the 
6597  * <tt>value</tt> role.
6598  * All of the box plot measure roles:
6599  *

6602  * <tt>upperQuartil</tt>, 
6603  * <tt>minimum</tt>, and

6625 /**
6626  * The options documentation class of the 
6627  * <b>Box plot</b> chart.
6628  * 
6629  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
6630  * For general information on the supported 
6631  * <b>data formats</b>
6632  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
6633  * <p>
6634  * The boxplot chart employs a non-default 
6635  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
6636  * 
6637  * <ol>
6638  * 
6639  * <li>All of the free columns of the "series" 
6640  * <i>physical group</i>
6641  * generate and load free dimensions of the "series" 
6642  * <i>dimension group</i>:
6643  * "series", "series2", ...
6644  * </li>
6645  * 
6646  * <li>All of the free columns of the "categories" 
6647  * <i>physical group</i>
6648  * generate and load free dimensions of the "category" 
6649  * <i>dimension group</i>:
6650  * "category", "category2", ...
6651  * </li>
6652  * 
6653  * <li>Free columns of the "measures" 
6654  * <i>physical group</i> generate and load,
6655  * in order, skipping the dimension when not-free,
6656  * the following numeric 
6657  * <i>dimensions</i>:
6658  * 
6659  * <ol>
6660  * 
6661  * <li>median</li>
6662  * 
6663  * <li>lowerQuartil</li>
6664  * 
6665  * <li>upperQuartil</li>
6666  * 
6667  * <li>minimum</li>
6668  * 
6669  * <li>maximum</li>
6670  * </ol>
6671  * </li>
6672  * </ol>
6673  * 
6674  * <style>
6675  * .dataformat {
6676  * border-spacing: 0;
6677  * margin: 1em 0;
6678  * }
6679  * .dataformat td {
6680  * border:  solid 1px;
6681  * padding: 3px;
6682  * width:   80px;
6683  * }
6684  * </style>
6685  * <p>
6686  * All the following are possible 
6687  * <i>default layouts</i> and dimension assignments:
6688  * 
6689  * <table class='dataformat'>
6690  * 
6691  * <tr>
6692  * <td>
6693  * <b>Index</b></td>
6694  * <td>0</td>
6695  * <td>1</td>
6696  * <td>2</td>
6697  * <td>3</td>
6698  * <td>4</td>
6699  * <td>5</td></tr>
6700  * 
6701  * <tr>
6702  * <td>
6703  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
6704  * <td>category</td>
6705  * <td>median</td>
6706  * <td>lowerQuartil</td>
6707  * <td>upperQuartil</td>
6708  * <td>minimum</td>
6709  * <td>maximum</td></tr>
6710  * 
6711  * <tr>
6712  * <td>
6713  * <b>DataType</b></td>
6714  * <td>string</td>
6715  * <td>number</td>
6716  * <td>number</td>
6717  * <td>number</td>
6718  * <td>number</td>
6719  * <td>number</td></tr>
6720  * </table>
6721  * 
6722  * <table class='dataformat'>
6723  * 
6724  * <tr>
6725  * <td>
6726  * <b>Index</b></td>
6727  * <td>0</td>
6728  * <td>1</td>
6729  * <td>2</td>
6730  * <td>3</td>
6731  * <td>4</td></tr>
6732  * 
6733  * <tr>
6734  * <td>
6735  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
6736  * <td>series</td>
6737  * <td>category</td>
6738  * <td>median</td>
6739  * <td>lowerQuartil</td>
6740  * <td>upperQuartil</td></tr>
6741  * 
6742  * <tr>
6743  * <td>
6744  * <b>DataType</b></td>
6745  * <td>string</td>
6746  * <td>string</td>
6747  * <td>number</td>
6748  * <td>number</td>
6749  * <td>number</td></tr>
6750  * </table>
6751  * 
6752  * @class
6753  * @extends pvc.options.charts.CategoricalNumericChart
6754  */

7109 /**
7110  * The extension points of the box plot type.
7111  * <p>
7112  * Plot extension points can be specified:
7113  * 
7114  * <ul>
7115  * 
7116  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
7117  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
7118  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7119  * plot id or name.
7120  * </li>
7121  * 
7122  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
7123  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7124  * plot id or name.
7125  * </li>
7126  * 
7127  * <li>
7128  * if it is an internal plot (
7129  * <i>main</i>, 
7130  * <i>plot2</i> or 
7131  * <i>trend</i>),
7132  * at the chart options level, directly.
7133  * </li>
7134  * </ul>
7135  * <p>
7136  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
7137  * 
7138  * <ol>
7139  * 
7140  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
7141  * <tt>box</tt>)</li>
7142  * 
7143  * <li>extension property (ex: 
7144  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
7145  * 
7146  * <li>the "_" character</li>
7147  * 
7148  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
7149  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
7150  * </ol>
7151  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
7152  * <tt>boxPanel_strokeStyle</tt>
7153  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
7154  * <p>
7155  * The extension points of the 
7156  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
7157  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
7158  * In the example, when the 
7159  * <tt>box</tt> plot is the main plot,
7160  * the extension point can be written as 
7161  * <tt>panel_strokeStyle</tt>.
7162  * 
7163  * @class
7164  */

7627 /**
7628  * The extension points of the 
7629  * <i>Heat grid</i> plot types.
7630  * <p>
7631  * Plot extension points can be specified:
7632  * 
7633  * <ul>
7634  * 
7635  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
7636  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
7637  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7638  * plot id or name.
7639  * </li>
7640  * 
7641  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
7642  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
7643  * plot id or name.
7644  * </li>
7645  * 
7646  * <li>
7647  * if it is an internal plot (
7648  * <i>main</i>, 
7649  * <i>plot2</i> or 
7650  * <i>trend</i>),
7651  * at the chart options level, directly.
7652  * </li>
7653  * </ul>
7654  * <p>
7655  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
7656  * 
7657  * <ol>
7658  * 
7659  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
7660  * <tt>heatGrid</tt>)</li>
7661  * 
7662  * <li>extension property (ex: 
7663  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
7664  * 
7665  * <li>the "_" character</li>
7666  * 
7667  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
7668  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
7669  * </ol>
7670  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
7671  * <tt>heatGridPanel_strokeStyle</tt>
7672  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
7673  * <p>
7674  * The extension points of the 
7675  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
7676  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
7677  * In the example, when the 
7678  * <tt>heatGrid</tt> plot is the main plot,
7679  * the extension point can be written as 
7680  * <tt>panel_strokeStyle</tt>.
7681  * 
7682  * @class
7683  */
