8013 /**
8014  * Indicates if legibility of value labels should be optimized.
8015  * <p>
8016  * The current algorithm varies the text color so that it has enough contrast
8017  * for the fill color of the associated bar.
8018  * <p>
8019  * It is applied only when a value label is considered to be 
8020  * <i>inside</i> its
8021  * associated bar. Presently, it is considered to be inside, if the center point
8022  * of the label is within the bounds of the bar.
8023  * 
8024  * @type boolean
8025  * @default false
8026  * @category Style
8027  */
8028 pvc.options.plots.BarPlotCommon.prototype.valuesOptimizeLegibility = undefined;
8029 /**
8030  * The behavior to apply when the text of a value label does not fit within the bounds of its associated bar.
8031  * <p>
8032  * This option applies only when {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesVisible} is true.
8033  * <p>
8034  * Moreover, it also applies only for certain configurations of value label placement,
8035  * relative to the associated bar. Presently, the supported placements are:
8036  * 
8037  * <ul>
8038  * 
8039  * <li>
8040  * <b>non-negative text margin</b>,
8041  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}.
8042  * </li>
8043  * 
8044  * <li>
8045  * <b>horizontal text</b> — on horizontal or vertical bars;
8046  * on vertical bars, text is allowed to overflow, without trimming.
8047  * Text is horizontal when
8048  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
8049  * is such that 
8050  * <tt>sin(textAngle) = 0</tt> (example: 
8051  * <tt>0</tt>).
8052  * </li>
8053  * 
8054  * <li>
8055  * <b>vertical text on vertical bars</b> —
8056  * text is vertical when
8057  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle}
8058  * is such that 
8059  * <tt>cos(textAngle) = 0</tt> (example: 
8060  * <tt>Math.PI/2</tt>, 
8061  * <tt>-Math.PI/2</tt>, 
8062  * <tt>3*Math.PI/2</tt>, ...).
8063  * </li>
8064  * 
8065  * <li>
8066  * <b>text that is intensionally inside the bar</b> —
8067  * this would be too painful to enumerate;
8068  * generally, it depends on the values of
8069  * {@link pvc.options.plots.Plot#valuesAnchor},
8070  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAngle},
8071  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textAlign} and
8072  * {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textBaseline}.
8073  * </li>
8074  * </ul>
8075  * <p>
8076  * When an unsupported placement occurs, the label is shown.
8077  * <p>
8078  * Note that for the purposes of hiding and trimming,
8079  * the value of {@link pvc.options.marks.LabelExtensionPoint#textMargin}
8080  * is used for more that the distance between the anchor points of the label and the bar.
8081  * <p>
8082  * It is also included as a required margin at the side opposite to the label's anchor.
8083  * For example, if a label is anchored with a 
8084  * <tt>bottom</tt> 
8085  * <i>textBaseline</i>,
8086  * the text margin must also be available on the top side of the label.
8087  * <p>
8088  * Also, the same margin is respected on the horizontal sides of the label (left and right),
8089  * whether or not they are anchor sides.
8090  * 
8091  * @type pvc.options.varia.ValuesOverflow
8092  * @default 'hide'
8093  * @category Style
8094  */
8095 pvc.options.plots.BarPlotCommon.prototype.valuesOverflow = undefined;

8102  * @category Visual Roles

8105 /**
8106  * The extension points of the 
8107  * <i>bar family</i> plot types.
8108  * <p>
8109  * Plot extension points can be specified:
8110  * 
8111  * <ul>
8112  * 
8113  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
8114  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
8115  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8116  * plot id or name.
8117  * </li>
8118  * 
8119  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
8120  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8121  * plot id or name.
8122  * </li>
8123  * 
8124  * <li>
8125  * if it is an internal plot (
8126  * <i>main</i>, 
8127  * <i>plot2</i> or 
8128  * <i>trend</i>),
8129  * at the chart options level, directly.
8130  * </li>
8131  * </ul>
8132  * <p>
8133  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
8134  * 
8135  * <ol>
8136  * 
8137  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
8138  * <tt>bar</tt>)</li>
8139  * 
8140  * <li>extension property (ex: 
8141  * <tt>panel</tt>)</li>
8142  * 
8143  * <li>the "_" character</li>
8144  * 
8145  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
8146  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
8147  * </ol>
8148  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
8149  * <tt>barPanel_strokeStyle</tt>
8150  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
8151  * <p>
8152  * The extension points of the 
8153  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
8154  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
8155  * In the example, when the 
8156  * <tt>bar</tt> plot is the main plot,
8157  * the extension point can be written as 
8158  * <tt>panel_strokeStyle</tt>.
8159  * 
8160  * @class
8161  */
8162 pvc.options.ext.BarPlotCommonExtensionPoints = function(){};

8731 /**
8732  * The extension points of the waterfall plot type.
8733  * <p>
8734  * Plot extension points can be specified:
8735  * 
8736  * <ul>
8737  * 
8738  * <li>at the plot level, in the 
8739  * <i>extensionPoints</i> property,
8740  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8741  * plot id or name.
8742  * </li>
8743  * 
8744  * <li>at the plot options level, directly,
8745  * without need to prefix the extension point with the
8746  * plot id or name.
8747  * </li>
8748  * 
8749  * <li>
8750  * if it is an internal plot (
8751  * <i>main</i>, 
8752  * <i>plot2</i> or 
8753  * <i>trend</i>),
8754  * at the chart options level, directly.
8755  * </li>
8756  * </ul>
8757  * <p>
8758  * To use an extension point you must find its full name, by joining:
8759  * 
8760  * <ol>
8761  * 
8762  * <li>plot property name (ex: 
8763  * <tt>water</tt>)</li>
8764  * 
8765  * <li>extension property (ex: 
8766  * <tt>line</tt>)</li>
8767  * 
8768  * <li>the "_" character</li>
8769  * 
8770  * <li>extension sub-property (ex: 
8771  * <tt>strokeStyle</tt>)</li>
8772  * </ol>
8773  * and obtaining, for the examples, the camel-cased name: 
8774  * <tt>waterLine_strokeStyle</tt>
8775  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase}).
8776  * <p>
8777  * The extension points of the 
8778  * <i>main plot</i> of a chart
8779  * may be used without the plot property name prefix.
8780  * In the example, when the 
8781  * <tt>water</tt> plot is the main plot,
8782  * the extension point can be written as 
8783  * <tt>line_strokeStyle</tt>.
8784  * 
8785  * @class
8786  * @extends pvc.options.ext.BarPlotCommonExtensionPoints
8787  */
8788 pvc.options.ext.WaterfallPlotExtensionPoints = function(){};

9686 /**
9687  * The common options documentation class for the 
9688  * <b>Metric Line/Dot family</b> charts.
9689  * 
9690  * <h3>Default Data Format</h3>
9691  * For general information on the supported 
9692  * <b>data formats</b>
9693  * see {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart}.
9694  * <p>
9695  * The metric-point chart family employs a non-default 
9696  * <i>logical row</i> to dimensions mapping:
9697  * 
9698  * <ol>
9699  * 
9700  * <li>
9701  * All of the free 
9702  * <i>discrete</i> columns of the 
9703  * <i>logical table</i>
9704  * generate and load free dimensions of the "series" 
9705  * <i>dimension group</i>:
9706  * "series", "series2", "series4", ...
9707  * </li>
9708  * 
9709  * <li>Free 
9710  * <i>continuous</i> columns of the 
9711  * <i>logical table</i> generate and load,
9712  * in order, skipping the dimension when not-free,
9713  * the following numeric 
9714  * <i>dimensions</i>:
9715  * 
9716  * <ol>
9717  * 
9718  * <li>x</li>
9719  * 
9720  * <li>y</li>
9721  * 
9722  * <li>color</li>
9723  * 
9724  * <li>size</li>
9725  * </ol>
9726  * </li>
9727  * </ol>
9728  * 
9729  * <style>
9730  * .dataformat {
9731  * border-spacing: 0;
9732  * margin: 1em 0;
9733  * }
9734  * .dataformat td {
9735  * border:  solid 1px;
9736  * padding: 3px;
9737  * width:   80px;
9738  * }
9739  * </style>
9740  * <p>
9741  * All the following are possible 
9742  * <i>default layouts</i> and dimension assignments:
9743  * 
9744  * <table class='dataformat'>
9745  * 
9746  * <tr>
9747  * <td>
9748  * <b>Index</b></td>
9749  * <td>0</td>
9750  * <td>1</td>
9751  * <td>2</td></tr>
9752  * 
9753  * <tr>
9754  * <td>
9755  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
9756  * <td>series</td>
9757  * <td>x</td>
9758  * <td>y</td></tr>
9759  * 
9760  * <tr>
9761  * <td>
9762  * <b>DataType</b></td>
9763  * <td>string</td>
9764  * <td>number</td>
9765  * <td>number</td></tr>
9766  * </table>
9767  * 
9768  * <table class='dataformat'>
9769  * 
9770  * <tr>
9771  * <td>
9772  * <b>Index</b></td>
9773  * <td>0</td>
9774  * <td>1</td>
9775  * <td>2</td>
9776  * <td>3</td>
9777  * <td>4</td></tr>
9778  * 
9779  * <tr>
9780  * <td>
9781  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
9782  * <td>series</td>
9783  * <td>series2</td>
9784  * <td>x</td>
9785  * <td>y</td>
9786  * <td>color</td></tr>
9787  * 
9788  * <tr>
9789  * <td>
9790  * <b>DataType</b></td>
9791  * <td>string</td>
9792  * <td>string</td>
9793  * <td>number</td>
9794  * <td>number</td>
9795  * <td>number</td></tr>
9796  * </table>
9797  * 
9798  * <table class='dataformat'>
9799  * 
9800  * <tr>
9801  * <td>
9802  * <b>Index</b></td>
9803  * <td>0</td>
9804  * <td>1</td>
9805  * <td>2</td>
9806  * <td>3</td>
9807  * <td>4</td></tr>
9808  * 
9809  * <tr>
9810  * <td>
9811  * <b>Dimension</b></td>
9812  * <td>series</td>
9813  * <td>x</td>
9814  * <td>y</td>
9815  * <td>color</td>
9816  * <td>size</td></tr>
9817  * 
9818  * <tr>
9819  * <td>
9820  * <b>DataType</b></td>
9821  * <td>string</td>
9822  * <td>number</td>
9823  * <td>number</td>
9824  * <td>number</td>
9825  * <td>number</td></tr>
9826  * </table>
9827  * 
9828  * <h3>How To Bind The Color Visual Role</h3>
9829  * The Metric Point's 
9830  * <tt>color</tt> visual role can be
9831  * bound to either continuous or discrete dimensions.
9832  * <p>
9833  * In the default table layout,
9834  * when enough free 
9835  * <i>continuous</i> columns exist,
9836  * a dimension named "color" is generated and loaded
9837  * — the name of the 
9838  * <tt>color</tt> role's default dimension —,
9839  * resulting in a 
9840  * <i>continuous</i> color scale.
9841  * <p>
9842  * Otherwise, by default,
9843  * the 
9844  * <tt>color</tt> visual role ends up being bound the
9845  * dimensions of the series role — its default 
9846  * <i>source role</i> —,
9847  * resulting in a 
9848  * <i>discrete</i> color scale.
9849  * <p>
9850  * The 
9851  * <tt>color</tt> role can also be bound to other discrete dimension(s), explicitly.
9852  * 
9853  * <h4>Solution 1</h4>
9854  * One possibility is to 
9855  * <i>switch</i> one of the automatically fed "series" dimensions
9856  * to the 
9857  * <tt>color</tt> visual role.
9858  * For example:
9859  * 
9860  * <pre>
9861  * seriesRole: "series", // steal one here
9862  * colorRole:  "series2" // and assign it here
9863  * 
9864  * </pre>
9865  * 
9866  * <h4>Solution 2</h4>
9867  * A second possibility is to simply match colors to "series":
9868  * 
9869  * <pre>
9870  * seriesRole: {from: "series"} // same dimensions as the series visual role
9871  * 
9872  * </pre>
9873  * 
9874  * <h4>Solution 3</h4>
9875  * Another possibility is to configure the {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers}
9876  * with the actual layout, using the default dimension names of
9877  * the desired visual roles.
9878  * For example:
9879  * 
9880  * <pre>
9881  * readers: "color, series, x, y, size"
9882  * 
9883  * </pre>
9884  * 
9885  * <h4>Solution 4</h4>
9886  * Of course, you can (and probably should) use actual business names for the names of dimensions.
9887  * To that end, both the readers and the visual roles' mappings need to be specified:
9888  * 
9889  * <pre>
9890  * readers:      "orderType, productFamily, productType, expectedSales, actualSales, profit"
9891  * colorRole:    "orderType",
9892  * seriesRole:   "orderType", // controls drawing layer only
9893  * xRole:        "expectedSales",
9894  * yRole:        "actualSales",
9895  * sizeRole:     "profit"
9896  * 
9897  * </pre>
9898  * Note that in this plot type, the series visual role only controls the layer
9899  * of the dot cloud.
9900  * Also, the dimensions "productFamily" and "productType"
9901  * were not mapped to any visual role,
9902  * and will only be presented in the tooltip.
9903  * 
9904  * @class
9905  * @extends pvc.options.charts.CartesianChart
9906  * @abstract
9907  */
9908 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart = function(){};
9909         
9910         
9911

10042 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallContentMargins = undefined;

10045  * <i>content panel</i> of a 
10046  * <i>small</i> chart.

10048  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
10049  * the different supported data types.
10050  * 
10051  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
10052  * @default 0

10055 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallContentPaddings = undefined;
10056 /**
10057  * Fixates the height of each 
10058  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
10059  * <p>
10060  * A value of type 
10061  * <tt>number</tt>,
10062  * or of type 
10063  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
10064  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
10065  * <p>
10066  * A value of type 
10067  * <tt>string</tt>,
10068  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
10069  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content height.
10070  * <p>
10071  * This property may cause the 
10072  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
10073  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #height}.
10074  * <p>
10075  * When this property is unspecified,
10076  * its value depends on the evaluation of the
10077  * {@link #smallWidth} property,
10078  * which may impose it a value.
10079  * If after the evaluation of {@link #smallWidth}
10080  * this property remains unspecified,
10081  * it is determined as follows.
10082  * <p>
10083  * If the layout will have a single column
10084  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleColFillsHeight}
10085  * is 
10086  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
10087  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
10088  * <p>
10089  * If the layout will have a single row
10090  * and the property {@link #multiChartSingleRowFillsHeight}
10091  * is 
10092  * <tt>true</tt> (it is by default)
10093  * then the height will be the initially available content height.
10094  * <p>
10095  * Otherwise, the property {@link #smallAspectRatio} is
10096  * used to determine the height of the small chart from its determined width.
10097  * <p>
10098  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
10099  * but is something around 
10100  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
10101  * 
10102  * @type number|string
10103  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10104  */
10105 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallHeight = undefined;
10106 /**
10107  * The margins of a 
10108  * <i>small</i> chart.
10109  * <p>
10110  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
10111  * the different supported data types.
10112  * 
10113  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
10114  * @default '2%'
10115  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10116  */
10117 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallMargins = undefined;
10118 /**
10119  * The paddings of a 
10120  * <i>small</i> chart.
10121  * <p>
10122  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides} for information about
10123  * the different supported data types.
10124  * 
10125  * @type number|string|pvc.options.varia.Sides
10126  * @default 0
10127  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10128  */
10129 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallPaddings = undefined;
10130 /**
10131  * Fixates the width of each 
10132  * <i>small</i> chart, in pixel units or as a percentage.
10133  * <p>
10134  * A value of type 
10135  * <tt>number</tt>,
10136  * or of type 
10137  * <tt>string</tt>, but with numeric content,
10138  * is interpreted as being in pixel units.
10139  * <p>
10140  * A value of type 
10141  * <tt>string</tt>,
10142  * with numeric content that is suffixed by a "%" character,
10143  * is interpreted as a percentage of the initially available content width.
10144  * <p>
10145  * This property may cause the 
10146  * <i>small multiples</i> chart
10147  * to take up a greater width than the one specified in {@link #width}.
10148  * <p>
10149  * When this property is unspecified,
10150  * a specified finite value, or a defaulted value, of the property {@link #multiChartColumnsMax} is
10151  * used to determine it:
10152  * by dividing the initially available content width
10153  * by the maximum number of charts in a row that 
10154  * <i>actually</i> occur
10155  * (so that if there are less small charts than
10156  * the maximum that can be placed in a row,
10157  * these, nevertheless, take up the whole width).
10158  * <p>
10159  * When an infinite value is specified for
10160  * {@link #multiChartColumnsMax},
10161  * the small charts are laid out in a single row,
10162  * and so the width is calculated from the height {@link #smallHeight},
10163  * using the aspect ratio {@link #smallAspectRatio}.
10164  * The height is defaulted to the initially available content height.
10165  * The aspect ratio is defaulted to a value that depends on the chart type,
10166  * but is something around 
10167  * <tt>4/3</tt>.
10168  * The width is then calculated.
10169  * 
10170  * @type number|string
10171  * @category Chart - Multi > Layout
10172  */
10173 pvc.options.charts.MetricPointChart.prototype.smallWidth = undefined;
10174 /**
10175  * The indexes of columns of the 
10176  * <i>logical table</i> that are to feed the

10181  * <tt>multiChart2</tt>, ...
10182  * dimensions.
10183  * <p>
10184  * See {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#readers} for related information.
10185  * 
10186  * @type number|string|list(number|string)
10187  * @category Chart > Data Source
10188  */

10190 /**
10191  * The 
10192  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role is a chart-level visual role that
10193  * allows turning a chart into a 
10194  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
10195  * {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_multiple}.
10196  * <p>
10197  * Almost all main chart types support being shown
10198  * as a small multiples chart.
10199  * Currently, the exceptions are the charts:
10200  * 
10201  * <i>Heat Grid</i>,
10202  * 
10203  * <i>Bullet</i>,
10204  * 
10205  * <i>Data Tree</i> and
10206  * 
10207  * <i>Parallel Coordinates</i>.
10208  * <p>
10209  * The 
10210  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role
10211  * can be bound to any number of dimensions,
10212  * that are, or will be turned into, discrete.
10213  * <p>
10214  * The 
10215  * <tt>multiChart</tt> visual role automatically binds to
10216  * every dimension whose name has the 
10217  * <tt>multiChart</tt> prefix.
10218  * <p>
10219  * One 
10220  * <i>small</i> chart is generated per
10221  * unique combination of the values of the bound dimensions
10222  * that is present in the source data.
10223  * Each small chart then receives as its data
10224  * the partition of the source data that shares its
10225  * unique combination of values.
10226  * <p>
10227  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
10228  * for more information on supported data types.
10229  * 
10230  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
10231  * @category Chart > Visual Roles
10232  */

10700 /**
10701  * The 
10702  * <tt>color</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
10703  * is visually encoded by the color of visual elements.
10704  * <p>
10705  * Specifically,
10706  * it is the color of the dots and lines of the visual elements
10707  * that is changed according to the color of the corresponding
10708  * color role value.
10709  * <p>
10710  * The 
10711  * <tt>color</tt> visual role automatically binds to
10712  * every discrete dimension, or a single continuous dimension,
10713  * whose name has the 
10714  * <tt>color</tt> prefix
10715  * or, if none exists,
10716  * the dimensions of the "series" role.
10717  * <p>
10718  * The 
10719  * <tt>color</tt> visual role is discrete or continuous.
10720  * <p>
10721  * The default value type of dimensions bound to it is 
10722  * <tt>Number</tt>.
10723  * <p>
10724  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
10725  * for more information on supported data types.
10726  * 
10727  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
10728  * @category Visual Roles
10729  */
10730 pvc.options.visualRoles.MetricPointPlotVisualRoles.prototype.color = undefined;
10731 /**
10732  * The 
10733  * <tt>size</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that
10734  * is visually encoded by the size of visual elements.
10735  * <p>
10736  * Specifically, when dots are visible,
10737  * controls the size of the dot mark.
10738  * <p>
10739  * The 
10740  * <tt>size</tt> visual role automatically binds to
10741  * every dimension whose name has the 
10742  * <tt>size</tt> prefix.
10743  * <p>
10744  * The 
10745  * <tt>size</tt> visual role is continuous and optional.
10746  * <p>
10747  * The default value type of the dimension bound to it is 
10748  * <tt>Number</tt>.
10749  * <p>
10750  * See {@link pvc.options.VisualRole}
10751  * for more information on supported data types.
10752  * 
10753  * @type string|pvc.options.VisualRole
10754  * @category Visual Roles
10755  */
10756 pvc.options.visualRoles.MetricPointPlotVisualRoles.prototype.size = undefined;

10759  * <tt>x</tt> visual role is a plot-level visual role that

10761  * <i>base</i> position of the "point" visual element.
10762  * <p>
10763  * The 
10764  * <tt>x</tt> visual role automatically binds to

10766  * <tt>x</tt> prefix.

10782  * for more information on supported data types.

10960 /**
10961  * Use this extension point to add
10962  * a new protovis mark to another mark.
10963  * <p>
10964  * If the extension point refers to a panel mark,
10965  * the parent of the new mark will be that panel.
10966  * Otherwise, its parent will
10967  * be the parent panel of the mark of the extension point.
10968  * 
10969  * <p>
10970  * The following example shows how to add an image to
10971  * an axis tick:
10972  * 
10973  * <pre>
10974  * function yAxisTick(){
10975  *     return new pv.Image()
10976  *             .url('res/images/arrowYy.png')
10977  *             .lineWidth(0)
10978  *             .height(7)
10979  *             .width(5);
10980  * }
10981  *                 
10982  * </pre>
10983  * 
10984  * <p>
10985  * 
10986  * @type function
10987  */
10988 pvc.options.marks.MarkExtensionPoint.prototype.add = undefined;

10996  * 
10997  * @type number
10998  */

11021  *

11025 /**
11026  * Flags that affect the interactivity of the mark.
11027  * <p>
11028  * The default value, 
11029  * <tt>-1</tt> has all bits with the value "1".
11030  * <p>
11031  * Only the bits for which {@link #imask} is "1" are considered.
11032  * <p>
11033  * Bits can be combined by using a "|" character, for example:
11034  * 
11035  * <code>"Selectable|Hoverable"</code>
11036  * <p>
11037  * The following are the supported bit values:
11038  * 
11039  * <style>
11040  * .bitstable {
11041  * border-spacing: 0;
11042  * margin: 1em 0;
11043  * }
11044  * .bitstable th {
11045  * font-weight: bold;
11046  * }
11047  * .bitstable td, .bitstable th {
11048  * border:  solid 1px;
11049  * padding: 5px;
11050  * }
11051  * </style>
11052  * 
11053  * <table class='bitstable'>
11054  * 
11055  * <tr>
11056  * 
11057  * <th>bit</th>
11058  * 
11059  * <th>description</th>
11060  * </tr>
11061  * 
11062  * <tr>
11063  * 
11064  * <td>Interactive</td>
11065  * 
11066  * <td>
11067  * The mark can trigger and display interaction.
11068  * </td>
11069  * </tr>
11070  * 
11071  * <tr>
11072  * 
11073  * <td>ShowsActivity</td>
11074  * 
11075  * <td>The mark's style can change based on the active scene.</td>
11076  * </tr>
11077  * 
11078  * <tr>
11079  * 
11080  * <td>ShowsSelection</td>
11081  * 
11082  * <td>The mark's style can change based on whether the datums in its scene are selected.</td>
11083  * </tr>
11084  * 
11085  * <tr>
11086  * 
11087  * <td>ShowsTooltip</td>
11088  * 
11089  * <td>The mark displays a tooltip when pointed to.</td>
11090  * </tr>
11091  * 
11092  * <tr>
11093  * 
11094  * <td>Selectable</td>
11095  * 
11096  * <td>
11097  * The mark can be selected by one of the possible means.
11098  * Use this to disable this mark from affecting selection,
11099  * by whatever means.
11100  * </td>
11101  * </tr>
11102  * 
11103  * <tr>
11104  * 
11105  * <td>SelectableByClick</td>
11106  * 
11107  * <td>
11108  * The mark can be selected by clicking on it.
11109  * Requires the 
11110  * <i>Selectable</i> bit as well.
11111  * </td>
11112  * </tr>
11113  * 
11114  * <tr>
11115  * 
11116  * <td>SelectableByRubberband</td>
11117  * 
11118  * <td>
11119  * The mark can be selected by using the rubber-band.
11120  * </td>
11121  * </tr>
11122  * 
11123  * <tr>
11124  * 
11125  * <td>SelectableByFocusWindow</td>
11126  * 
11127  * <td>
11128  * The mark can be selected when the focus window reveals it.
11129  * </td>
11130  * </tr>
11131  * 
11132  * <tr>
11133  * 
11134  * <td>Hoverable</td>
11135  * 
11136  * <td>
11137  * The mark can be hovered-over and affect its scene's active state.
11138  * </td>
11139  * </tr>
11140  * 
11141  * <tr>
11142  * 
11143  * <td>Clickable</td>
11144  * 
11145  * <td>
11146  * The mark can be clicked and trigger the 
11147  * <i>clickAction</i> handler.
11148  * </td>
11149  * </tr>
11150  * 
11151  * <tr>
11152  * 
11153  * <td>DoubleClickable</td>
11154  * 
11155  * <td>
11156  * The mark can be double-clicked and trigger the 
11157  * <i>doubleClickAction</i> handler.
11158  * </td>
11159  * </tr>
11160  * </table>
11161  * 
11162  * @type number|string
11163  * @default -1
11164  */
11165 pvc.options.marks.MarkExtensionPoint.prototype.ibits = undefined;

11910  * @namespace

11912 pvc.options.axes = {};
11913 
11914 /**
11915  * The options documentation class of the color axis.
11916  * <p>
11917  * A color axis panel and its properties
11918  * can be referred to in several ways,
11919  * in order of precedence:
11920  * 
11921  * <dl>
11922  * 
11923  * <dt>By 
11924  * <b>full id</b></dt>
11925  * 
11926  * <dd>
11927  * the id of the axis is the word 
11928  * <tt>color</tt>,
11929  * followed by it's index (when >= 2),
11930  * and terminated by the word 
11931  * <tt>Axis</tt>.
11932  * </dd>
11933  * 
11934  * <dd>(ex: 
11935  * <tt>colorAxis</tt>, 
11936  * <tt>color2Axis</tt>, 
11937  * <tt>color3Axis</tt>, ...)</dd>
11938  * 
11939  * <dt>By the single word 
11940  * <tt>color</tt>, when it is the first one</dt>
11941  * 
11942  * <dd>
11943  * to make it easier to specify the properties of
11944  * the most used color axis - the first one -
11945  * it can be referred to without the suffix 
11946  * <tt>Axis</tt>,
11947  * resulting in the name 
11948  * <tt>color</tt>.
11949  * </dd>
11950  * 
11951  * <dt>Without id, when it is the first one, for legend properties and the 
11952  * <tt>colors</tt> property</dt>
11953  * 
11954  * <dd>
11955  * Legend related properties of the first axis
11956  * can be referred to directly, without the axis id.
11957  * The same applies to the property 
11958  * <tt>colors</tt>.
11959  * <p>
11960  * As an example,
11961  * the name of the property 
11962  * <tt>legendDrawLine</tt>
11963  * can be used directly, instead of its full name:
11964  * 
11965  * <tt>colorLegendDrawLine</tt>.
11966  * <p>
11967  * For color axes other than the first,
11968  * the legend properties still need to be referred to
11969  * with its full name, like in:
11970  * 
11971  * <tt>color2AxisLegendDrawLine</tt>.
11972  * </dd>
11973  * </dl>
11974  * <p>
11975  * The domain of color axes
11976  * is evaluated at the root chart level.
11977  * When in a 
11978  * <i>small multiples</i> chart,
11979  * colors are shared among 
11980  * <i>small</i> charts.
11981  * <p>
11982  * Color axes map values of the "color" visual role.
11983  * <p>
11984  * For more information on options
11985  * that are specific to only certain color axis types,
11986  * please see one of the following concrete sub-classes:
11987  * 
11988  * <ul>
11989  * 
11990  * <li>
11991  * Numeric or discrete domain color axes: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyColorAxis}
11992  * </li>
11993  * 
11994  * <li>
11995  * Discrete domain color axes: {@link pvc.options.axes.DiscreteColorAxis}
11996  * </li>
11997  * 
11998  * <li>
11999  * Heat-grid - numeric domain color axis: {@link pvc.options.axes.HeatGridColorAxis}
12000  * </li>
12001  * </ul>
12002  * 
12003  * @class
12004  * @abstract
12005  */
12006 pvc.options.axes.ColorAxis = function(){};
12007         
12008         
12009         
12010         
12011 /**
12012  * The colors of a color axis.
12013  * <p>
12014  * It can be a single color as documented in
12015  * {@link pvc.options.varia.ColorString} or
12016  * a single 
12017  * <i>protovis</i> color object
12018  * (like: 
12019  * <tt>pv.color('red')</tt> or 
12020  * <tt>pv.Color.names.blueviolet</tt>).
12021  * <p>
12022  * Additionally, an array of color strings or
12023  * 
12024  * <i>protovis</i> colors can be specified.
12025  * <p>
12026  * If a function is specified, it can be:
12027  * 
12028  * <ul>
12029  * 
12030  * <li>
12031  * 
12032  * <b>a protovis scale</b>,
12033  * like the one obtained by:
12034  * 
12035  * <tt>pv.colors('red', 'blueviolet')</tt>
12036  * </li>
12037  * 
12038  * <li>
12039  * 
12040  * <b>a scale factory</b> - a function that
12041  * given the domain values as arguments
12042  * return a protovis color scale
12043  * </li>
12044  * </ul>
12045  * <p>
12046  * The default color scheme depends on the
12047  * axis domain being discrete or numeric.
12048  * <p>
12049  * For 
12050  * <b>discrete domains</b>, the default value is the 
12051  * <i>protovis</i>
12052  * 
12053  * <tt>category10</tt> color scheme:
12054  * 
12055  * <ol style='font-weight:bold'>
12056  * 
12057  * <li style='color:#1f77b4'>value</li>
12058  * 
12059  * <li style='color:#ff7f0e'>value</li>
12060  * 
12061  * <li style='color:#2ca02c'>value</li>
12062  * 
12063  * <li style='color:#d62728'>value</li>
12064  * 
12065  * <li style='color:#9467bd'>value</li>
12066  * 
12067  * <li style='color:#8c564b'>value</li>
12068  * 
12069  * <li style='color:#e377c2'>value</li>
12070  * 
12071  * <li style='color:#7f7f7f'>value</li>
12072  * 
12073  * <li style='color:#bcbd22'>value</li>
12074  * 
12075  * <li style='color:#17becf'>value</li>
12076  * </ol>
12077  * <p>
12078  * For 
12079  * <b>numeric domains</b>, the default value is the
12080  * color scheme:
12081  * 
12082  * <ol style='font-weight:bold'>
12083  * 
12084  * <li style='color:red'>value</li>
12085  *

12157 /**
12158  * Allows reserving colors to certain color scale keys.
12159  * <p>
12160  * Color scale keys are the values of the color role.
12161  * By default, the color role is bound to the dimensions of the series role.
12162  * Color scale keys that are not mapped,
12163  * receive colors taken from {@link #colors}.
12164  * Colors in {@link #colors} that are also present in the color map are ignored.
12165  *

12168  * <tt>"territory, country"</tt>,
12169  * the following map would reserve the colors 
12170  * <i>red</i> and 
12171  * <i>green</i> to
12172  * Canada and Portugal, respectively:
12173  * 
12174  * <pre>
12175  * chartOptions.colorMap = {
12176  *     "NA~Canada":     "red",
12177  *     "EMEA~Portugal": "green"
12178  * };
12179  *                 
12180  * </pre>
12181  * <p>
12182  * Assumes that the default {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#dataSeparator} is used.
12183  * 
12184  * <p>
12185  *

12681 /**
12682  * The options documentation class of 
12683  * the cartesian axis 
12684  * and cartesian axis panel.
12685  * <p>
12686  * A cartesian axis (and its panel) can be referred to in several ways,
12687  * in order of precedence:
12688  * 
12689  * <dl>
12690  * 
12691  * <dt>By 
12692  * <b>id</b></dt>
12693  * 
12694  * <dd>the id of the axis is its type followed by it's index (when >= 2)</dd>
12695  * 
12696  * <dd>(ex: 
12697  * <tt>base</tt>, 
12698  * <tt>ortho</tt>, 
12699  * <tt>base2</tt>, 
12700  * <tt>ortho2</tt>, ...)</dd>
12701  * 
12702  * <dt>By 
12703  * <b>oriented id</b></dt>
12704  * 
12705  * <dd>the oriented id of the axis is its orientation followed by it's index (when >= 2)</dd>
12706  * 
12707  * <dd>(ex: 
12708  * <tt>x</tt>, 
12709  * <tt>y</tt>, 
12710  * <tt>x2</tt>, 
12711  * <tt>y2</tt>, ...)</dd>
12712  * 
12713  * <dt>By 
12714  * <b>legacy name</b></dt>
12715  * 
12716  * <dd>
12717  * for the special case of the bar chart, 
12718  * the second axes:
12719  * 
12720  * <ul>
12721  * 
12722  * <li>
12723  * 
12724  * <b>normal properties</b> —
12725  * may be referred to by the name 
12726  * <tt>second</tt> 
12727  * </li>
12728  * 
12729  * <li>
12730  * 
12731  * <b>extension points</b> —
12732  * may be referred to by the names 
12733  * <tt>secondX</tt> and 
12734  * <tt>secondY</tt>
12735  * </li>
12736  * </ul>
12737  * <p>
12738  * In any case, those names are now deprecated.
12739  * </dd>
12740  * 
12741  * <dt>By 
12742  * <b>scale type</b></dt>
12743  * 
12744  * <dd>
12745  * the scale type can be 
12746  * <tt>discrete</tt> or 
12747  * <tt>continuous</tt> and, 
12748  * in the later case, with lower precedence, 
12749  * 
12750  * <tt>numeric</tt> and 
12751  * <tt>timeSeries</tt> are also possible
12752  * </dd>
12753  * 
12754  * <dt>By 
12755  * <b>catch all name</b></dt>
12756  * 
12757  * <dd>the name 
12758  * <tt>axis</tt> matches any cartesian axis</dd>
12759  * </dl>
12760  * <p>
12761  * These names apply equally to the prefixes used to 
12762  * build extension point names.
12763  * <p>
12764  * Which of the names is used depends on 
12765  * which better selects the axes for the properties being specified.
12766  * If a property should only be applied to vertical axes, 
12767  * independently of the chart's orientation, the 
12768  * <i>oriented id</i>
12769  * should be used. 
12770  * If, otherwise, a property should only be applied to the base axis,
12771  * whether or not it is horizontally aligned, 
12772  * then the normal 
12773  * <i>id</i> should be used.
12774  * If, a property should only apply to continuous axes,
12775  * the 
12776  * <i>scale type</i> should be used.
12777  * <p>
12778  * For more information on options
12779  * that are specific to only certain axis types,
12780  * please see one of the following concrete sub-classes:
12781  * 
12782  * <ul>
12783  * 
12784  * <li>
12785  * Numeric-only axes: {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis}
12786  * </li>
12787  * 
12788  * <li>
12789  * Normal discrete: {@link pvc.options.axes.FlattenedDiscreteCartesianAxis}
12790  * </li>
12791  * 
12792  * <li>
12793  * Numeric or time-series: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis}
12794  * </li>
12795  * 
12796  * <li>
12797  * Normal or hierarchical discrete:: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyDiscreteCartesianAxis}
12798  * </li>
12799  * 
12800  * <li>
12801  * Numeric, time-series or normal discrete: {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis}
12802  * </li>
12803  * </ul>
12804  * 
12805  * @class
12806  * @extends pvc.options.panels.Panel
12807  * @abstract
12808  */
12809 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis = function(){};

12814 /**

12949 /**
12950  * A tick formatter function.
12951  * <p>
12952  * This function has two arguments variants:
12953  * 
12954  * <dl>
12955  * 
12956  * <dt>continuous</dt> 
12957  * <dd>tickFormatter(value, precision, index)</dd>
12958  * 
12959  * <dt>discrete</dt>   
12960  * <dd>tickFormatter(value, label)</dd>
12961  * </dl>
12962  * <p>
12963  * Generally,
12964  * a continuous axis uses the 
12965  * <i>continuous</i> variant and
12966  * a discrete axis uses the 
12967  * <i>discrete</i> variant.
12968  * <p>
12969  * But, there is one exception to this rule:
12970  * a discrete axis having a single date dimension,
12971  * uses the 
12972  * <i>continuous</i> variant.
12973  * This makes it easier to format date categories,
12974  * by automatically choosing an adequate precision,
12975  * that takes the actual data range into account.
12976  * It's also legacy, version 1, behavior.
12977  * <p>
12978  * Summing up:
12979  * 
12980  * <ul>
12981  * 
12982  * <li>a continuous axis uses the 
12983  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant,</li>
12984  * 
12985  * <li>a discrete axis can use both arguments variant,</li>
12986  * 
12987  * <li>an axis with a single date dimension, uses the 
12988  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant.</li>
12989  * </ul>
12990  * 
12991  * <p>
12992  * <b>Context object</b></p>
12993  * <p>
12994  * The function is called having as 
12995  * <tt>this</tt> the ticks array,
12996  * whose tick values are being formatted.
12997  * <p>
12998  * Together with the 
12999  * <i>index</i> argument,
13000  * it is possible to use the value of the previous and/or following ticks
13001  * to format the current tick.
13002  * <p>
13003  * The ticks array provides the following useful properties:
13004  * 
13005  * <ul>
13006  * 
13007  * <li>step — the used precision</li>
13008  * 
13009  * <li>base — the base precision from which step is derived</li>
13010  * 
13011  * <li>mult — the multiple of base precision that yields step (step = base * mult)</li>
13012  * 
13013  * <li>format(v) - the default formatting function</li>
13014  * 
13015  * <li>length — the number of ticks</li>
13016  * </ul>
13017  * 
13018  * @returns {string}
13019  * The string that is the formatted value.
13020  * 
13021  * @method
13022  * @this Array
13023  * @param {string|number|Date} value
13024  * The value to format.
13025  * 
13026  * <dl>
13027  * 
13028  * <dt>
13029  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant</dt>
13030  * 
13031  * <dd>
13032  * The type of argument 
13033  * <i>value</i> can be 
13034  * <i>number</i> or 
13035  * <i>Date</i>.
13036  * </dd>
13037  * 
13038  * <dt>
13039  * <i>discrete</i> arguments variant</dt>
13040  * 
13041  * <dd>
13042  * The type of argument 
13043  * <i>value</i> can be 
13044  * <i>string</i> or 
13045  * <i>number</i>.
13046  * <p>
13047  * When the axis has a single dimension,
13048  * argument 
13049  * <i>value</i> is the 
13050  * <b>value</b> of that dimension.
13051  * <p>
13052  * When the axis has more than one dimension, and is flattened,
13053  * argument 
13054  * <i>value</i> is the junction of the 
13055  * <b>key</b> values of all dimensions,
13056  * separated by {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#dataSeparator}.
13057  * <p>
13058  * When the axis is hierarchical (composite),
13059  * argument 
13060  * <i>value</i> is the 
13061  * <b>key</b> value of the dimension at a certain level.
13062  * </dd>
13063  * </dl>
13064  * 
13065  * @param {number} [precision]
13066  * The precision in which the 
13067  * <i>value</i> argument should be formatted.
13068  * 
13069  * <p>
13070  * <b>ATTENTION:</b> only present in the 
13071  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant!</p>
13072  * <p>
13073  * When the axis has a 
13074  * <b>date</b> scale type,
13075  * the argument is the chosen 
13076  * 
13077  * <i>number of milliseconds</i> between tick values.
13078  * <p>
13079  * The standard time precisions are:
13080  * 
13081  * <dl>
13082  * 
13083  * <dt>
13084  * <tt>31536e6</tt></dt>
13085  * <dd>1 year (pvc.time.intervals.y)</dd>
13086  * 
13087  * <dt>
13088  * <tt>2592e6</tt></dt>
13089  * <dd>30 days (pvc.time.intervals.m or pvc.time.intervals.d30)</dd>
13090  * 
13091  * <dt>
13092  * <tt>6048e5</tt></dt>
13093  * <dd>7 days (pvc.time.intervals.w or pvc.time.intervals.d7)</dd>
13094  * 
13095  * <dt>
13096  * <tt>864e5</tt></dt>
13097  * <dd>1 day (pvc.time.intervals.d)</dd>
13098  * 
13099  * <dt>
13100  * <tt>36e5</tt></dt>
13101  * <dd>1 hour (pvc.time.intervals.h)</dd>
13102  * 
13103  * <dt>
13104  * <tt>6e4</tt></dt>
13105  * <dd>1 minute (pvc.time.intervals.M)</dd>
13106  * 
13107  * <dt>
13108  * <tt>1e3</tt></dt>
13109  * <dd>1 second (pvc.time.intervals.s)</dd>
13110  * 
13111  * <dt>
13112  * <tt>1</tt></dt>
13113  * <dd>1 millisecond (pvc.time.intervals.ms)</dd>
13114  * </dl>
13115  * <p>
13116  * In general, the given precision is an integer multiple of one the standard precisions.
13117  * It is many times more useful to use the base standard precision on which the final precision is based on
13118  * (the value of the context property 
13119  * <tt>this.base</tt>).
13120  * <p>
13121  * When the axis has a 
13122  * <b>numeric</b> scale type,
13123  * the argument is the 
13124  * <i>number of decimal places</i> of
13125  * the chosen step value.
13126  * 
13127  * @param {number} [index]
13128  * The index of the tick being formatted.
13129  * 
13130  * <p>
13131  * <b>ATTENTION:</b> only present in the 
13132  * <i>continuous</i> arguments variant!</p>
13133  * <p>
13134  * You may use the index to access neighbouring ticks from the 
13135  * <tt>this</tt> ticks array
13136  * (e..g. 
13137  * <tt>this[index + 1]</tt>).
13138  * 
13139  * @param {string} [label]
13140  * The default label.
13141  * 
13142  * <p>
13143  * <b>ATTENTION:</b> only present in the 
13144  * <i>discrete</i> arguments variant!</p>
13145  * <p>
13146  * The default label is the label that would be displayed
13147  * if the tick formatter had not been specified.
13148  * <p>
13149  * When the axis has a single dimension,
13150  * argument 
13151  * <i>label</i> is the 
13152  * <b>label</b> as formatted by that dimension.
13153  * <p>
13154  * When the axis has more than one dimension, and is flattened,
13155  * argument 
13156  * <i>label</i> is the junction of the 
13157  * <b>label</b> values of all dimensions,
13158  * separated by {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#groupedLabelSep}.
13159  * <p>
13160  * When the axis is hierarchical (composite),
13161  * argument 
13162  * <i>label</i> is the 
13163  * <b>label</b> as formatted by the dimension at a certain level.
13164  * 
13165  * @category Style
13166  */
13167 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis.prototype.tickFormatter = function(){};

13171  * @type string|pvc.options.panels.CartesianAxisTitlePanel

13173  */
13174 pvc.options.axes.CartesianAxis.prototype.title = undefined;

13312 /**
13313  * The size, in pixels, of the bands used to represent the discrete domain values (applies to discrete axes).
13314  * <p>
13315  * A non-negative number.
13316  * 
13317  * <p>
13318  * 
13319  * <b>In multi-charts</b>
13320  * <p>
13321  * The current layout algorithm used by multi-charts does not support
13322  * minimum, fixed or maximum sizes in small charts.
13323  * As such, the simples band size ratio model always needs to be used.
13324  * <p>
13325  * The minimum, fixed and maximum sizes and spacings are used to determine an
13326  * equivalent or best-possible band size ratio.
13327  * </p>
13328  * 
13329  * <p>
13330  * 
13331  * <b>Band Size, Spacing, Ratio and Step</b>
13332  * <p>
13333  * The band layout arranges bands and space in the following way.
13334  * Taking 
13335  * <i>B</i> to represent 
13336  * <i>bandSize</i>,
13337  * 
13338  * <i>E</i> to represent {@link #bandSpacing} and
13339  * 
13340  * <i>e</i> to be 
13341  * <tt>E/2</tt>,
13342  * bands and space will follow the pattern:
13343  * 
13344  * <tt>eBe</tt>, 
13345  * <tt>eBEBe</tt>, 
13346  * <tt>eBEBEBe</tt>, ...
13347  * <p>
13348  * For a given pair of 
13349  * <i>B</i> and 
13350  * <i>E</i>, each discrete category will occupy a space given by
13351  * the 
13352  * <i>step</i>, 
13353  * <i>S</i>:
13354  * <br></br>
13355  * 
13356  * <i>S = B + E</i>.
13357  * <p>
13358  * Given the number of discrete categories, a cartesian panel (axis or plot) will have
13359  * corresponding fixed or minimum and maximum sizes.
13360  * <p>
13361  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, R, is used, in under-constrained cases,
13362  * to relate 
13363  * <i>B</i> and 
13364  * <i>E</i>:
13365  * <br></br>
13366  * 
13367  * <i>B = R * S</i>
13368  * </p>
13369  * 
13370  * <p>
13371  * 
13372  * <b>Impact on chart size</b>
13373  * <p>
13374  * If the chart size along the axis' dimension
13375  * is such that the available space is less than the
13376  * determined fixed or minimum size,
13377  * then the chart will grow as much as needed to accommodate the fixed or minimum size,
13378  * along that dimension.
13379  * <p>
13380  * If, on the contrary, the chart size along the axis' dimension
13381  * is greater than the determined fixed or maximum size,
13382  * the plot and axis content will be centered in the available space.
13383  * </p>
13384  * 
13385  * <p>
13386  * 
13387  * <b>Option values harmonization</b>
13388  * <p>
13389  * When both {@link #bandSizeMax} and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
13390  * and {@link #bandSizeMax} is less than or equal to 
13391  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
13392  * then {@link #bandSize} is set to the the minimum value.
13393  * <p>
13394  * When both 
13395  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
13396  * and 
13397  * <i>bandSize</i> is less than 
13398  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
13399  * then the minimum value is used instead.
13400  * <p>
13401  * When both 
13402  * <i>bandSpacing</i> and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
13403  * and 
13404  * <i>bandSpacing</i> is less than 
13405  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
13406  * then the minimum value is used instead.
13407  * <p>
13408  * When both {@link #bandSpacingMax} and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
13409  * and {@link #bandSpacingMax} is less than or equal to 
13410  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
13411  * then {@link #bandSpacing} is set to the the minimum value.
13412  * </p>
13413  * 
13414  * <p>
13415  * 
13416  * <b>The algorithm</b>
13417  * <p>
13418  * The options you specify should just behave as you'd expected them to.
13419  * At least, after thinking about them for a while.
13420  * <p>
13421  * If doubts remain on which options and values should be specified,
13422  * or on why the specified options are behaving in a certain way,
13423  * you can follow this explanation of the band layout algorithm.
13424  * </p>
13425  * 
13426  * <ul>
13427  * 
13428  * <li>
13429  * When both 
13430  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSpacing} are specified, the layout is 
13431  * <b>fixed</b>.
13432  * <p>
13433  * When they both have the value 
13434  * <tt>0</tt>, then the layout is reevaluated as if they had not been specified.
13435  * <p>
13436  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
13437  * </li>
13438  * 
13439  * <li>
13440  * When one and only one of 
13441  * <i>bandSize</i> or {@link #bandSpacing} is specified,
13442  * the layout is 
13443  * <b>partially fixed</b>.
13444  * <p>
13445  * For the variable option, size or spacing,
13446  * any specified minimum and/or maximum options are still considered.
13447  * <p>
13448  * This configuration does not define a fixed step size,
13449  * but instead constrains the range of step size values.
13450  * <p>
13451  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
13452  * </li>
13453  * 
13454  * <li>
13455  * When neither 
13456  * <i>bandSize</i> nor {@link #bandSpacing} are specified,
13457  * the layout is 
13458  * <b>strictly variable</b>.
13459  * <p>
13460  * There are several cases:
13461  * 
13462  * <ul>
13463  * 
13464  * <li>
13465  * When none of the minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
13466  * the size and spacing are governed solely by the {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
13467  * <i>R</i>.
13468  * <p>
13469  * This is the way the band layout used to behave,
13470  * before the existence of the fixed, minimum and maximum options.
13471  * <p>
13472  * Small-charts continue to behave this way,
13473  * although with a band size ratio that is determined from the
13474  * the other specified options.
13475  * <p>
13476  * The half-line 
13477  * <i>(E,B)</i> departs from 
13478  * <i>(0,0)</i>
13479  * and goes on indefinitely with a slope given by 
13480  * <i>R</i>: 
13481  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
13482  * </li>
13483  * 
13484  * <li>
13485  * 
13486  * <p>
13487  * When minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
13488  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
13489  * line segment 
13490  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
13491  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i> to point 
13492  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
13493  * </p>
13494  * </li>
13495  * 
13496  * <li>
13497  * 
13498  * <p>
13499  * When only the minimum size and spacing values are specified,
13500  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
13501  * line segment 
13502  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
13503  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
13504  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i>.
13505  * </p>
13506  * </li>
13507  * 
13508  * <li>
13509  * 
13510  * <p>
13511  * When only the maximum size and spacing values are specified,
13512  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
13513  * line segment 
13514  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
13515  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
13516  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
13517  * </p>
13518  * </li>
13519  * 
13520  * <li>
13521  * In all the following mixed and under-constrained cases,
13522  * option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
13523  * <i>R</i>, is taken into account.
13524  * <p>
13525  * The size and spacing are constrained to belong to the the line 
13526  * <i>(E,B)</i> that
13527  * passes through 
13528  * <i>(0,0)</i> and has a slope
13529  * given by 
13530  * <i>R</i>: 
13531  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
13532  * <p>
13533  * Again, a few more cases:
13534  * 
13535  * <ul>
13536  * 
13537  * <li>
13538  * 
13539  * <p>
13540  * When only the minimum and maximum size values are specified,
13541  * the corresponding spacing values are implied.
13542  * </p>
13543  * </li>
13544  * 
13545  * <li>
13546  * 
13547  * <p>
13548  * When only the minimum and maximum spacing values are specified,
13549  * the corresponding size values are implied.
13550  * </p>
13551  * </li>
13552  * 
13553  * <li>
13554  * When only the minimum size and the maximum spacing values are specified,
13555  * the specified minimum size implies a minimum spacing and
13556  * the specified maximum spacing implies a maximum size.
13557  * <p>
13558  * If the implied minimum spacing is greater than or equal to the specified
13559  * maximum spacing, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed spacing
13560  * equal to the implied minimum spacing.
13561  * </li>
13562  * 
13563  * <li>
13564  * When only the maximum size and the minimum spacing values are specified,
13565  * the specified maximum size implies a maximum spacing and
13566  * the specified minimum spacing implies a minimum size.
13567  * <p>
13568  * If the implied minimum size is greater than or equal to the specified
13569  * maximum size, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed size
13570  * equal to the implied minimum size.
13571  * </li>
13572  * </ul>
13573  * </li>
13574  * </ul>
13575  * </li>
13576  * </ul>
13577  * <p>
13578  * See other band-control options:
13579  * {@link #bandSpacing},
13580  * {@link #bandSizeMin},
13581  * {@link #bandSizeMax},
13582  * {@link #bandSpacingMin},
13583  * {@link #bandSpacingMax} and,
13584  * for charts that give it representation,
13585  * {@link #bandSizeRatio}.
13586  * 
13587  * @type number
13588  * @category Discrete > Layout
13589  */
13590 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSize = undefined;

13595  * <p>
13596  * See {@link #bandSize} for information on the band layout algorithm.

13686 /**

13688  * <p>
13689  * The value is converted using the
13690  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of

13713  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
13714  * </li>
13715  * </ul>

13723  * <tt>auto</tt>,
13724  * clipping is activated in the plot panel.

13726  * <p>
13727  * This property takes precedence over the property 
13728  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>.
13729  * 
13730  * @type number|string|Date
13731  * @category Continuous > Scale
13732  */

13784  * <p>

13806 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.originIsZero = undefined;
13807 /**
13808  * The 
13809  * <i>desired</i> number of major ticks.
13810  * <p>
13811  * A positive integer, possibly infinite.
13812  * <p>
13813  * Attention: This option is ignored when {@link #tickUnit} is specified!
13814  * <p>
13815  * Depending on
13816  * the domain values extent,
13817  * the labels' font size,
13818  * the available space,
13819  * the axis' orientation,
13820  * and the minimum label spacing
13821  * (given by {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}),
13822  * a maximum number of ticks is implied.
13823  * <p>
13824  * The value of 
13825  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> is clamped to this layout imposed maximum.
13826  * <p>
13827  * When specified and finite,
13828  * the tick calculation algorithm chooses,
13829  * amongst possible tick units,
13830  * the one that results in a number of ticks
13831  * that is 
13832  * <b>closest</b> to the specified 
13833  * <b>desired</b> value.
13834  * <p>
13835  * When specified and infinite (
13836  * <tt>Infinity</tt>),
13837  * the layout imposed maximum is used instead.
13838  * 
13839  * <p>
13840  * 
13841  * <b>The minimum tick count</b>
13842  * </p>
13843  * <p>
13844  * This actually depends on the value of {@link #domainRoundMode}.
13845  * 
13846  * <ul>
13847  * 
13848  * <li>
13849  * 
13850  * <p>
13851  * <b>
13852  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Tick}</b></p>
13853  * <p>
13854  * For tick counts greater than two or three, the algorithm strives to satisfy the user's desire!
13855  * <p>
13856  * However,
13857  * the algorithm always generates at least two or three ticks,
13858  * ignoring both 
13859  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> and 
13860  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>,
13861  * if needed.
13862  * <p>
13863  * At least three ticks are generated for numeric domains having both negative and positive data.
13864  * There are also temporal domain cases where a minimum of three ticks are generated.
13865  * <p>
13866  * When the labels of these ticks really overlap,
13867  * one of the labels is kept visible and the other(s) is hidden.
13868  * <p>
13869  * This behavior ensures that, unless it is really impossible to do so,
13870  * the axis serves one of its main purposes - allowing to translate visual lengths.
13871  * <p>
13872  * When three tick labels overlap,
13873  * the middle label is kept visible and the end labels are hidden.
13874  * <p>
13875  * When two tick labels overlap,
13876  * one of the labels
13877  * — the one with tick value 
13878  * <tt>0</tt>, if any, or the first one, if none —
13879  * is kept visible and the other is hidden.
13880  * </li>
13881  * 
13882  * <li>
13883  * 
13884  * <p>
13885  * <b>
13886  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is
13887  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#None} or
13888  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Nice}</b></p>
13889  * <p>
13890  * The algorithm always generates at least one tick.
13891  * </li>
13892  * </ul>
13893  * <p>
13894  * Specifying a value of 
13895  * <tt>1</tt> results in the minimum possible tick count.
13896  * 
13897  * <p>
13898  * 
13899  * <b>Domain type specifics</b>
13900  * </p>
13901  * 
13902  * <ul>
13903  * 
13904  * <li>
13905  * 
13906  * <b>Numeric</b>
13907  * <p>
13908  * When unspecified, the default value is 
13909  * <tt>Infinity</tt>.
13910  * </li>
13911  * 
13912  * <li>
13913  * 
13914  * <b>Temporal</b>
13915  * <p>
13916  * The value must be less than or equal to 
13917  * <tt>10</tt>.
13918  * <p>
13919  * When unspecified, the default value is 
13920  * <tt>5</tt>.
13921  * </li>
13922  * </ul>
13923  * <p>
13924  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
13925  * 
13926  * @type number
13927  * @category Continuous > Style
13928  */
13929 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.desiredTickCount = undefined;
13930 /**
13931  * Indicates if minor ticks are shown between major ticks (applies to continuous axes).
13932  * 
13933  * @type boolean
13934  * @default true
13935  * @category Continuous > Style
13936  */
13937 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.minorTicks = undefined;
13938 /**
13939  * The ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
13940  * <p>
13941  * When a number, it must be a non-negative, finite, integer.
13942  * 
13943  * <ul>
13944  * 
13945  * <li>
13946  * 
13947  * <b>Numeric axis</b>
13948  * <p>
13949  * Specified values are rounded down to one of the standard precisions:
13950  * a number that is an integer power of 10,
13951  * multiplied by 1, 2 or 5 (e.g. 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, ...).
13952  * </li>
13953  * 
13954  * <li>
13955  * 
13956  * <b>Temporal axis</b>
13957  * <p>
13958  * When a number or numeric string is specified,
13959  * it is a the number of milliseconds of a duration.
13960  * <p>
13961  * It is rounded down to an integer and used directly.
13962  * By default, the corresponding tick format will be the one of the
13963  * greatest standard unit that is below the specified value.
13964  * <p>
13965  * When a (non-numeric) string is specified,
13966  * it should be the code of a standard precision,
13967  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple
13968  * (e.g. 
13969  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days).
13970  * <p>
13971  * The standard time precision codes are:
13972  * 
13973  * <ul>
13974  * 
13975  * <li>'y' - Year - 
13976  * <tt>31536e6</tt> ms</li>
13977  * 
13978  * <li>'m' - Month - 
13979  * <tt>2592e6</tt> ms</li>
13980  * 
13981  * <li>'w' - Week - 
13982  * <tt>6048e5</tt> ms</li>
13983  * 
13984  * <li>'d' - Day - 
13985  * <tt>864e5</tt> ms</li>
13986  * 
13987  * <li>'h' - Hour - 
13988  * <tt>36e5</tt> ms</li>
13989  * 
13990  * <li>'M' - Minute - 
13991  * <tt>6e4</tt> ms</li>
13992  * 
13993  * <li>'s' - Second - 
13994  * <tt>1e3</tt> ms</li>
13995  * 
13996  * <li>'ms' - Millisecond - 
13997  * <tt>1</tt> ms</li>
13998  * </ul>
13999  * <p>
14000  * This option should be used instead of the now deprecated
14001  * {@link pvc.options.marks.QuantitativeScaleExtensionPoint#dateTickPrecision}
14002  * extension point, via {@link #extensionPoints} and then 
14003  * <i>scale</i>.
14004  * </li>
14005  * </ul>
14006  * 
14007  * <b>Relations with other options</b>
14008  * <p>
14009  * When both {@link #tickUnitMin} and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
14010  * and the former is greater than or equal to the later,
14011  * then it is as if 
14012  * <i>tickUnit</i> had been specified with the value of 
14013  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>.
14014  * <p>
14015  * When both 
14016  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMin} are specified,
14017  * and 
14018  * <i>tickUnit</i> is less than 
14019  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>,
14020  * then the value of 
14021  * <i>tickUnitMin</i> is used instead.
14022  * <p>
14023  * When both 
14024  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
14025  * and 
14026  * <i>tickUnit</i> is greater than 
14027  * <i>tickUnitMax</i>,
14028  * then the value of 
14029  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> is used instead.
14030  * <p>
14031  * When specified or implied,
14032  * both {@link #desiredTickCount} and 
14033  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>
14034  * are ignored.
14035  * <p>
14036  * See related axis options:
14037  * {@link #tickUnitMin},
14038  * {@link #tickUnitMax},
14039  * {@link #domainRoundMode},
14040  * {@link #desiredTickCount} and
14041  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}.
14042  * <p>
14043  * For numeric axes, see also
14044  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin} and
14045  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax}.
14046  * 
14047  * @type number|string
14048  * @category Continuous > Style
14049  */
14050 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnit = undefined;
14051 /**
14052  * The maximum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
14053  * <p>
14054  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by at most a certain value.
14055  * For example,
14056  * a value of 
14057  * <tt>100</tt> ensures that the unit 
14058  * <tt>200</tt> will not be used,
14059  * and of 
14060  * <tt>'3m'</tt> that a year or semester unit will not be used.
14061  * <p>
14062  * As another example,
14063  * to ensure that the tick unit is less than 
14064  * <tt>1000</tt>,
14065  * either
14066  * specify a 
14067  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> of 
14068  * <tt>900</tt>, or, maybe better,
14069  * specify a {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax} of 
14070  * <tt>2</tt>.
14071  * <p>
14072  * When a number, it must be a positive integer.
14073  * <p>
14074  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option.
14075  * <p>
14076  * For numeric axes,
14077  * the value of this option is combined with that of
14078  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax},
14079  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14080  * <p>
14081  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14082  * 
14083  * @type number|string
14084  * @default Infinity
14085  * @category Continuous > Style
14086  */
14087 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMax = undefined;
14088 /**
14089  * The minimum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
14090  * <p>
14091  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by a minimum value.
14092  * For example, a value of 
14093  * <tt>1</tt> ensures ticks are integers,
14094  * and of 
14095  * <tt>'d'</tt>, that hour ticks are not used.
14096  * <p>
14097  * When a number, it must be a non-negative finite integer.
14098  * <p>
14099  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option,
14100  * with the exception that rounding to a standard precision is performed 
14101  * <i>up</i>.
14102  * <p>
14103  * For numeric axes,
14104  * the value of this option is combined with that of
14105  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin},
14106  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14107  * <p>
14108  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14109  * 
14110  * @type number|string
14111  * @default 0
14112  * @category Continuous > Style
14113  */
14114 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMin = undefined;
14115 /**
14116  * The axis' domain rounding mode (applies to continuous axes).
14117  * 
14118  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode
14119  * @default 'tick'
14120  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
14121  */
14122 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.domainRoundMode = undefined;
14123 /**
14124  * The maximum exponent of 
14125  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
14126  * <p>
14127  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
14128  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14129  * <p>
14130  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
14131  * <i>step</i> value.
14132  * A step value is a certain power of 
14133  * <tt>10</tt>,
14134  * possibly multiplied by 
14135  * <tt>2</tt> or 
14136  * <tt>5</tt>.
14137  * <p>
14138  * For example, 
14139  * for a chosen exponent of 
14140  * <tt>4</tt>,
14141  * the corresponding power of 
14142  * <tt>10</tt> is 
14143  * <tt>10^4=10000</tt> and
14144  * the generated ticks could be:
14145  * 
14146  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14147  * <tt>10000</tt>, 
14148  * <tt>20000</tt>, ...
14149  * <p>
14150  * If the multiplier 
14151  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
14152  * those ticks would instead be:
14153  * 
14154  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14155  * <tt>50000</tt>, 
14156  * <tt>100000</tt>, ...
14157  * <p>
14158  * Setting this property allows imposing a limit on 
14159  * the size of numbers chosen to separate ticks,
14160  * which may be seen as imposing a minimum granularity 
14161  * on the generated tick values.
14162  * <p>
14163  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14164  * 
14165  * @type number
14166  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
14167  */
14168 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMax = undefined;
14169 /**
14170  * The minimum exponent of 
14171  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
14172  * <p>
14173  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
14174  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
14175  * <p>
14176  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
14177  * <i>step</i> value.
14178  * A step value is a certain power of 
14179  * <tt>10</tt>,
14180  * possibly multiplied by 
14181  * <tt>2</tt> or 
14182  * <tt>5</tt>.
14183  * <p>
14184  * For example, 
14185  * for a chosen exponent of 
14186  * <tt>2</tt>,
14187  * the corresponding power of 
14188  * <tt>10</tt> is 
14189  * <tt>10^2=100</tt> and
14190  * the generated ticks could be:
14191  * 
14192  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14193  * <tt>100</tt>, 
14194  * <tt>200</tt>, ...
14195  * <p>
14196  * If the multiplier 
14197  * <tt>2</tt> was chosen, 
14198  * those ticks would instead be:
14199  * 
14200  * <tt>0</tt>, 
14201  * <tt>200</tt>, 
14202  * <tt>400</tt>, ...
14203  * <p>
14204  * Setting this property to 
14205  * <tt>2</tt> would ensure 
14206  * that generated ticks would be separated by the step values
14207  * 
14208  * <tt>100</tt>, 
14209  * <tt>200</tt> or 
14210  * <tt>500</tt>,
14211  * or by steps whose corresponding exponent is 
14212  * bigger than 
14213  * <tt>2</tt>, 
14214  * like: 
14215  * <tt>1000</tt>, 
14216  * <tt>2000</tt> or 
14217  * <tt>5000</tt>.
14218  * <p>
14219  * A more typical use case is ensuring that generated ticks are integers.
14220  * A value of 
14221  * <tt>tickExponentMin</tt> of 
14222  * <tt>0</tt> would accomplish that.
14223  * <p>
14224  * Generally, 
14225  * to impose a maximum number of decimal places on the generated ticks, 
14226  * a negative number can be specified.
14227  * For example, the value 
14228  * <tt>-1</tt> could generate the ticks:
14229  * 
14230  * <tt>0.1</tt>, 
14231  * <tt>0.2</tt>, 
14232  * <tt>0.3</tt>, ...
14233  * If the multiplier 
14234  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
14235  * those ticks would instead be:
14236  * 
14237  * <tt>0.5</tt>, 
14238  * <tt>1.0</tt>, 
14239  * <tt>1.5</tt>, ...
14240  * It could not generate ticks 
14241  * with more that one decimal place.
14242  * <p>
14243  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
14244  * 
14245  * @type number
14246  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
14247  */
14248 pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMin = undefined;

14467 pvc.options.axes.DiscreteCartesianAxis.prototype.tooltipFormat = function(){};
14468 /**
14469  * The size, in pixels, of the bands used to represent the discrete domain values (applies to discrete axes).
14470  * <p>
14471  * A non-negative number.
14472  * 
14473  * <p>
14474  * 
14475  * <b>In multi-charts</b>
14476  * <p>
14477  * The current layout algorithm used by multi-charts does not support
14478  * minimum, fixed or maximum sizes in small charts.
14479  * As such, the simples band size ratio model always needs to be used.
14480  * <p>
14481  * The minimum, fixed and maximum sizes and spacings are used to determine an
14482  * equivalent or best-possible band size ratio.
14483  * </p>
14484  * 
14485  * <p>
14486  * 
14487  * <b>Band Size, Spacing, Ratio and Step</b>
14488  * <p>
14489  * The band layout arranges bands and space in the following way.
14490  * Taking 
14491  * <i>B</i> to represent 
14492  * <i>bandSize</i>,
14493  * 
14494  * <i>E</i> to represent {@link #bandSpacing} and
14495  * 
14496  * <i>e</i> to be 
14497  * <tt>E/2</tt>,
14498  * bands and space will follow the pattern:
14499  * 
14500  * <tt>eBe</tt>, 
14501  * <tt>eBEBe</tt>, 
14502  * <tt>eBEBEBe</tt>, ...
14503  * <p>
14504  * For a given pair of 
14505  * <i>B</i> and 
14506  * <i>E</i>, each discrete category will occupy a space given by
14507  * the 
14508  * <i>step</i>, 
14509  * <i>S</i>:
14510  * <br></br>
14511  * 
14512  * <i>S = B + E</i>.
14513  * <p>
14514  * Given the number of discrete categories, a cartesian panel (axis or plot) will have
14515  * corresponding fixed or minimum and maximum sizes.
14516  * <p>
14517  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, R, is used, in under-constrained cases,
14518  * to relate 
14519  * <i>B</i> and 
14520  * <i>E</i>:
14521  * <br></br>
14522  * 
14523  * <i>B = R * S</i>
14524  * </p>
14525  * 
14526  * <p>
14527  * 
14528  * <b>Impact on chart size</b>
14529  * <p>
14530  * If the chart size along the axis' dimension
14531  * is such that the available space is less than the
14532  * determined fixed or minimum size,
14533  * then the chart will grow as much as needed to accommodate the fixed or minimum size,
14534  * along that dimension.
14535  * <p>
14536  * If, on the contrary, the chart size along the axis' dimension
14537  * is greater than the determined fixed or maximum size,
14538  * the plot and axis content will be centered in the available space.
14539  * </p>
14540  * 
14541  * <p>
14542  * 
14543  * <b>Option values harmonization</b>
14544  * <p>
14545  * When both {@link #bandSizeMax} and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
14546  * and {@link #bandSizeMax} is less than or equal to 
14547  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
14548  * then {@link #bandSize} is set to the the minimum value.
14549  * <p>
14550  * When both 
14551  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSizeMin} are specified,
14552  * and 
14553  * <i>bandSize</i> is less than 
14554  * <i>bandSizeMin</i>,
14555  * then the minimum value is used instead.
14556  * <p>
14557  * When both 
14558  * <i>bandSpacing</i> and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
14559  * and 
14560  * <i>bandSpacing</i> is less than 
14561  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
14562  * then the minimum value is used instead.
14563  * <p>
14564  * When both {@link #bandSpacingMax} and {@link #bandSpacingMin} are specified,
14565  * and {@link #bandSpacingMax} is less than or equal to 
14566  * <i>bandSpacingMin</i>,
14567  * then {@link #bandSpacing} is set to the the minimum value.
14568  * </p>
14569  * 
14570  * <p>
14571  * 
14572  * <b>The algorithm</b>
14573  * <p>
14574  * The options you specify should just behave as you'd expected them to.
14575  * At least, after thinking about them for a while.
14576  * <p>
14577  * If doubts remain on which options and values should be specified,
14578  * or on why the specified options are behaving in a certain way,
14579  * you can follow this explanation of the band layout algorithm.
14580  * </p>
14581  * 
14582  * <ul>
14583  * 
14584  * <li>
14585  * When both 
14586  * <i>bandSize</i> and {@link #bandSpacing} are specified, the layout is 
14587  * <b>fixed</b>.
14588  * <p>
14589  * When they both have the value 
14590  * <tt>0</tt>, then the layout is reevaluated as if they had not been specified.
14591  * <p>
14592  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
14593  * </li>
14594  * 
14595  * <li>
14596  * When one and only one of 
14597  * <i>bandSize</i> or {@link #bandSpacing} is specified,
14598  * the layout is 
14599  * <b>partially fixed</b>.
14600  * <p>
14601  * For the variable option, size or spacing,
14602  * any specified minimum and/or maximum options are still considered.
14603  * <p>
14604  * This configuration does not define a fixed step size,
14605  * but instead constrains the range of step size values.
14606  * <p>
14607  * The option {@link #bandSizeRatio} is ignored.
14608  * </li>
14609  * 
14610  * <li>
14611  * When neither 
14612  * <i>bandSize</i> nor {@link #bandSpacing} are specified,
14613  * the layout is 
14614  * <b>strictly variable</b>.
14615  * <p>
14616  * There are several cases:
14617  * 
14618  * <ul>
14619  * 
14620  * <li>
14621  * When none of the minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
14622  * the size and spacing are governed solely by the {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
14623  * <i>R</i>.
14624  * <p>
14625  * This is the way the band layout used to behave,
14626  * before the existence of the fixed, minimum and maximum options.
14627  * <p>
14628  * Small-charts continue to behave this way,
14629  * although with a band size ratio that is determined from the
14630  * the other specified options.
14631  * <p>
14632  * The half-line 
14633  * <i>(E,B)</i> departs from 
14634  * <i>(0,0)</i>
14635  * and goes on indefinitely with a slope given by 
14636  * <i>R</i>: 
14637  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
14638  * </li>
14639  * 
14640  * <li>
14641  * 
14642  * <p>
14643  * When minimum and maximum values, of both size and spacing, are specified,
14644  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
14645  * line segment 
14646  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
14647  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i> to point 
14648  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
14649  * </p>
14650  * </li>
14651  * 
14652  * <li>
14653  * 
14654  * <p>
14655  * When only the minimum size and spacing values are specified,
14656  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
14657  * line segment 
14658  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
14659  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
14660  * <i>(Emin,Bmin)</i>.
14661  * </p>
14662  * </li>
14663  * 
14664  * <li>
14665  * 
14666  * <p>
14667  * When only the maximum size and spacing values are specified,
14668  * the size and spacing are constrained to belong to the
14669  * line segment 
14670  * <i>(E,B)</i>, that goes from point 
14671  * <i>(0,0)</i> to point 
14672  * <i>(Emax,Bmax)</i>.
14673  * </p>
14674  * </li>
14675  * 
14676  * <li>
14677  * In all the following mixed and under-constrained cases,
14678  * option {@link #bandSizeRatio}, 
14679  * <i>R</i>, is taken into account.
14680  * <p>
14681  * The size and spacing are constrained to belong to the the line 
14682  * <i>(E,B)</i> that
14683  * passes through 
14684  * <i>(0,0)</i> and has a slope
14685  * given by 
14686  * <i>R</i>: 
14687  * <i>E = (1/R - 1) * B</i>.
14688  * <p>
14689  * Again, a few more cases:
14690  * 
14691  * <ul>
14692  * 
14693  * <li>
14694  * 
14695  * <p>
14696  * When only the minimum and maximum size values are specified,
14697  * the corresponding spacing values are implied.
14698  * </p>
14699  * </li>
14700  * 
14701  * <li>
14702  * 
14703  * <p>
14704  * When only the minimum and maximum spacing values are specified,
14705  * the corresponding size values are implied.
14706  * </p>
14707  * </li>
14708  * 
14709  * <li>
14710  * When only the minimum size and the maximum spacing values are specified,
14711  * the specified minimum size implies a minimum spacing and
14712  * the specified maximum spacing implies a maximum size.
14713  * <p>
14714  * If the implied minimum spacing is greater than or equal to the specified
14715  * maximum spacing, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed spacing
14716  * equal to the implied minimum spacing.
14717  * </li>
14718  * 
14719  * <li>
14720  * When only the maximum size and the minimum spacing values are specified,
14721  * the specified maximum size implies a maximum spacing and
14722  * the specified minimum spacing implies a minimum size.
14723  * <p>
14724  * If the implied minimum size is greater than or equal to the specified
14725  * maximum size, the algorithm is reevaluated using a fixed size
14726  * equal to the implied minimum size.
14727  * </li>
14728  * </ul>
14729  * </li>
14730  * </ul>
14731  * </li>
14732  * </ul>
14733  * <p>
14734  * See other band-control options:
14735  * {@link #bandSpacing},
14736  * {@link #bandSizeMin},
14737  * {@link #bandSizeMax},
14738  * {@link #bandSpacingMin},
14739  * {@link #bandSpacingMax} and,
14740  * for charts that give it representation,
14741  * {@link #bandSizeRatio}.
14742  * 
14743  * @type number
14744  * @category Discrete > Layout
14745  */
14746 pvc.options.axes.DiscreteCartesianAxis.prototype.bandSize = undefined;

15099 /**
15100  * The fixed maximum domain value that the axis will show (applies to continuous axes).
15101  * <p>
15102  * The value is converted using the
15103  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter} of
15104  * the first dimension of the first role bound to the axis.
15105  * <p>
15106  * For example, if the base axis shows the 
15107  * <i>category</i> dimension,
15108  * and the dimension is configured as type Date,
15109  * and it uses the default converter, then it accepts:
15110  *

15121  * <tt>Date</tt>, which are accepted as is</li>
15122  *

15125  * in a format defined by the dimension's
15126  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#rawFormat}.
15127  * </li>
15128  * </ul>
15129  * <p>

15131  * maximum value of the data.

15134  * and {@link pvc.options.charts.CartesianChart#leafContentOverflow}
15135  * is set to 
15136  * <tt>auto</tt>,
15137  * clipping is activated in the plot panel.
15138  * Elements that are drawn beyond its area are clipped.
15139  * <p>
15140  * This property takes precedence over the property 
15141  * <tt>originIsZero</tt>.
15142  * 
15143  * @type number|string|Date
15144  * @category Continuous > Scale
15145  */

15195 /**
