15197  * <p>
15198  * The properties
15199  * 
15200  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> and
15201  * 
15202  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> have precedence over this one.
15203  * If this property is 
15204  * <tt>true</tt>
15205  * and respecting it would require changing
15206  * the minimum value,
15207  * but the option 
15208  * <tt>fixedMin</tt> is also specified,
15209  * then this property is ignored.
15210  * The same would apply if
15211  * it were required to change
15212  * the maximum value,
15213  * but the property 
15214  * <tt>fixedMax</tt> was also specified.
15215  * 
15216  * @type boolean
15217  * @category Continuous > Scale
15218  */
15219 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.originIsZero = undefined;
15220 /**
15221  * The 
15222  * <i>desired</i> number of major ticks.
15223  * <p>
15224  * A positive integer, possibly infinite.
15225  * <p>
15226  * Attention: This option is ignored when {@link #tickUnit} is specified!
15227  * <p>
15228  * Depending on
15229  * the domain values extent,
15230  * the labels' font size,
15231  * the available space,
15232  * the axis' orientation,
15233  * and the minimum label spacing
15234  * (given by {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}),
15235  * a maximum number of ticks is implied.
15236  * <p>
15237  * The value of 
15238  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> is clamped to this layout imposed maximum.
15239  * <p>
15240  * When specified and finite,
15241  * the tick calculation algorithm chooses,
15242  * amongst possible tick units,
15243  * the one that results in a number of ticks
15244  * that is 
15245  * <b>closest</b> to the specified 
15246  * <b>desired</b> value.
15247  * <p>
15248  * When specified and infinite (
15249  * <tt>Infinity</tt>),
15250  * the layout imposed maximum is used instead.
15251  * 
15252  * <p>
15253  * 
15254  * <b>The minimum tick count</b>
15255  * </p>
15256  * <p>
15257  * This actually depends on the value of {@link #domainRoundMode}.
15258  * 
15259  * <ul>
15260  * 
15261  * <li>
15262  * 
15263  * <p>
15264  * <b>
15265  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Tick}</b></p>
15266  * <p>
15267  * For tick counts greater than two or three, the algorithm strives to satisfy the user's desire!
15268  * <p>
15269  * However,
15270  * the algorithm always generates at least two or three ticks,
15271  * ignoring both 
15272  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> and 
15273  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>,
15274  * if needed.
15275  * <p>
15276  * At least three ticks are generated for numeric domains having both negative and positive data.
15277  * There are also temporal domain cases where a minimum of three ticks are generated.
15278  * <p>
15279  * When the labels of these ticks really overlap,
15280  * one of the labels is kept visible and the other(s) is hidden.
15281  * <p>
15282  * This behavior ensures that, unless it is really impossible to do so,
15283  * the axis serves one of its main purposes - allowing to translate visual lengths.
15284  * <p>
15285  * When three tick labels overlap,
15286  * the middle label is kept visible and the end labels are hidden.
15287  * <p>
15288  * When two tick labels overlap,
15289  * one of the labels
15290  * — the one with tick value 
15291  * <tt>0</tt>, if any, or the first one, if none —
15292  * is kept visible and the other is hidden.
15293  * </li>
15294  * 
15295  * <li>
15296  * 
15297  * <p>
15298  * <b>
15299  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is
15300  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#None} or
15301  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Nice}</b></p>
15302  * <p>
15303  * The algorithm always generates at least one tick.
15304  * </li>
15305  * </ul>
15306  * <p>
15307  * Specifying a value of 
15308  * <tt>1</tt> results in the minimum possible tick count.
15309  * 
15310  * <p>
15311  * 
15312  * <b>Domain type specifics</b>
15313  * </p>
15314  * 
15315  * <ul>
15316  * 
15317  * <li>
15318  * 
15319  * <b>Numeric</b>
15320  * <p>
15321  * When unspecified, the default value is 
15322  * <tt>Infinity</tt>.
15323  * </li>
15324  * 
15325  * <li>
15326  * 
15327  * <b>Temporal</b>
15328  * <p>
15329  * The value must be less than or equal to 
15330  * <tt>10</tt>.
15331  * <p>
15332  * When unspecified, the default value is 
15333  * <tt>5</tt>.
15334  * </li>
15335  * </ul>
15336  * <p>
15337  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
15338  * 
15339  * @type number
15340  * @category Continuous > Style
15341  */
15342 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.desiredTickCount = undefined;
15343 /**
15344  * Indicates if minor ticks are shown between major ticks (applies to continuous axes).
15345  * 
15346  * @type boolean
15347  * @default true
15348  * @category Continuous > Style
15349  */
15350 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.minorTicks = undefined;
15351 /**
15352  * The ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
15353  * <p>
15354  * When a number, it must be a non-negative, finite, integer.
15355  * 
15356  * <ul>
15357  * 
15358  * <li>
15359  * 
15360  * <b>Numeric axis</b>
15361  * <p>
15362  * Specified values are rounded down to one of the standard precisions:
15363  * a number that is an integer power of 10,
15364  * multiplied by 1, 2 or 5 (e.g. 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, ...).
15365  * </li>
15366  * 
15367  * <li>
15368  * 
15369  * <b>Temporal axis</b>
15370  * <p>
15371  * When a number or numeric string is specified,
15372  * it is a the number of milliseconds of a duration.
15373  * <p>
15374  * It is rounded down to an integer and used directly.
15375  * By default, the corresponding tick format will be the one of the
15376  * greatest standard unit that is below the specified value.
15377  * <p>
15378  * When a (non-numeric) string is specified,
15379  * it should be the code of a standard precision,
15380  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple
15381  * (e.g. 
15382  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days).
15383  * <p>
15384  * The standard time precision codes are:
15385  * 
15386  * <ul>
15387  * 
15388  * <li>'y' - Year - 
15389  * <tt>31536e6</tt> ms</li>
15390  * 
15391  * <li>'m' - Month - 
15392  * <tt>2592e6</tt> ms</li>
15393  * 
15394  * <li>'w' - Week - 
15395  * <tt>6048e5</tt> ms</li>
15396  * 
15397  * <li>'d' - Day - 
15398  * <tt>864e5</tt> ms</li>
15399  * 
15400  * <li>'h' - Hour - 
15401  * <tt>36e5</tt> ms</li>
15402  * 
15403  * <li>'M' - Minute - 
15404  * <tt>6e4</tt> ms</li>
15405  * 
15406  * <li>'s' - Second - 
15407  * <tt>1e3</tt> ms</li>
15408  * 
15409  * <li>'ms' - Millisecond - 
15410  * <tt>1</tt> ms</li>
15411  * </ul>
15412  * <p>
15413  * This option should be used instead of the now deprecated
15414  * {@link pvc.options.marks.QuantitativeScaleExtensionPoint#dateTickPrecision}
15415  * extension point, via {@link #extensionPoints} and then 
15416  * <i>scale</i>.
15417  * </li>
15418  * </ul>
15419  * 
15420  * <b>Relations with other options</b>
15421  * <p>
15422  * When both {@link #tickUnitMin} and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
15423  * and the former is greater than or equal to the later,
15424  * then it is as if 
15425  * <i>tickUnit</i> had been specified with the value of 
15426  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>.
15427  * <p>
15428  * When both 
15429  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMin} are specified,
15430  * and 
15431  * <i>tickUnit</i> is less than 
15432  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>,
15433  * then the value of 
15434  * <i>tickUnitMin</i> is used instead.
15435  * <p>
15436  * When both 
15437  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
15438  * and 
15439  * <i>tickUnit</i> is greater than 
15440  * <i>tickUnitMax</i>,
15441  * then the value of 
15442  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> is used instead.
15443  * <p>
15444  * When specified or implied,
15445  * both {@link #desiredTickCount} and 
15446  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>
15447  * are ignored.
15448  * <p>
15449  * See related axis options:
15450  * {@link #tickUnitMin},
15451  * {@link #tickUnitMax},
15452  * {@link #domainRoundMode},
15453  * {@link #desiredTickCount} and
15454  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}.
15455  * <p>
15456  * For numeric axes, see also
15457  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin} and
15458  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax}.
15459  * 
15460  * @type number|string
15461  * @category Continuous > Style
15462  */
15463 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnit = undefined;
15464 /**
15465  * The maximum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
15466  * <p>
15467  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by at most a certain value.
15468  * For example,
15469  * a value of 
15470  * <tt>100</tt> ensures that the unit 
15471  * <tt>200</tt> will not be used,
15472  * and of 
15473  * <tt>'3m'</tt> that a year or semester unit will not be used.
15474  * <p>
15475  * As another example,
15476  * to ensure that the tick unit is less than 
15477  * <tt>1000</tt>,
15478  * either
15479  * specify a 
15480  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> of 
15481  * <tt>900</tt>, or, maybe better,
15482  * specify a {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax} of 
15483  * <tt>2</tt>.
15484  * <p>
15485  * When a number, it must be a positive integer.
15486  * <p>
15487  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option.
15488  * <p>
15489  * For numeric axes,
15490  * the value of this option is combined with that of
15491  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax},
15492  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
15493  * <p>
15494  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
15495  * 
15496  * @type number|string
15497  * @default Infinity
15498  * @category Continuous > Style
15499  */
15500 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMax = undefined;
15501 /**
15502  * The minimum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
15503  * <p>
15504  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by a minimum value.
15505  * For example, a value of 
15506  * <tt>1</tt> ensures ticks are integers,
15507  * and of 
15508  * <tt>'d'</tt>, that hour ticks are not used.
15509  * <p>
15510  * When a number, it must be a non-negative finite integer.
15511  * <p>
15512  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option,
15513  * with the exception that rounding to a standard precision is performed 
15514  * <i>up</i>.
15515  * <p>
15516  * For numeric axes,
15517  * the value of this option is combined with that of
15518  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin},
15519  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
15520  * <p>
15521  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
15522  * 
15523  * @type number|string
15524  * @default 0
15525  * @category Continuous > Style
15526  */
15527 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMin = undefined;
15528 /**
15529  * The axis' domain rounding mode (applies to continuous axes).
15530  * 
15531  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode
15532  * @default 'tick'
15533  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
15534  */
15535 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.domainRoundMode = undefined;
15536 /**
15537  * The maximum exponent of 
15538  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
15539  * <p>
15540  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
15541  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
15542  * <p>
15543  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
15544  * <i>step</i> value.
15545  * A step value is a certain power of 
15546  * <tt>10</tt>,
15547  * possibly multiplied by 
15548  * <tt>2</tt> or 
15549  * <tt>5</tt>.
15550  * <p>
15551  * For example, 
15552  * for a chosen exponent of 
15553  * <tt>4</tt>,
15554  * the corresponding power of 
15555  * <tt>10</tt> is 
15556  * <tt>10^4=10000</tt> and
15557  * the generated ticks could be:
15558  * 
15559  * <tt>0</tt>, 
15560  * <tt>10000</tt>, 
15561  * <tt>20000</tt>, ...
15562  * <p>
15563  * If the multiplier 
15564  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
15565  * those ticks would instead be:
15566  * 
15567  * <tt>0</tt>, 
15568  * <tt>50000</tt>, 
15569  * <tt>100000</tt>, ...
15570  * <p>
15571  * Setting this property allows imposing a limit on 
15572  * the size of numbers chosen to separate ticks,
15573  * which may be seen as imposing a minimum granularity 
15574  * on the generated tick values.
15575  * <p>
15576  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
15577  * 
15578  * @type number
15579  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
15580  */
15581 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMax = undefined;
15582 /**
15583  * The minimum exponent of 
15584  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
15585  * <p>
15586  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
15587  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
15588  * <p>
15589  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
15590  * <i>step</i> value.
15591  * A step value is a certain power of 
15592  * <tt>10</tt>,
15593  * possibly multiplied by 
15594  * <tt>2</tt> or 
15595  * <tt>5</tt>.
15596  * <p>
15597  * For example, 
15598  * for a chosen exponent of 
15599  * <tt>2</tt>,
15600  * the corresponding power of 
15601  * <tt>10</tt> is 
15602  * <tt>10^2=100</tt> and
15603  * the generated ticks could be:
15604  * 
15605  * <tt>0</tt>, 
15606  * <tt>100</tt>, 
15607  * <tt>200</tt>, ...
15608  * <p>
15609  * If the multiplier 
15610  * <tt>2</tt> was chosen, 
15611  * those ticks would instead be:
15612  * 
15613  * <tt>0</tt>, 
15614  * <tt>200</tt>, 
15615  * <tt>400</tt>, ...
15616  * <p>
15617  * Setting this property to 
15618  * <tt>2</tt> would ensure 
15619  * that generated ticks would be separated by the step values
15620  * 
15621  * <tt>100</tt>, 
15622  * <tt>200</tt> or 
15623  * <tt>500</tt>,
15624  * or by steps whose corresponding exponent is 
15625  * bigger than 
15626  * <tt>2</tt>, 
15627  * like: 
15628  * <tt>1000</tt>, 
15629  * <tt>2000</tt> or 
15630  * <tt>5000</tt>.
15631  * <p>
15632  * A more typical use case is ensuring that generated ticks are integers.
15633  * A value of 
15634  * <tt>tickExponentMin</tt> of 
15635  * <tt>0</tt> would accomplish that.
15636  * <p>
15637  * Generally, 
15638  * to impose a maximum number of decimal places on the generated ticks, 
15639  * a negative number can be specified.
15640  * For example, the value 
15641  * <tt>-1</tt> could generate the ticks:
15642  * 
15643  * <tt>0.1</tt>, 
15644  * <tt>0.2</tt>, 
15645  * <tt>0.3</tt>, ...
15646  * If the multiplier 
15647  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
15648  * those ticks would instead be:
15649  * 
15650  * <tt>0.5</tt>, 
15651  * <tt>1.0</tt>, 
15652  * <tt>1.5</tt>, ...
15653  * It could not generate ticks 
15654  * with more that one decimal place.
15655  * <p>
15656  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
15657  * 
15658  * @type number
15659  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
15660  */
15661 pvc.options.axes.AnyContinuousCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMin = undefined;

15945 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.originIsZero = undefined;
15946 /**
15947  * The 
15948  * <i>desired</i> number of major ticks.
15949  * <p>
15950  * A positive integer, possibly infinite.
15951  * <p>
15952  * Attention: This option is ignored when {@link #tickUnit} is specified!
15953  * <p>
15954  * Depending on
15955  * the domain values extent,
15956  * the labels' font size,
15957  * the available space,
15958  * the axis' orientation,
15959  * and the minimum label spacing
15960  * (given by {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}),
15961  * a maximum number of ticks is implied.
15962  * <p>
15963  * The value of 
15964  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> is clamped to this layout imposed maximum.
15965  * <p>
15966  * When specified and finite,
15967  * the tick calculation algorithm chooses,
15968  * amongst possible tick units,
15969  * the one that results in a number of ticks
15970  * that is 
15971  * <b>closest</b> to the specified 
15972  * <b>desired</b> value.
15973  * <p>
15974  * When specified and infinite (
15975  * <tt>Infinity</tt>),
15976  * the layout imposed maximum is used instead.
15977  * 
15978  * <p>
15979  * 
15980  * <b>The minimum tick count</b>
15981  * </p>
15982  * <p>
15983  * This actually depends on the value of {@link #domainRoundMode}.
15984  * 
15985  * <ul>
15986  * 
15987  * <li>
15988  * 
15989  * <p>
15990  * <b>
15991  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Tick}</b></p>
15992  * <p>
15993  * For tick counts greater than two or three, the algorithm strives to satisfy the user's desire!
15994  * <p>
15995  * However,
15996  * the algorithm always generates at least two or three ticks,
15997  * ignoring both 
15998  * <i>desiredTickCount</i> and 
15999  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>,
16000  * if needed.
16001  * <p>
16002  * At least three ticks are generated for numeric domains having both negative and positive data.
16003  * There are also temporal domain cases where a minimum of three ticks are generated.
16004  * <p>
16005  * When the labels of these ticks really overlap,
16006  * one of the labels is kept visible and the other(s) is hidden.
16007  * <p>
16008  * This behavior ensures that, unless it is really impossible to do so,
16009  * the axis serves one of its main purposes - allowing to translate visual lengths.
16010  * <p>
16011  * When three tick labels overlap,
16012  * the middle label is kept visible and the end labels are hidden.
16013  * <p>
16014  * When two tick labels overlap,
16015  * one of the labels
16016  * — the one with tick value 
16017  * <tt>0</tt>, if any, or the first one, if none —
16018  * is kept visible and the other is hidden.
16019  * </li>
16020  * 
16021  * <li>
16022  * 
16023  * <p>
16024  * <b>
16025  * <i>domainRoundMode</i> is
16026  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#None} or
16027  * {@link pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode#Nice}</b></p>
16028  * <p>
16029  * The algorithm always generates at least one tick.
16030  * </li>
16031  * </ul>
16032  * <p>
16033  * Specifying a value of 
16034  * <tt>1</tt> results in the minimum possible tick count.
16035  * 
16036  * <p>
16037  * 
16038  * <b>Domain type specifics</b>
16039  * </p>
16040  * 
16041  * <ul>
16042  * 
16043  * <li>
16044  * 
16045  * <b>Numeric</b>
16046  * <p>
16047  * When unspecified, the default value is 
16048  * <tt>Infinity</tt>.
16049  * </li>
16050  * 
16051  * <li>
16052  * 
16053  * <b>Temporal</b>
16054  * <p>
16055  * The value must be less than or equal to 
16056  * <tt>10</tt>.
16057  * <p>
16058  * When unspecified, the default value is 
16059  * <tt>5</tt>.
16060  * </li>
16061  * </ul>
16062  * <p>
16063  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16064  * 
16065  * @type number
16066  * @category Continuous > Style
16067  */
16068 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.desiredTickCount = undefined;
16069 /**
16070  * Indicates if minor ticks are shown between major ticks (applies to continuous axes).
16071  * 
16072  * @type boolean
16073  * @default true
16074  * @category Continuous > Style
16075  */
16076 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.minorTicks = undefined;
16077 /**
16078  * The ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
16079  * <p>
16080  * When a number, it must be a non-negative, finite, integer.
16081  * 
16082  * <ul>
16083  * 
16084  * <li>
16085  * 
16086  * <b>Numeric axis</b>
16087  * <p>
16088  * Specified values are rounded down to one of the standard precisions:
16089  * a number that is an integer power of 10,
16090  * multiplied by 1, 2 or 5 (e.g. 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, ...).
16091  * </li>
16092  * 
16093  * <li>
16094  * 
16095  * <b>Temporal axis</b>
16096  * <p>
16097  * When a number or numeric string is specified,
16098  * it is a the number of milliseconds of a duration.
16099  * <p>
16100  * It is rounded down to an integer and used directly.
16101  * By default, the corresponding tick format will be the one of the
16102  * greatest standard unit that is below the specified value.
16103  * <p>
16104  * When a (non-numeric) string is specified,
16105  * it should be the code of a standard precision,
16106  * optionally immediately preceded by an integer multiple
16107  * (e.g. 
16108  * <tt>'25d'</tt> means twenty five days).
16109  * <p>
16110  * The standard time precision codes are:
16111  * 
16112  * <ul>
16113  * 
16114  * <li>'y' - Year - 
16115  * <tt>31536e6</tt> ms</li>
16116  * 
16117  * <li>'m' - Month - 
16118  * <tt>2592e6</tt> ms</li>
16119  * 
16120  * <li>'w' - Week - 
16121  * <tt>6048e5</tt> ms</li>
16122  * 
16123  * <li>'d' - Day - 
16124  * <tt>864e5</tt> ms</li>
16125  * 
16126  * <li>'h' - Hour - 
16127  * <tt>36e5</tt> ms</li>
16128  * 
16129  * <li>'M' - Minute - 
16130  * <tt>6e4</tt> ms</li>
16131  * 
16132  * <li>'s' - Second - 
16133  * <tt>1e3</tt> ms</li>
16134  * 
16135  * <li>'ms' - Millisecond - 
16136  * <tt>1</tt> ms</li>
16137  * </ul>
16138  * <p>
16139  * This option should be used instead of the now deprecated
16140  * {@link pvc.options.marks.QuantitativeScaleExtensionPoint#dateTickPrecision}
16141  * extension point, via {@link #extensionPoints} and then 
16142  * <i>scale</i>.
16143  * </li>
16144  * </ul>
16145  * 
16146  * <b>Relations with other options</b>
16147  * <p>
16148  * When both {@link #tickUnitMin} and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
16149  * and the former is greater than or equal to the later,
16150  * then it is as if 
16151  * <i>tickUnit</i> had been specified with the value of 
16152  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>.
16153  * <p>
16154  * When both 
16155  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMin} are specified,
16156  * and 
16157  * <i>tickUnit</i> is less than 
16158  * <i>tickUnitMin</i>,
16159  * then the value of 
16160  * <i>tickUnitMin</i> is used instead.
16161  * <p>
16162  * When both 
16163  * <i>tickUnit</i> and {@link #tickUnitMax} are specified,
16164  * and 
16165  * <i>tickUnit</i> is greater than 
16166  * <i>tickUnitMax</i>,
16167  * then the value of 
16168  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> is used instead.
16169  * <p>
16170  * When specified or implied,
16171  * both {@link #desiredTickCount} and 
16172  * <i>labelSpacingMin</i>
16173  * are ignored.
16174  * <p>
16175  * See related axis options:
16176  * {@link #tickUnitMin},
16177  * {@link #tickUnitMax},
16178  * {@link #domainRoundMode},
16179  * {@link #desiredTickCount} and
16180  * {@link pvc.options.axes.AnyNonHierarchicalCartesianAxis#labelSpacingMin}.
16181  * <p>
16182  * For numeric axes, see also
16183  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin} and
16184  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax}.
16185  * 
16186  * @type number|string
16187  * @category Continuous > Style
16188  */
16189 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnit = undefined;
16190 /**
16191  * The maximum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
16192  * <p>
16193  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by at most a certain value.
16194  * For example,
16195  * a value of 
16196  * <tt>100</tt> ensures that the unit 
16197  * <tt>200</tt> will not be used,
16198  * and of 
16199  * <tt>'3m'</tt> that a year or semester unit will not be used.
16200  * <p>
16201  * As another example,
16202  * to ensure that the tick unit is less than 
16203  * <tt>1000</tt>,
16204  * either
16205  * specify a 
16206  * <i>tickUnitMax</i> of 
16207  * <tt>900</tt>, or, maybe better,
16208  * specify a {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax} of 
16209  * <tt>2</tt>.
16210  * <p>
16211  * When a number, it must be a positive integer.
16212  * <p>
16213  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option.
16214  * <p>
16215  * For numeric axes,
16216  * the value of this option is combined with that of
16217  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMax},
16218  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16219  * <p>
16220  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16221  * 
16222  * @type number|string
16223  * @default Infinity
16224  * @category Continuous > Style
16225  */
16226 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMax = undefined;
16227 /**
16228  * The minimum ticks' major unit (difference in domain value between consecutive ticks).
16229  * <p>
16230  * Use this option to ensure that ticks are separated by a minimum value.
16231  * For example, a value of 
16232  * <tt>1</tt> ensures ticks are integers,
16233  * and of 
16234  * <tt>'d'</tt>, that hour ticks are not used.
16235  * <p>
16236  * When a number, it must be a non-negative finite integer.
16237  * <p>
16238  * The same value parsing rules of {@link #tickUnit} apply to this option,
16239  * with the exception that rounding to a standard precision is performed 
16240  * <i>up</i>.
16241  * <p>
16242  * For numeric axes,
16243  * the value of this option is combined with that of
16244  * {@link pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis#tickExponentMin},
16245  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16246  * <p>
16247  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16248  * 
16249  * @type number|string
16250  * @default 0
16251  * @category Continuous > Style
16252  */
16253 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickUnitMin = undefined;
16254 /**
16255  * The axis' domain rounding mode (applies to continuous axes).
16256  * 
16257  * @type pvc.options.varia.AxisDomainRoundingMode
16258  * @default 'tick'
16259  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16260  */
16261 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.domainRoundMode = undefined;
16262 /**
16263  * The maximum exponent of 
16264  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
16265  * <p>
16266  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
16267  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16268  * <p>
16269  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
16270  * <i>step</i> value.
16271  * A step value is a certain power of 
16272  * <tt>10</tt>,
16273  * possibly multiplied by 
16274  * <tt>2</tt> or 
16275  * <tt>5</tt>.
16276  * <p>
16277  * For example, 
16278  * for a chosen exponent of 
16279  * <tt>4</tt>,
16280  * the corresponding power of 
16281  * <tt>10</tt> is 
16282  * <tt>10^4=10000</tt> and
16283  * the generated ticks could be:
16284  * 
16285  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16286  * <tt>10000</tt>, 
16287  * <tt>20000</tt>, ...
16288  * <p>
16289  * If the multiplier 
16290  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
16291  * those ticks would instead be:
16292  * 
16293  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16294  * <tt>50000</tt>, 
16295  * <tt>100000</tt>, ...
16296  * <p>
16297  * Setting this property allows imposing a limit on 
16298  * the size of numbers chosen to separate ticks,
16299  * which may be seen as imposing a minimum granularity 
16300  * on the generated tick values.
16301  * <p>
16302  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16303  * 
16304  * @type number
16305  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16306  */
16307 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMax = undefined;
16308 /**
16309  * The minimum exponent of 
16310  * <tt>10</tt> that is used to generate ticks (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
16311  * <p>
16312  * The value of this option is combined with that of {@link #tickUnitMax},
16313  * resulting in the most restrictive one being used.
16314  * <p>
16315  * The generated ticks are separated by a 
16316  * <i>step</i> value.
16317  * A step value is a certain power of 
16318  * <tt>10</tt>,
16319  * possibly multiplied by 
16320  * <tt>2</tt> or 
16321  * <tt>5</tt>.
16322  * <p>
16323  * For example, 
16324  * for a chosen exponent of 
16325  * <tt>2</tt>,
16326  * the corresponding power of 
16327  * <tt>10</tt> is 
16328  * <tt>10^2=100</tt> and
16329  * the generated ticks could be:
16330  * 
16331  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16332  * <tt>100</tt>, 
16333  * <tt>200</tt>, ...
16334  * <p>
16335  * If the multiplier 
16336  * <tt>2</tt> was chosen, 
16337  * those ticks would instead be:
16338  * 
16339  * <tt>0</tt>, 
16340  * <tt>200</tt>, 
16341  * <tt>400</tt>, ...
16342  * <p>
16343  * Setting this property to 
16344  * <tt>2</tt> would ensure 
16345  * that generated ticks would be separated by the step values
16346  * 
16347  * <tt>100</tt>, 
16348  * <tt>200</tt> or 
16349  * <tt>500</tt>,
16350  * or by steps whose corresponding exponent is 
16351  * bigger than 
16352  * <tt>2</tt>, 
16353  * like: 
16354  * <tt>1000</tt>, 
16355  * <tt>2000</tt> or 
16356  * <tt>5000</tt>.
16357  * <p>
16358  * A more typical use case is ensuring that generated ticks are integers.
16359  * A value of 
16360  * <tt>tickExponentMin</tt> of 
16361  * <tt>0</tt> would accomplish that.
16362  * <p>
16363  * Generally, 
16364  * to impose a maximum number of decimal places on the generated ticks, 
16365  * a negative number can be specified.
16366  * For example, the value 
16367  * <tt>-1</tt> could generate the ticks:
16368  * 
16369  * <tt>0.1</tt>, 
16370  * <tt>0.2</tt>, 
16371  * <tt>0.3</tt>, ...
16372  * If the multiplier 
16373  * <tt>5</tt> was chosen, 
16374  * those ticks would instead be:
16375  * 
16376  * <tt>0.5</tt>, 
16377  * <tt>1.0</tt>, 
16378  * <tt>1.5</tt>, ...
16379  * It could not generate ticks 
16380  * with more that one decimal place.
16381  * <p>
16382  * See {@link #tickUnit} for more information.
16383  * 
16384  * @type number
16385  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16386  */
16387 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.tickExponentMin = undefined;
16388 /**
16389  * Indicates if the zero line rule is drawn, 
16390  * on the position of the 0-valued tick, 
16391  * when there is one (applies to continuous-numeric axes).
16392  * <p>
16393  * An horizontal axis has a vertical zero line rule,
16394  * while a a vertical axis has an horizontal zero line rule.
16395  * 
16396  * @type boolean
16397  * @default true
16398  * @category Continuous-Numeric > Style
16399  */
16400 pvc.options.axes.NumericCartesianAxis.prototype.zeroLine = undefined;

16638 /**

16641  * <p>

16648  * (i.e. the available size with margins and paddings discounted).

16666 /**
16667  * The fixed size of legend items, in pixel units or as a percentage.
16668  * 
16669  * <p>
16670  * The size includes {@link #itemPadding}.
16671  * The items' client size is the size discounted of the item padding.
16672  * </p>
16673  * 
16674  * <p>
16675  * Percentage values are in relation to the legend panel's available client size 
16676  * (i.e. the available size with margins and paddings discounted).
16677  * </p>
16678  * 
16679  * <p>
16680  * When unspecified, each item assumes the smallest possible size that fits all content.
16681  * You can specify only the item's width or height.
16682  * </p>
16683  * 
16684  * <p>
16685  * The default item height is the biggest of the font height and the {@link #markerSize}.
16686  * The default item width is 
16687  * the {@link #markerSize}, 
16688  * plus the {@link #textMargin}, 
16689  * plus the width of the item's text at the current font.
16690  * </p>
16691  * 
16692  * <p>
16693  * See {@link pvc.options.varia.Size} for information about 
16694  * the different supported data types.

17016 /**
17017  * The options documentation class for 
17018  * specifying trending options for a plot.
17019  * <p>
17020  * Each trend type may define additional options.
17021  * Specifying additional options requires using object notation
17022  * for the trend option, like in the following example:
17023  * 
17024  * <pre>
17025  *             var chartOptions = {
17026  *                 trend: {
17027  *                     type:    'moving-average',
17028  *                     label:   'My Trend',
17029  *                     periods: 4 // additional option of the 'moving-average' trend type
17030  *                 }
17031  *             };
17032  *             
17033  * </pre>
17034  * Trending is performed after null-interpolation,
17035  * so that it takes the null-interpolated datums into account. 
17036  * 
17037  * @class
17038  */
17039 pvc.options.varia.PlotTrending = function(){};
17040         
17041         
17042         
17043         
17044 /**
17045  * A description to show next to the trended data.
17046  * <p>
17047  * The description shows next to legend items and 
17048  * in auto-generated tooltips.
17049  * <p>
17050  * The default value is the description of the associated trend type.  
17051  * 
17052  * @type string
17053  */
17054 pvc.options.varia.PlotTrending.prototype.label = undefined;
17055 /**
17056  * The type of trend to perform on the data of the associated plot.
17057  * <p>
17058  * The specified trend type must have been 
17059  * previously defined in the CCC library, 
17060  * through the 
17061  * <tt>pvc.trends.define</tt> method.
17062  * <p>
17063  * Some trend types come with the CCC library. 
17064  * Currently these are:
17065  * 
17066  * <dl>
17067  * 
17068  * <dt>'linear'</dt>
17069  * 
17070  * <dd>
17071  * performs a 
17072  * <bb>simple linear regression</bb>
17073  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_linear_regression})
17074  * </dd>
17075  * 
17076  * <dt>'moving-average'</dt>
17077  * 
17078  * <dd>
17079  * performs a simple moving average
17080  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average});
17081  * the additional option 
17082  * <tt>periods</tt>, which defaults to 
17083  * <tt>3</tt>, and must not be less than 
17084  * <tt>2</tt>, 
17085  * may be specified to control the number of data points of the average window.
17086  * </dd>
17087  * 
17088  * <dt>'weighted-moving-average'</dt>
17089  * 
17090  * <dd>
17091  * performs a weighted moving average
17092  * (see {@link http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average});
17093  * the additional option 
17094  * <tt>periods</tt>, which defaults to 
17095  * <tt>3</tt>, and must not be less than 
17096  * <tt>2</tt>, 
17097  * may be specified to control the number of data points of the average window.
17098  * </dd>
17099  * </dl> 
17100  * 
17101  * @type string
17102  */
17103 pvc.options.varia.PlotTrending.prototype.type = undefined;

17265 pvc.options.format = {};

17267 /**
17268  * The options documentation of the format provider class.
17269  * <p>
17270  * A format provider contains formats for main value types and main modes in which these are formatted.
17271  * Currently, it contains the following formats:
17272  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} ,
17273  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#percent},
17274  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#date} and
17275  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#any}.
17276  * 
17277  * <p>
17278  * Format providers exist in, and can be configured at,
17279  * three levels, from most specific to least specific:
17280  * </p>
17281  * 
17282  * <dl>
17283  * 
17284  * <dt>
17285  * <b>Dimension Type</b></dt>
17286  * 
17287  * <dd>
17288  * Most formatting operations use a dimension type's format provider to obtain a format.
17289  * <p>
17290  * By default, the unconfigured properties of a dimension type's format provider
17291  * inherit the corresponding value obtained from the chart's format provider.
17292  * <p>
17293  * A dimension type's format provider is configured through
17294  * the option {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#format}.
17295  * </dd>
17296  * 
17297  * <dt>
17298  * <b>Chart</b></dt>
17299  * 
17300  * <dd>
17301  * The chart's format provides defaults for all formatting operations done in the chart.
17302  * <p>
17303  * The unconfigured properties of a chart's format provider
17304  * inherit the corresponding value obtained from the global format provider
17305  * (any format provider directly or indirectly inherits from the global format provider).
17306  * <p>
17307  * A chart's format provider is configured
17308  * through the option {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#format}.
17309  * </dd>
17310  * 
17311  * <dt>
17312  * <b>Global</b></dt>
17313  * 
17314  * <dd>
17315  * Allows changing the default formats used by all charts.
17316  * <p>
17317  * The global format provider exists in 
17318  * <tt>pvc.data.format.defaults</tt>.
17319  * And can also be accessed by its alias 
17320  * <tt>cdo.format.defaults</tt>.
17321  * 
17322  * <p>
17323  * Using the auxiliary method 
17324  * <tt>def.configure</tt>,
17325  * global defaults can be configured the following way:
17326  * 
17327  * <pre>
17328  * def.configure(pvc.data.format.defaults, {
17329  *     number: {
17330  *         mask: "#,0.00",
17331  *         style: {
17332  *             decimal: ",",
17333  *             group: "."
17334  *         }
17335  *     },
17336  *     date: "%m %Y"
17337  * });
17338  *                         
17339  * </pre>
17340  * 
17341  * <p>
17342  * 
17343  * <p>
17344  * Configuring global defaults can also be done
17345  * by using the format provider and contained objects' accessor methods
17346  * (which follow a similar structure to that of the here documented options):
17347  * 
17348  * <pre>
17349  * pvc.data.format.defaults
17350  *     .number().mask("#,0.00");
17351  * 
17352  * pvc.data.format.defaults
17353  *     .style()
17354  *         .decimal(",")
17355  *         .group(".");
17356  * 
17357  * pvc.data.format.defaults
17358  *     .date("%m %Y");
17359  *                         
17360  * </pre>
17361  * 
17362  * <p>
17363  * </dd>
17364  * </dl>
17365  * 
17366  * <h2>
17367  * Internationalization
17368  * </h2>
17369  * 
17370  * <p>
17371  * Get, set, create and configure different format providers arranged by language.
17372  * <p>
17373  * The default language is 
17374  * <i>en-us</i> but can also be accessed with an empty string.
17375  * It's configuration is the same as the global defaults in cdo.
17376  * </p>
17377  * 
17378  * <p>
17379  * 
17380  * <b>Warning:</b> If you change cdo global defaults, the configuration for the default
17381  * language 
17382  * <i>en-us</i> will also change, so changing them is not recommended.
17383  * </p>
17384  * 
17385  * <dl>
17386  * 
17387  * <dt>Create or configure a format provider by specifying a language and the configuration object</dt>
17388  * 
17389  * <dd>
17390  * 
17391  * <p>
17392  * 
17393  * <pre>
17394  * cdo.format.language('fr-fr', {
17395  *     number: {
17396  *         mask:              '#,0.##',
17397  *         style: {
17398  *             integerPad:    '0',
17399  *             fractionPad:   '0',
17400  *             decimal:       ',',
17401  *             group:         ' ',
17402  *             groupSizes:    [3],
17403  *             abbreviations: ['k','m', 'b', 't'],
17404  *             negativeSign:  '-',
17405  *             currency:      '€'
17406  *         }
17407  *     },
17408  *     date: {
17409  *         mask:              '%d/%m/%Y'
17410  *     }
17411  * });
17412  *                         
17413  * </pre>
17414  * 
17415  * <p>
17416  * </dd>
17417  * 
17418  * <dt>Create or configure multiple format providers</dt>
17419  * 
17420  * <dd>
17421  * 
17422  * <p>
17423  * 
17424  * <pre>
17425  * cdo.format.language({
17426  *     'en-us': {
17427  *         number: {
17428  *             mask:              '0,0 Currency',
17429  *         },
17430  *         date: '%Y/%m/%d'
17431  *     },
17432  *     'en-gb': {
17433  *         number: {
17434  *             mask:              '0.00 Abbreviation',
17435  *             style: {
17436  *                 abbreviations: ['k','m', 'b', 't']
17437  *             }
17438  *     }
17439  * });
17440  *                         
17441  * </pre>
17442  * 
17443  * <p>
17444  * </dd>
17445  * 
17446  * <dt>Get the format provider of a specific language</dt>
17447  * 
17448  * <dd>
17449  * 
17450  * <p>
17451  * 
17452  * <pre>
17453  * cdo.format.language('pt-pt');
17454  *                         
17455  * </pre>
17456  * 
17457  * <p>
17458  * </dd>
17459  * </dl>
17460  * 
17461  * @class
17462  */
17463 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider = function(){};

17518 /**
17519  * The format function/object used to format numbers in a general way.
17520  * <p>
17521  * When a string is specified,
17522  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat#mask} property of
17523  * a new number format that replaces the current format.

17530  * <i>current</i> format object.
17531  * <p>
17532  * Alternatively, direct instances of
17533  * {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat} and {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
17534  * can be specified, replacing the existing format.
17535  * <p>
17536  * The global default of the number format mask is 
17537  * <tt>"#,0.##"</tt> —

17549 /**
17550  * The format function/object used to format percentage numbers.
17551  * <p>
17552  * The formatting function should multiply the numeric value by 100.
17553  * <p>
17554  * This function is used whenever a chart needs to show percentages,
17555  * like in the tooltips of a stacked chart or the percentages shown in a Pie chart.
17556  * <p>
17557  * When a string is specified,
17558  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat#mask} property of
17559  * a new number format that replaces the current format.
17560  * <p>
17561  * When a function is specified,
17562  * it is the {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat#formatter} property
17563  * of a new custom format that replaces the current format.
17564  * <p>
17565  * When an object is specified, it configures the 
17566  * <i>current</i> format object.
17567  * <p>
17568  * Alternatively, direct instances of
17569  * {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat} and {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
17570  * can be specified, replacing the existing format.
17571  * <p>
17572  * The global default percent mask is 
17573  * <tt>"#,0.#%"</tt> —
17574  * numbers are first multiplied by 100 and then
17575  * rounded to one decimal place.
17576  * Then, they are formatted
17577  * with a thousands group separator,
17578  * with only significant decimal places,
17579  * and by appending a "%" character.
17580  * <p>
17581  * See the {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormatStyle}
17582  * for information on the global default number styles.
17583  * <p>
17584  * See also related information in {@link pvc.options.charts.Chart#percentValueFormat}.
17585  * 
17586  * @type string|function|object|pvc.options.format.NumberFormat|pvc.options.format.CustomFormat
17587  */
17588 pvc.options.format.FormatProvider.prototype.percent = undefined;

17799 /**
17800  * The options documentation class of a data dimensions reader.
17801  * <p>
17802  * A dimensions reader is executed for each row of a
17803  * data source to convert values of one or more columns
17804  * into one or more atoms of certain dimensions.
17805  * <p>
17806  * Together, a set of dimensions readers,
17807  * are executed to fully convert
17808  * each data source row into atoms of the defined dimension types.
17809  * The atoms of each row are used to construct a datum.
17810  * <p>
17811  * The mentioned data source row is called the 
17812  * <i>logical row</i>.
17813  * Depending on the data source format (crosstab or relational),
17814  * the actual rows carry different informaton.
17815  * The 
17816  * <i>logical row</i> is a normalized view of each row of the data source,
17817  * independent of its format.
17818  * <p>
17819  * A dimensions reader can be configured in the following ways:
17820  * 
17821  * <dl>
17822  * 
17823  * <dt>specify 
17824  * <tt>names</tt> but not 
17825  * <tt>reader</tt></dt>
17826  * 
17827  * <dd>
17828  * names are paired with any specified indexes, from left to right;
17829  * excess indexes feed dimensions whose name starts with the last specified name (a dimension group);
17830  * excess names are fed with the 
17831  * <i>non reserved</i>indexes
17832  * that follow the last specified index (or 0, if none);
17833  * indexes explicitly specified in dimensions readers are all
17834  * reserved beforehand
17835  * </dd>
17836  * 
17837  * <dt>specify 
17838  * <tt>indexes</tt> but not 
17839  * <tt>names</tt> and 
17840  * <tt>reader</tt></dt>
17841  * 
17842  * <dd>
17843  * the specified indexes become reserved but are not read,
17844  * and so are effectively ignored
17845  * </dd>
17846  * 
17847  * <dt>specify both 
17848  * <tt>reader</tt> and 
17849  * <tt>names</tt></dt>
17850  * 
17851  * <dd>
17852  * any specified indexes are reserved,
17853  * and no pairing is performed between these and the specified names;
17854  * the reader function may
17855  * read any column from the 
17856  * <i>logical row</i> and
17857  * return atoms from any of the dimensions specified in 
17858  * <tt>names</tt>;
17859  * atoms of stated dimensions, that are not returned,
17860  * result in a 
17861  * <i>null</i> value;
17862  * this form allows, for example,
17863  * splitting a value in the 
17864  * <i>logical row</i> into two dimensions.
17865  * </dd>
17866  * </dl>
17867  * 
17868  * @class
17869  */
17870 pvc.options.DimensionsReader = function(){};
17871         
17872         
17873         
17874         
17875 /**
17876  * The index or indexes of the columns that the reader reads
17877  * from each 
17878  * <i>logical row</i>.
17879  * <p>
17880  * Only one dimensions reader can state that it reads a given index
17881  * (although a dimensions reader function may sneek into any columns it likes).
17882  * 
17883  * @type number|string|list(number|string)
17884  * @category General
17885  */
17886 pvc.options.DimensionsReader.prototype.indexes = undefined;
17887 /**
17888  * The name or names of the dimensions that the reader reads
17889  * from each 
17890  * <i>logical row</i>.
17891  * <p>
17892  * When the argument is a string, it can be a list of names,
17893  * separated by the character ",".
17894  * <p>
17895  * Only one dimensions reader or dimensions calculation can
17896  * read or calculate a given dimension.
17897  * 
17898  * @type string|list(string)
17899  * @category General
17900  */
17901 pvc.options.DimensionsReader.prototype.names = undefined;
17902 /**
17903  * A dimensions reader function,
17904  * reads the values of dimensions,
17905  * for each 
17906  * <i>logical row</i>.
17907  * <p>
17908  * When unspecified,
17909  * one is created that performs a simple
17910  * mapping between the specified names and indexes.
17911  * <p>
17912  * A dimensions reader function can be specified
17913  * to perform non-simple operations over the read columnss,
17914  * like the following:
17915  * 
17916  * <ul>
17917  * 
17918  * <li>
17919  * combine values from two or more columns into a single dimension,
17920  * </li>
17921  * 
17922  * <li>
17923  * split the value of one column into more than one dimension,
17924  * </li>
17925  * 
17926  * <li>
17927  * feed a dimension with correlated data read from an external data source.
17928  * </li>
17929  * </ul>
17930  * <p>
17931  * Dimensions reader functions need not be specifed to perform
17932  * conversion or formatting operations of a single column.
17933  * For those cases, the dimension type's
17934  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#converter}
17935  * and
17936  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#formatter}
17937  * are more appropriate.
17938  * <p>
17939  * Also, when the value of a dimension
17940  * is calculated from the value of other dimensions,
17941  * a dimensions calculation may be more appropriate:
17942  * see {@link pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation}.
17943  * <p>
17944  * The function may read columns whose indexes were not
17945  * "reserved" in 
17946  * <tt>indexes</tt>.
17947  * Those columns might be read by other readers,
17948  * possibly default ones created by the translator.
17949  * 
17950  * @returns {undefined}
17951  * @method
17952  * @this pvc.data.Data
17953  * @param {list(any)} logicalRow
17954  * The 
17955  * <i>logical row</i> array.
17956  * 
17957  * @param {object} outAtoms
17958  * An object that should be filled with read raw values,
17959  * each placed in a property with the name
17960  * of the corresponding dimension.
17961  * <p>
17962  * It is also possible that the values be the atoms themselves,
17963  * a technique that can be used to achieve greater performance,
17964  * when a dimension only has two or three possible values.
17965  * 
17966  * @category General
17967  */
17968 pvc.options.DimensionsReader.prototype.reader = function(){};
17969 /**
17970  * A dimensions calculation allows the values of a dimension
17971  * to be calculated from the typed values of
17972  * the other non-calculated dimensions.
17973  * <p>
17974  * While a dimensions reader could achieve the same result,
17975  * it works by reading values from the 
17976  * <i>logical table</i>,
17977  * accessing it by index.
17978  * That would require the knowledge of the indexes
17979  * in which the desired dimensions were,
17980  * which is many times not true,
17981  * specially when the mapping between
17982  * dimensions and 
17983  * <i>logical table</i> indexes is determined automatically
17984  * by the data translator.
17985  * 
17986  * @class
17987  */
17988 pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation = function(){};
17989         
17990         
17991         
17992         
17993 /**
17994  * A dimensions calculation function.
17995  * 
17996  * @returns {undefined}
17997  * @method
17998  * @this null
17999  * @param {pvc.data.Complex} datum
18000  * The complex (Datum or Data) instance 
18001  * whose dimensions are being calculated.
18002  * 
18003  * @param {object} outAtoms
18004  * An object that should be filled with read raw or typed values, 
18005  * each placed in a property with the name
18006  * of the corresponding dimension.
18007  * <p>
18008  * It is also possible that the values be the atoms themselves, 
18009  * a technique that can be used to achieve greater performance,
18010  * when a dimension only has two or three possible values. 
18011  * 
18012  * @category General
18013  */
18014 pvc.options.DimensionsCalculation.prototype.calculation = function(){};

18039 /**
18040  * A function that compares two different and non-null values of the dimension's
18041  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}.
18042  * <p>
18043  * When unspecified,
18044  * a default natural order comparer function
18045  * is applied to the continuous value types:
18046  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Number} and
18047  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date}.
18048  * <p>
18049  * Dimension types that do not have a comparer
18050  * function "compare" their values by "input order"
18051  * - order of first appearance, in the data source.
18052  * 
18053  * @returns {number}
18054  * The number 0 if the two values have the same order, 
18055  * a negative number if 
18056  * <tt>a</tt> is before 
18057  * <tt>b</tt>, and
18058  * a positive number if 
18059  * <tt>a</tt> is after 
18060  * <tt>b</tt>.
18061  * 
18062  * @method
18063  * @this null
18064  * @param {any} a
18065  * The first value to compare.
18066  * 
18067  * @param {any} b
18068  * The second value to compare.
18069  * 
18070  * @category Data
18071  */
18072 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.comparer = function(){};
18073 /**
18074  * Converts a non-null raw value,
18075  * as read from the data source,
18076  * into a value of the dimension's {@link #valueType}.
18077  * <p>
18078  * The returned value
18079  * need not have the type of the dimension's value type.
18080  * Yet,
18081  * it must be such that
18082  * the associated value type's cast function can
18083  * convert it to the dimension's value type.
18084  * In this way,
18085  * only "non-standard" conversions
18086  * need to be handled with a converter function.
18087  * <p>
18088  * Values that are not convertible by the dimension's value type
18089  * cast function become null.
18090  * <p>
18091  * Also, note that the only value type that
18092  * does not have a cast function is the
18093  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Any}.
18094  * <p>
18095  * When unspecified and
18096  * the value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date},
18097  * and the option {@link #rawFormat} is specified
18098  * a default converter is created for it.
18099  * 
18100  * @returns {any}
18101  * The converted value.
18102  * 
18103  * @method
18104  * @this null
18105  * @param {any} sourceValue
18106  * The non-null source value to convert.
18107  * <p>
18108  * In the case where the raw value to convert is 
18109  * a Google-table-like cell, 
18110  * it is the value of its 
18111  * <tt>v</tt>
18112  * property that is passed to this argument.
18113  * 
18114  * @category Data
18115  */
18116 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.converter = function(){};
18117 /**
18118  * Indicates if a dimension type should be considered discrete
18119  * or continuous.
18120  * <p>
18121  * Only dimension types whose {@link #valueType}
18122  * is one of
18123  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Number} or
18124  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date}
18125  * can be continuous.
18126  * <p>
18127  * Some chart types support binding
18128  * a continuous or a discrete dimension to a visual role,
18129  * yielding different visual results.
18130  * An example is the "color" visual role of the Metric Line/Dot charts.
18131  * Another example is the Line/Dot/Area chart that supports
18132  * both a continuous or a discrete dimension in its "category" visual role.
18133  * <p>
18134  * The default value dependends on the value of {@link #valueType}.
18135  * If it can be continuous, then the default value is 
18136  * <tt>false</tt>.
18137  * If it cannot, the default value is 
18138  * <tt>true</tt>.
18139  * 
18140  * @type boolean
18141  * @category Data
18142  */
18143 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.isDiscrete = undefined;
18144 /**
18145  * A function that converts a non-null value of the dimension's
18146  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}
18147  * into a string that (uniquely) identifies
18148  * the value in the dimension.
18149  * <p>
18150  * The default key function is
18151  * the standard JavaScript 
18152  * <tt>String</tt> function,
18153  * and is suitable for most value types.
18154  * <p>
18155  * If the dimension's value type is one of
18156  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Any} or
18157  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Object}
18158  * the 
18159  * <tt>String</tt> function may not be suitable to
18160  * identify the values.
18161  * <p>
18162  * If more than one value has a given key,
18163  * only the first one will be stored in the dimension.
18164  * 
18165  * @returns {string}
18166  * The corresponding key.
18167  * 
18168  * @method
18169  * @this null
18170  * @param {any} value
18171  * The non-null value to convert.
18172  * 
18173  * @category Data
18174  */
18175 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.key = function(){};
18176 /**

18180  * option {@link #converter} is unspecified
18181  * and the value type is
18182  * {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date}.
18183  * <p>
18184  * When the chart option

18207 /**
18208  * The dimension type's format provider.
18209  * <p>
18210  * When the option {@link #formatter} is specified, this one is ignored.
18211  * <p>
18212  * When a string, it is the mask of the
18213  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} or
18214  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#date} formats,
18215  * depending on the dimension's the dimension's
18216  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType},
18217  * of a new format provider that replaces the current one.
18218  * <p>
18219  * When a function, it is the formatter of the
18220  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#number} or
18221  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider#date} custom formats,
18222  * depending on the dimension's the dimension's
18223  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType},
18224  * of a new format provider that replaces the current one.
18225  * Note that specifying a function to this property is equivalent to specifying
18226  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#formatter}.
18227  * <p>
18228  * When an object is specified,
18229  * it configures the 
18230  * <i>current</i> format object.
18231  * <p>
18232  * Alternatively,
18233  * a direct instance of
18234  * {@link pvc.options.format.FormatProvider},
18235  * can be specified, replacing the existing format provider.
18236  * Instead, specifying
18237  * {@link pvc.options.format.NumberFormat},
18238  * {@link pvc.options.format.DateFormat},
18239  * or {@link pvc.options.format.CustomFormat}
18240  * configures the existing format provider.
18241  * <p>
18242  * A protovis format string that is to format a value of
18243  * the dimension's
18244  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}.
18245  * <p>
18246  * When unspecified,
18247  * and the dimension type's value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date},
18248  * and the property {@link #rawFormat} is specified,
18249  * a format string is derived from the later by replacing the "-" character with a "/" character.
18250  * <p>
18251  * Otherwise, the dimension type's format provider inherits its
18252  * property values from the chart's format provider.
18253  * 
18254  * @type string|function|object|pvc.options.format.FormatProvider
18255  * @category Presentation
18256  */
18257 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.format = undefined;
18258 /**
18259  * A function that formats a value,
18260  * possibly null,
18261  * of the dimension's
18262  * {@link pvc.options.DimensionType#valueType}.
18263  * <p>
18264  * Note that, the chart option
18265  * {@link pvc.options.charts.BasicChart#valueFormat},
18266  * is used to build a default formatter function
18267  * for numeric dimensions of the "value" dimension group.
18268  * <p>
18269  * When unspecified and
18270  * the value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Number},
18271  * a default formatter is created that formats numbers with two decimal places.
18272  * <p>
18273  * When unspecified and
18274  * the value type is {@link pvc.options.varia.DimensionValueType#Date},
18275  * and the option {@link #format} is specified (or implied)
18276  * a default formatter is created for it.
18277  * <p>
18278  * Otherwise a value is formatted by calling
18279  * the standard JavaScript 
18280  * <tt>String</tt> function on it.
18281  * 
18282  * @returns {string}
18283  * The string that is the formatted value.
18284  * Only the 
18285  * <tt>null</tt> value 
18286  * <i>should</i> have the empty string
18287  * as the formatted value.
18288  * 
18289  * @method
18290  * @this null
18291  * @param {any} value
18292  * The value to format.
18293  * 
18294  * @param {any} [sourceValue]
18295  * The source (or raw) value,
18296  * when the value was read from a data source,
18297  * or 
18298  * <tt>undefined</tt>, otherwise.
18299  * <p>
18300  * In the case where the raw value is 
18301  * a Google-table-like cell, 
18302  * it is the value of its 
18303  * <i>v</i>
18304  * property that is passed to this argument.
18305  * 
18306  * @category Presentation
18307  */
18308 pvc.options.DimensionType.prototype.formatter = function(){};
18309 /**

18316  * 
18317  * <li>hold extra data, required for drill-down purposes</li>
18318  * 
18319  * <li>

18321  * like, for example,
18322  * a "series" dimension created automatically by a chart if
18323  * its required "series" visual role was not unbound
18324  * </li>

19160 /**
19161  * The gravity of the tooltip controls 
19162  * where the tooltip is place relative to the
19163  * visual element's anchor point.
19164  * <p>
19165  * The gravity is the 
19166  * tooltip's corner or side
19167  * that is placed at the visual element's anchor point.
19168  * <p>
19169  * Said in yet another way: 
19170  * «Gravity is the direction of the tooltip arrow.
19171  * The arrow points to the target element.»
19172  * 
19173  * <p>
19174  * The following diagram illustrates the
19175  * tooltip arrow anchor points.
19176  * <p>
19177  * When {@link pvc.options.Tooltip#useCorners}
19178  * is 
19179  * <tt>true</tt>,
19180  * the "crossed" gravities are really at
19181  * the tooltip box corners.
19182  * 
19183  * <pre>
19184  *                nw    n    ne
19185  *               +-o----o----o-+
19186  *               |             |
19187  *             w o   Tooltip   o e
19188  *               |             |
19189  *               +-o----o----o-+
19190  *                sw    s    se
19191  *                 
19192  * </pre>
19193  * 
19194  * <p>
19195  * 
19196  * @class
19197  * @enum
19198  * @extends string
19199  */
19200 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity = function(){};
19201         
19202         
19203         
19204 /**
19205  * Right tooltip side is placed at the 
19206  * visual element's anchor point,
19207  * resulting in the tooltip being at its left.
19208  * 
19209  * @value 'e'
19210  */
19211 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.East = 'e';
19212 /**
19213  * Top tooltip side is placed at the 
19214  * visual element's anchor point,
19215  * resulting in the tooltip being below it. 
19216  * 
19217  * @value 'n'
19218  */
19219 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.North = 'n';
19220 /**
19221  * Upper-right tooltip corner is placed at the 
19222  * visual element's anchor point,
19223  * resulting in the tooltip being below it and at its left.
19224  * 
19225  * @value 'ne'
19226  */
19227 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.NorthEast = 'ne';
19228 /**
19229  * Upper-left tooltip corner is placed at the 
19230  * visual element's anchor point,
19231  * resulting in the tooltip being below it and at its right.
19232  * 
19233  * @value 'nw'
19234  */
19235 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.NorthWest = 'nw';
19236 /**
19237  * Bottom tooltip side is placed at the 
19238  * visual element's anchor point,
19239  * resulting in the tooltip being above it.  
19240  * 
19241  * @value 's'
19242  */
19243 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.South = 's';
19244 /**
19245  * Lower-right tooltip corner is placed at the

19251 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.SouthEast = 'se';

19267 pvc.options.varia.TooltipGravity.prototype.West = 'w';

19553  * This type is a documentation type and

19555  * <p>
19556  * Colors can be specified as a string that follows one of the following formats:
19557  * 
19558  * <ul>

19574  * 
19575  * <li>
19576  * 
19577  * <tt>rgb(255, 0, 0)</tt>
19578  * </li>
19579  * 
19580  * <li>
19581  * 
19582  * <tt>rgba(100%, 0, 0, 0.5)</tt>
19583  * </li>
19584  *

19588  * </li>

19621  * 
19622  * <li>

19624  *

19627  * </ul>
19628  * </li>

19631  *

20015 /**
20016  * Describes the distances from
20017  * each of the four sides of a rectangle:
20018  * "left", "right", "top" and "bottom".
20019  * <p>
20020  * It is used to describe the margins and the paddings of panels.
20021  * <p>
20022  * It is possible to specify any combination of the side properties.
20023  * <p>
20024  * All side properties support values in absolute or relative units:
20025  * 
20026  * <dl>
20027  * 
20028  * <dt>absolute</dt>
20029  * 
20030  * <dd>
20031  * if it is a 
20032  * <tt>number</tt> or a numeric 
20033  * <tt>string</tt>,
20034  * the measure is in pixel units
20035  * </dd>
20036  * 
20037  * <dt>relative</dt>
20038  * 
20039  * <dd>
20040  * if it is a numeric 
20041  * <tt>string</tt> with a "%" suffix,
20042  * the measure is a percentage of some reference size;
20043  * usually, the reference size is
20044  * the size of the corresponding container panel side
20045  * ("width" if side is "left" or "right", or "height" otherwise)
20046  * </dd>
20047  * </dl>
20048  * 
20049  * <h3>Special properties</h3>
20050  * 
20051  * <p>The special property, 
20052  * <tt>all</tt>, affects all unspecified properties at once.</p>
20053  * 
20054  * <p>The special property, 
20055  * <tt>width</tt>, is interpreted as if both "left" and "right" had been specified, with half the value.</p>
20056  * 
20057  * <p>The special property, 
20058  * <tt>height</tt>, is interpreted as if both "top" and "bottom" had been specified, with half the value.</p>
20059  * 
20060  * <p>When all, width, or height are specified, they are evaluated in that order, and before normal properties.</p>
20061  * 
20062  * <h3>JSON syntax example</h3>
20063  * 
20064  * <p>
20065  * The following is an example of a 
20066  * <i>sides</i>-structured object,
20067  * the hypothetical margins of a legend panel:
20068  * 
20069  * <pre>
20070  * var legendMargins = {left: 10, right: '20', all: '15%'};
20071  *                 
20072  * </pre>
20073  * It says that
20074  * the left margin has 10 pixels,
20075  * the right margin has 20 pixels, and
20076  * the top and bottom margins have each
20077  * the size of 15 percent of the legend panel's parent client height.
20078  * 
20079  * <p>
20080  * 
20081  * <h3>Single number or numeric string interpretation</h3>
20082  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides}
20083  * allow specifying
20084  * a 
20085  * <tt>number</tt> or
20086  * a 
20087  * <tt>string</tt> of a single number, possibly followed by a "%" sign,
20088  * instead of the JSON form,
20089  * as meaning 
20090  * <i>all</i> properties.
20091  * 
20092  * <h3>String syntax</h3>
20093  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Sides}
20094  * also allow specifying a CSS2-like margins string,
20095  * {@link http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/box.html#propdef-margin}.
20096  * 
20097  * <p>
20098  * The following shows the equivalence between the string and JSON syntax:
20099  * 
20100  * <pre>
20101  * var margins1 = '1';       // {all: '1'}
20102  * var margins2 = '1 2';     // {top: '1', bottom: '1', right: '2', left: '2'}
20103  * var margins3 = '1 2 3';   // {top: '1', bottom: '3', right: '2', left: '2'}
20104  * var margins4 = '1 2 3 4'; // {top: '1', bottom: '3', right: '2', left: '4'}
20105  *                 
20106  * </pre>
20107  * 
20108  * <p>
20109  * 
20110  * @class
20111  */
20112 pvc.options.varia.Sides = function(){};
20113         
20114         
20115         
20116         
20117 /**
20118  * @type number|string
20119  */
20120 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.all = undefined;
20121 /**
20122  * @type number|string
20123  */
20124 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.bottom = undefined;
20125 /**
20126  * @type number|string
20127  */
20128 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.height = undefined;
20129 /**
20130  * @type number|string
20131  */
20132 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.left = undefined;
20133 /**
20134  * @type number|string
20135  */
20136 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.right = undefined;
20137 /**
20138  * @type number|string
20139  */
20140 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.top = undefined;
20141 /**
20142  * @type number|string
20143  */
20144 pvc.options.varia.Sides.prototype.width = undefined;
20145 /**
20146  * Describes the size
20147  * of the horizontal and vertical dimensions
20148  * of an axis aligned box.
20149  * It is used to describe the margins and the paddings of panels.
20150  * <p>
20151  * It is possible to specify any combination of the size properties.
20152  * <p>
20153  * All size properties support values in absolute or relative units:
20154  * 
20155  * <dl>
20156  * 
20157  * <dt>absolute</dt>
20158  * 
20159  * <dd>
20160  * if it is a 
20161  * <tt>number</tt> or a numeric 
20162  * <tt>string</tt>,
20163  * the measure is in pixel units
20164  * </dd>
20165  * 
20166  * <dt>relative</dt>
20167  * 
20168  * <dd>
20169  * if it is a numeric 
20170  * <tt>string</tt> with a "%" suffix,
20171  * the measure is a percentage of some reference size;
20172  * usually,
20173  * the reference size is
20174  * the container panel's corresponding size
20175  * </dd>
20176  * </dl>
20177  * <p>
20178  * The special property, 
20179  * <tt>all</tt>, affects all unspecified properties at once.
20180  * 
20181  * <p>
20182  * The following is an example of a 
20183  * <i>size</i>-structured object,
20184  * the hypothetical size of a title panel:
20185  * 
20186  * <pre>
20187  * var titleSize = {width: '80%', all: 100};
20188  *                 
20189  * </pre>
20190  * It says that
20191  * the height has 100 pixels,
20192  * and that the width is 80 percent of the base panel's width.
20193  * 
20194  * <p>
20195  * 
20196  * <h3>Single number or numeric string interpretation</h3>
20197  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Size}
20198  * allow specifying
20199  * a 
20200  * <tt>number</tt> or
20201  * a 
20202  * <tt>string</tt> of a single number, possibly followed by a "%" sign,
20203  * instead of the JSON form.
20204  * <p>
20205  * The interpretation of what the number or percentage stand
20206  * for depends on the specific option.
20207  * In the legend and title panels, for example,
20208  * it is the size of the dimension orthogonal to the anchored to side.
20209  * So if a legend is anchored to the 
20210  * <tt>'left'</tt> side,
20211  * the number or percentage is the legend's width.
20212  * 
20213  * <h3>String syntax</h3>
20214  * All chart options of type {@link pvc.options.varia.Size}
20215  * also allow specifying a string with a fixed structure.
20216  * 
20217  * <p>
20218  * The following shows the equivalence between the string and JSON syntax:
20219  * 
20220  * <pre>
20221  * var size1 = '1';   // {all: '1'}
20222  * var size2 = '1 2'; // {width: '1', height: '2'}
20223  *                 
20224  * </pre>
20225  * 
20226  * <p>
20227  * 
20228  * @class
20229  */
20230 pvc.options.varia.Size = function(){};
20231

20424 /**
20425  * A list of dimension names and respective
20426  * sort orders.
20427  * <p>
20428  * A dimensions string is similar to an SQL 'order by' clause,
20429  * like the following examples show:
20430  * 
20431  * <dl>
20432  * 
20433  * <dt>
20434  * 
20435  * <tt>"productType"</tt>
20436  * </dt>
20437  * 
20438  * <dd>
20439  * the visual role is bound to the single dimension named 
20440  * <tt>"productType"</tt>,
20441  * and data will be sorted in ascending order
20442  * </dd>
20443  * </dl>
20444  * 
20445  * <dl>
20446  * 
20447  * <dt>
20448  * 
20449  * <tt>"sales"</tt>
20450  * </dt>
20451  * 
20452  * <dd>
20453  * the visual role is bound to the single dimension named 
20454  * <tt>"sales"</tt>,
20455  * and data will be sorted in ascending order
20456  * </dd>
20457  * </dl>
20458  * 
20459  * <dl>
20460  * 
20461  * <dt>
20462  * 
20463  * <tt>"country, productType"</tt>
20464  * </dt>
20465  * 
20466  * <dd>
20467  * the visual role is bound to the dimensions
20468  * named 
20469  * <tt>"country"</tt> and 
20470  * <tt>"productType"</tt>,
20471  * and data will be sorted first by
20472  * 
20473  * <tt>"country"</tt>, in ascending order,
20474  * and then by
20475  * 
20476  * <tt>"productType"</tt>, in ascending order
20477  * </dd>
20478  * </dl>
20479  * 
20480  * <dl>
20481  * 
20482  * <dt>
20483  * 
20484  * <tt>"country desc, productType asc"</tt>
20485  * </dt>
20486  * 
20487  * <dd>
20488  * the visual role is bound to the dimensions
20489  * named 
20490  * <tt>"country"</tt> and 
20491  * <tt>"productType"</tt>,
20492  * and data will be sorted first by
20493  * 
20494  * <tt>"country"</tt>, in descending order,
20495  * and then by
20496  * 
20497  * <tt>"productType"</tt>, in ascending order
20498  * </dd>
20499  * </dl>
20500  * 
20501  * @type string
20502  */
20503 pvc.options.VisualRole.prototype.dimensions = undefined;
20504 /**

20521  * prefix the local name of the visual role with "main.", to obtain, for example, "main.series".
20522  * <p>
20523  * To refer, unambiguously, to a visual role of the

20525  * prefix its local name with "$.", to obtain, for example, "$.multiChart".
20526  *

20528  */
